</node>
<node id="WEEK 5">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">An optional fifth seven-day period within a monthly cash flow budget, if the month extends beyond four full weeks.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TOTAL INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The aggregated sum of all money and benefits received within a specific weekly period.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="OTHER INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A general category for miscellaneous sources of money received that are not explicitly itemized in the budget.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OTHER EXPENSES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A general category for miscellaneous expenditures that are not explicitly itemized in the budget.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Government or other forms of financial aid or support received by individuals, often tied to specific eligibility criteria, mentioned as a resource to cover living expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">18</data>
</node>
<node id="RESOURCES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Various means available to an individual to meet their financial needs and goals, including money, benefits, and other assets, used to cover bills and expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="YOUR MONEY, YOUR GOALS IMPLEMENTATION GUIDE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A resource providing guidance for practitioners on how to effectively use and implement the "Your Money, Your Goals" toolkit, including how to build a referral network.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="BANK STATEMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A periodic summary of financial transactions that should be reviewed for errors and may contain identifying or account information.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A card that allows the holder to borrow money up to an approved credit limit to make purchases, requiring at least a minimum monthly payment and incurring interest if the balance is not paid in full.</data>
  <data key="d2">34</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBIT CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A card linked to a bank account that allows spending money already owned, but can lead to overdraft if opted into a bank's overdraft program, incurring fees and requiring repayment. It's used for purchases without carrying cash.</data>
  <data key="d2">17</data>
</node>
<node id="IDENTIFYING INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Key pieces of data, such as Social Security numbers or mother's maiden names, that can be used to confirm an individual's identity and are targets for theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCOUNT NUMBERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Unique identifiers for financial accounts or credit cards, which should be protected and physically destroyed when no longer needed to prevent identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="SHREDDING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of physically destroying documents with identifying or account information into tiny pieces to prevent others from accessing sensitive data.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SOCIAL SECURITY NUMBER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A Social Security Number is a unique nine-digit numerical identifier issued to U.S. citizens and residents, primarily used for tracking earnings and benefits, but also commonly used for identification.</data>
  <data key="d2">20</data>
</node>
<node id="MOTHER'S MAIDEN NAME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A personal detail often used by financial institutions for identity verification, which should be protected from online exposure, especially on social media.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="IDENTITY VERIFICATION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of confirming an individual's identity, often used by financial institutions or required by creditors before opening new accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL INSTITUTIONS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">General term for organizations like banks and credit card companies that manage financial accounts and have procedures for security, monitoring, closing, or reopening accounts in response to issues like theft or illegal access.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="SOCIAL MEDIA ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An online platform account where personal information, like a mother's maiden name, should not be posted due to the risk of identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ONLINE SECURITY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Practices and technologies implemented to safeguard personal and financial information when using the internet, including strong passwords and secure websites.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PERSONAL INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Sensitive data (like billing address or credit card information) that financial apps may require users to enter or access from financial accounts with permission. Must be safeguarded.</data>
  <data key="d2">8</data>
</node>
<node id="PASSWORD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A secret string of characters used to authenticate access to electronic systems and accounts (e.g., for electronic banking, bill paying, purchasing), crucial for securing financial activities.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Data related to an individual's financial status or transactions, which should never be given out over unsecured internet connections or public Wi-Fi.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="ENCRYPTION PROGRAM">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Software or a method used to secure data transmitted online, indicating that a website is secure and preventing interception of information.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WEBSITE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A location on the internet where information is provided and exchanged; secure ones start with 'https' and show a lock symbol, crucial for sharing sensitive data.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="HTTPS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A secure communication protocol that indicates a website is encrypted and secure for transmitting data.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOCK SYMBOL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A visual indicator, typically in a web browser's address bar, signifying that a website is secure using an encryption program.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PUBLIC WIFI">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">An unsecured network connection that poses a significant risk to personal and financial information if used for sensitive online activities.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PUBLIC COMPUTER">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A computer accessible to multiple users, posing a risk to personal data if not logged off properly, or if passwords are saved by the browser.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BROWSER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Software used to access the internet; should never be permitted to save passwords on public computers to prevent unauthorized access to accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PHONE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A mobile device that stores sensitive personal information and apps, requiring passcode protection to prevent unauthorized access.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="TABLET">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A mobile device that stores sensitive personal information and apps, requiring passcode protection to prevent unauthorized access.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="APP">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Software applications on mobile devices that may save passwords and log users in automatically, making device passcode protection crucial.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MOBILE DEVICES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">General category for phones and tablets, which store sensitive information and passwords via apps, necessitating strong passcode protection.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PASSCODE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A security code used to protect access to a phone, tablet, or other mobile device, safeguarding sensitive information stored on it.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="IDENTITY THIEF">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual who fraudulently uses another person's identifying information, often attempting to open new credit accounts or misuse existing ones.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SENSITIVE INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Personal data such as names, account numbers, or other details that, if disclosed, could pose a security risk to individuals, and which the Bureau advises against including when using their tools.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="EMAIL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of sending or receiving electronic messages, used as a communication method for customer support, inquiries, or official notifications from financial institutions.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="PERSONAL BANKING INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Confidential details related to an individual's bank accounts, which financial institutions will never request via email.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="IDENTITY THEFT">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial risk involving the misuse of checking accounts, the theft of financial documents, or the loss of debit/credit cards or government-issued identification, where personal information is used without authorization.</data>
  <data key="d2">26</data>
</node>
<node id="FRAUD">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">Deceptive practices or misrepresentations carried out for financial or personal gain, often resulting in harm to another party. It can manifest as inaccuracies on credit reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">18</data>
</node>
<node id="NATIONWIDE CREDIT REPORTING COMPANIES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">These are three companies required to ensure new and existing public record information comes from sources including specific personal data to maintain accuracy, updating every 90 days.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="IDENTITY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The state of being who a person is, which requires proof when ordering credit reports or for identity verification processes.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEDERAL TRADE COMMISSION (FTC)">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A U.S. government agency that assists victims of identity theft by providing recovery plans, pre-filled letters, and an official Identity Theft Report via its website, identitytheft.gov.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="IDENTITYTHEFT.GOV">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">IdentityTheft.gov is a federal government website provided by the Federal Trade Commission, offering resources and a reporting mechanism for victims of identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="PERSONAL RECOVERY PLAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A structured approach created by the Federal Trade Commission to guide victims through the steps necessary to recover from identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MERCHANTS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Businesses or individuals involved in trade or commerce, from whom checking account reporting companies collect data regarding consumer account management.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="BANKS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial institutions that offer a range of services including checking and savings accounts, loans, and investment products. They use identification and banking history reports to make account opening decisions.</data>
  <data key="d2">13</data>
</node>
<node id="IDENTITY THEFT REPORT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An official document issued by the Federal Trade Commission that serves as a statement about the crime of identity theft, often usable in place of a police report.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="POLICE REPORT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An official document issued by the police documenting a crime, sometimes required in identity theft cases, though an FTC Identity Theft Report can often substitute it.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT HISTORY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A record of a borrower's ability to repay debts and demonstrate responsibility in repaying them, reflected in credit reports. A good credit history is crucial for maintaining a strong credit score.</data>
  <data key="d2">21</data>
</node>
<node id="TRANSACTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial dealings or activities, which can be fraudulent due to identity theft and need to be cleared from an individual's credit history.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="POLICE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Law enforcement authorities to whom identity theft should be reported under specific circumstances, such as knowing the perpetrator or when a police report is required.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="TRAFFIC STOP">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">An encounter with police while driving, where an identity thief might fraudulently use another person's name, leading to further complications for the victim.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT PROTECTION TOOL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Mechanisms available from credit reporting companies designed to safeguard against identity theft and fraudulent account openings, including security freezes and fraud alerts.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SECURITY FREEZE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A protective measure that can be requested for minors under 16 ("protected consumers") by authorized persons to prevent unauthorized access to their credit records, thereby safeguarding against identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="INITIAL FRAUD ALERT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A one-year alert on a credit report requiring creditors to verify identity before opening new accounts or increasing credit limits, often used after a data breach.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="EXTENDED FRAUD ALERT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A seven-year alert on a credit report requiring creditors to contact the consumer before approving credit, and removing them from prescreening lists for five years, available if an identity theft report has been filed.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An arrangement with a financial institution that allows an individual to borrow money or access funds, such as a credit card or a loan, thereby contributing to their credit history.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="LOAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial agreement where money is provided to another party in exchange for future repayment of the principal amount plus interest or other finance charges, often used for specific purchases.</data>
  <data key="d2">26</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDITORS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Organizations, such as lenders or credit card companies, that extend credit and are required to verify identity before opening new accounts, issuing additional cards, or increasing credit limits under a fraud alert.</data>
  <data key="d2">9</data>
</node>
<node id="COPYRIGHT PROTECTION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The legal right safeguarding the Emergency Financial First Aid Kit, prohibiting unauthorized commercial use or sale, for which Operation HOPE, Inc. holds the copyright.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A category of property that includes the DHS Visual Identities, which are owned by the Department of Homeland Security.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEDERAL LAW">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A body of laws enacted by the U.S. federal government that provides consumer protections related to financial products, prepaid cards, and money transfers abroad.</data>
  <data key="d2">11</data>
</node>
<node id="CAUSE OF ACTION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal right to seek a remedy from a court, which is explicitly stated not to be conferred against the United States Government by the publication of views in the EFFAK by DHS.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LIABILITY">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The legal responsibility or obligation that users of information in the Emergency Financial First Aid Kit assume from such use.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HOME">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A primary residence or property owned by an individual or family, requiring specific insurance coverage and serving as a location for storing important documents.</data>
  <data key="d2">12</data>
</node>
<node id="U.S. SAVINGS BONDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial product where money cannot be lost or destroyed in a disaster, and funds can be recovered even if the bond is paper. However, cashing it before maturity results in loss of some interest, and it is more difficult to access immediately.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="BANK">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial institution that provides services such as opening checking and savings accounts, offering online banking, and providing ATM access. Banks typically require identification and an initial deposit to open an account.</data>
  <data key="d2">47</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT UNION">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A member-owned financial cooperative that offers financial services, including checking and savings accounts. Like banks, they require identification and an initial deposit for account opening and provide services like online banking and ATMs.</data>
  <data key="d2">38</data>
</node>
<node id="VOLUNTEER INCOME TAX ASSISTANCE (VITA) SITE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A location supported by the IRS where IRS-certified volunteers provide free assistance for preparing and filing tax returns and making plans for refunds.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="IRS-CERTIFIED VOLUNTEERS">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals certified by the IRS who provide free assistance with tax preparation and filing at VITA sites.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="IRS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The Internal Revenue Service, a U.S. government agency responsible for tax collection and tax law enforcement, which certifies volunteers, supports VITA sites, and administers tax credits like EITC and CTC.</data>
  <data key="d2">10</data>
</node>
<node id="PAID PREPARERS">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Professionals who charge fees for preparing taxes and may offer services like refund anticipation checks.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="REFUND ANTICIPATION CHECK">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A service offered by paid tax preparers where tax preparation fees are deducted directly from a tax refund, which is then deposited onto a prepaid card or bank account. This service may incur additional fees and does not provide money faster than direct deposit.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="BANK ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A general term for an account held at a bank or credit union for depositing and withdrawing money, including checking accounts, and can be used for money transfers.</data>
  <data key="d2">22</data>
</node>
<node id="EARNED INCOME TAX CREDIT (EITC)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A tax benefit for working individuals with low-to-moderate income, the amount of which depends on income and filing status and changes annually. The IRS is responsible for its administration and verification, which may cause delays in refunds.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CHILD TAX CREDIT (CTC)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A tax credit that reduces taxes owed by up to $2,000 for each qualifying child under 17, with a refundable portion limited to $1,400. It requires a Social Security number for each child claimed, and the IRS is responsible for its administration and verification, which may cause delays in refunds.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DIRECT DEPOSIT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">An electronic payment method where funds are transferred directly into a bank account, credit union account, or prepaid card account, reducing risks of loss/theft for traditional accounts and offering immediate availability.</data>
  <data key="d2">18</data>
</node>
<node id="TAX RETURN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A document filed with the IRS to report income, deductions, and credits, including necessary information for claiming credits and processing direct deposits of refunds.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="TAX REFUND">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Money returned by the government to a taxpayer who has overpaid taxes, which can be received via direct deposit or check, and used for immediate expenses or savings.</data>
  <data key="d2">13</data>
</node>
<node id="SAVINGS ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial account designed for depositing and accumulating money, earning interest, and typically used for long-term savings rather than frequent transactions. Deposits are usually insured.</data>
  <data key="d2">27</data>
</node>
<node id="SERIES I SAVINGS BOND">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of U.S. savings bond that earns interest from the U.S. government, does not require a bank account, and can be given as a gift. More information is available on TreasuryDirect.gov.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="U.S. GOVERNMENT">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The federal authority responsible for minting U.S. currency, overseeing federal protections, and administering government programs, including those distributing benefits.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="RETIREMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The period of life after a person stops working, often associated with receiving pension or retirement plan benefits which may be protected from garnishment.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="MEDICAL COSTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Expenses related to healthcare treatments and services, which can be significant and are addressed by health insurance and Medicare.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="FAMILY NEEDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial requirements for a household, often considered in long-term financial planning.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INSURANCE POLICIES AND COVERAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Contracts providing financial protection against various risks, requiring regular review and customization.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ANNUAL INSURANCE REVIEWS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The systematic process of examining and updating insurance policies, ideally conducted every year or after significant life changes.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BUSINESS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An entity that may decide an account is uncollectible (charge off), collect debts, provide loans, or furnish information to credit reporting companies.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE FARM AGENT">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">A representative employed by State Farm who assists customers with purchasing, managing, and bundling insurance policies, providing quotes, and explaining available discounts and programs.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE FARM">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">State Farm is a large insurance company that provides various insurance products, including auto, home, renters, motorcycle, life, small business, Medicare Supplement, supplemental health, and pet insurance. It operates through entities such as State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance Company, State Farm Indemnity Company, and State Farm County Mutual Insurance Company of Texas.</data>
  <data key="d2">13</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE FARM MUTUAL AUTOMOBILE INSURANCE COMPANY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A company within the State Farm group that provides various insurance products, including auto insurance, and is implicitly associated with operations in Bloomington, IL.</data>
  <data key="d2">8</data>
</node>
<node id="QUALIFIED PROFESSIONAL">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">A general term for experts, such as accountants or certified financial advisors, whose guidance or advice is recommended by the CFPB as a replacement for its educational materials.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE FARM EDITORS">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals responsible for reviewing articles published by State Farm, including those drafted with AI.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE FARM INDEMNITY COMPANY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A company within the State Farm group that provides various insurance products and is implicitly associated with operations in Bloomington, IL.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE FARM FIRE AND CASUALTY COMPANY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A company within the State Farm group that provides various insurance products, including fire and casualty insurance, and is implicitly associated with operations in Bloomington, IL.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE FARM GENERAL INSURANCE COMPANY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A company within the State Farm group that provides various insurance products and is implicitly associated with operations in Bloomington, IL.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE FARM LIFE INSURANCE COMPANY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A subsidiary of State Farm specializing in life insurance, noted as not being licensed in Massachusetts, New York, or Wisconsin for life insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE FARM LIFE AND ACCIDENT ASSURANCE COMPANY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A company within the State Farm group that provides life and accident assurance and is licensed in New York and Wisconsin.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="BLOOMINGTON">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">The city in Illinois where State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance Company is located.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ILLINOIS">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">A US state where State Farm offers services, and where pricing and coverage options may vary; Bloomington, IL is located here.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE FARM FLORIDA INSURANCE COMPANY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A company within the State Farm group that provides insurance services, specifically located in Tallahassee, FL.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="TALLAHASSEE">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">The capital city of Florida, associated with State Farm Florida Insurance Company.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FLORIDA">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">A U.S. state where Tallahassee is located and where State Farm Florida Insurance Company operates.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE FARM COUNTY MUTUAL INSURANCE COMPANY OF TEXAS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific legal entity within the State Farm group, providing insurance services in Texas, based in Richardson, TX.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE FARM LLOYDS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A company within the State Farm group that provides insurance services, specifically located in Richardson, TX.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="RICHARDSON">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">The city in Texas where State Farm County Mutual Insurance Company of Texas is located.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="TEXAS">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">A U.S. state where Richardson is located and where State Farm County Mutual Insurance Company of Texas and State Farm Lloyds operate.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="START A QUOTE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">An action a customer can take to obtain a price estimate for insurance products from State Farm.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="AUTO INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A comprehensive type of insurance product offered by State Farm that covers damages and injuries related to vehicles, featuring various coverage options like collision, comprehensive, uninsured/underinsured motorist, med pay/personal injury protection, emergency road service, rental reimbursement, and ridesharing.</data>
  <data key="d2">10</data>
</node>
<node id="AUTO + RENTERS INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific bundled product offering that combines auto insurance and renters insurance, listed as an option in State Farm's quote dropdown menu.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="MOTORCYCLE INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Insurance coverage specifically for motorcycles, protecting against risks associated with operating the vehicle.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="HOMEOWNERS INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An insurance policy designed to cover property damage, liability, and living expenses for homeowners in a private residence, crucial for emergency support.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="CONDO OWNERS INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Insurance coverage specifically designed for individuals who own a condominium unit, protecting their unit's interior and personal belongings.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="RENTERS INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An insurance policy designed to protect the personal property of individuals living in rented residences. It is frequently bundled with auto insurance to maximize savings.</data>
  <data key="d2">11</data>
</node>
<node id="SMALL BUSINESS INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Insurance coverage tailored to protect small businesses from various risks, including property damage, liability, and business interruption.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="LIFE INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An insurance policy that provides financial protection for beneficiaries upon the policyholder's death. It can be bundled with auto insurance, particularly for expanding families.</data>
  <data key="d2">10</data>
</node>
<node id="MEDICARE SUPPLEMENT INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Insurance policies that help pay for some of the healthcare costs that Original Medicare does not cover, such as deductibles and copayments.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="SUPPLEMENTAL HEALTH INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Insurance that provides additional coverage to an existing health insurance policy, often covering specific conditions or services not fully covered by primary insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="PET INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Insurance policies designed to help cover the cost of veterinary care for pets due to illness, accidents, or routine check-ups.</data>
  <data key="d2">9</data>
</node>
<node id="FIND AN AGENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">An action a customer can take to locate a State Farm insurance agent for personalized service.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="LIABILITY COVERAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Liability coverage is a component of auto insurance, often legally required, that typically includes bodily injury and property damage liability to pay for expenses for others injured or for repairs to their property in an accident you’re responsible for.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="AUTO INSURANCE DEDUCTIBLE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The amount of money a policyholder must pay out-of-pocket for a covered loss before their auto insurance coverage begins to pay.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MASSACHUSETTS">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">A US state where State Farm offers services; however, discounts are not available here.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="NEW YORK">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">A U.S. state with specific licensing status for State Farm Life Insurance Company (not licensed) and State Farm Life and Accident Assurance Company (licensed).</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="LOSS CONTROL MEASURE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Actions or strategies taken to reduce the potential for losses, related to the information provided by State Farm.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT CARDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Revolving credit products issued by financial institutions that allow cardholders to borrow funds for purchases, covered by the Military Lending Act if opened on or after October 3, 2017, for servicemembers.</data>
  <data key="d2">11</data>
</node>
<node id="LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial product involving borrowed money that must be repaid over time, typically with interest and associated fees; this category includes mortgages and personal loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">8</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYMENT HISTORY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The most influential factor in FICO scores and an "extremely influential" factor for VantageScore, tracking an individual's record of paying bills on time.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="BALANCES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The outstanding amounts owed on credit cards or other accounts, which accrue interest if not paid off.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PRACTICING GOOD HABITS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Engaging in consistent, positive financial behaviors, such as timely payments and responsible credit use, to build and maintain a strong credit history.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MAKE CORRECTIONS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of amending or updating inaccurate information on credit reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TRACK WHEN YOUR BILLS ARE DUE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The activity of monitoring and recording the specific dates by which various financial obligations must be paid.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DECIDE WHEN YOU'LL PAY BILLS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of determining and scheduling the specific dates for making payments towards financial obligations.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ESTABLISH A CREDIT HISTORY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The initial process of creating a record of an individual's borrowing and repayment activities, typically for those with no prior credit.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BUREAU OF CONSUMER FINANCIAL PROTECTION">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A US government agency that provides the "Your Money, Your Goals" toolkit, handles complaints about various financial products and services, and answers questions about money matters. It offers services via toll-free phone (855.411.2372, Monday–Friday 8:00 a.m.–8:00 p.m. EST), TTY/TDD phone (855.729.2372), fax (855.237.2392), and mail at P.O. Box 2900, Clinton, IA 52733-2900.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="FEDERAL CONSUMER FINANCIAL LAWS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The legal framework under which the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau operates to regulate consumer financial activities and ensure consumer protection.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMER FINANCIAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Various financial offerings, such as loans, credit cards, or bank accounts, that are provided to consumers and are subject to regulation by the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="YOUR MONEY, YOUR GOALS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A toolkit or program provided by the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection that offers tools and guidance for consumers to manage their money and debt, including resources like the "Debt Action Plan" and "Student Loan Checklist".</data>
  <data key="d2">9</data>
</node>
<node id="PRIORITIZING DEBT PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">An activity or strategy for deciding which debts to pay first, especially during financially challenging months.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT ACTION PLAN">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A strategic plan created to guide individuals in reducing and repaying their debt by choosing a suitable repayment method and listing debts in order.</data>
  <data key="d2">10</data>
</node>
<node id="DEALING WITH DEBT COLLECTORS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of understanding and exercising one's rights and options when interacting with debt collectors, including verifying and disputing debts.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="RESOURCE CARDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Educational materials or tools provided within the "Your Money, Your Goals" toolkit by the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection to assist consumers with debt management.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="STUDENT LOAN CHECKLIST">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific tool or document offered within the "Your Money, Your Goals" toolkit by the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection to help individuals deal with their student loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="SEASONAL SNAPSHOT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool or activity presented within the "Your Money, Your Goals" framework that helps individuals assess how their expenses change during the year.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An obligation to pay money to another party, which if unpaid, can lead to legal actions like garnishment. Examples include unpaid debts, child support, defaulted federal student loans, back taxes, and court costs.</data>
  <data key="d2">44</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBTS IN COLLECTION">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial obligations that are significantly past due and have been turned over to a collection agency, indicating a heightened risk of financial difficulty.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="PAST-DUE UTILITIES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Unpaid bills for essential utility services (e.g., electricity, water) that are overdue, representing a financial risk and potential disruption of services.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="INSTALLMENT LOAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of loan where the borrower receives the full amount upfront and repays it with interest in fixed, regular payments over a predetermined period.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="LINE OF CREDIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A flexible borrowing arrangement from a financial institution that allows a borrower to withdraw money as needed up to a certain limit and repay it over time, offering revolving access to funds.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT CARD DEBT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The accumulated balance of money owed on a credit card, which can arise from paying medical bills with a credit card and is considered by creditors when assessing loan applications.</data>
  <data key="d2">10</data>
</node>
<node id="BACK CHILD SUPPORT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Unpaid child support payments that are overdue, representing a financial obligation to a former spouse or child's guardian.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="AUTO TITLE LOAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A short-term loan where the borrower gives up the title to their car or truck as security until repayment, with the loan amount typically 25 to 50 percent of the car’s total value.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="FRIENDS &amp; FAMILY">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals to whom one might owe money, often representing informal debt arrangements.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="STUDENT LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of loan taken out to finance education, often considered "good debt" if it leads to better job prospects, but can be a setback if educational goals are not met.</data>
  <data key="d2">22</data>
</node>
<node id="MORTGAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal agreement by which a bank or other creditor lends money at interest in exchange for taking title to the debtor's property, with the condition that the conveyance of title becomes void upon the payment of the debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">24</data>
</node>
<node id="PAST-DUE RENT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Unpaid rent payments that are overdue, representing a financial risk that could lead to penalties, eviction, or damage to one's rental history.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="GAMBLING DEBT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial obligations incurred as a result of gambling activities, which may not always be legally enforceable depending on jurisdiction.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MEDICAL DEBT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial obligations incurred from medical services, which were a major factor in declining credit scores for many and are subject to specific reporting rules by credit reporting companies.</data>
  <data key="d2">14</data>
</node>
<node id="BACK TAXES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Unpaid tax obligations owed to a government agency, which can be collected through garnishment of wages, federal benefits, or tax refund offsets.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYDAY LOAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A small, short-term loan typically repaid, along with fees, when the borrower receives their next paycheck. Lenders often cash a post-dated check or electronically debit payment from a checking account.</data>
  <data key="d2">10</data>
</node>
<node id="PAST-DUE FEES &amp; FINES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Unpaid charges or penalties that are overdue, representing a financial risk that can lead to additional costs or legal consequences.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="BEHIND ON BILLS? START WITH ONE STEP">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A booklet resource offered by the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection to help individuals who are behind on bill payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT LOG">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool designed to help individuals see a full picture of all their debt payments and figure out when they will pay, aiding in debt management.</data>
  <data key="d2">8</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT CARD STATEMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A monthly summary of credit card account activity that includes crucial information such as the payment date, minimum payment, interest rate, current balance, and estimated payoff date.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="LOAN OR MORTGAGE AGREEMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal document outlining the terms and conditions of a loan or mortgage, including the interest rate, fees, payment dates, and other contractual terms.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="COURT ORDERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Legal directives that specify payment amounts, due dates, and other terms, often related to financial obligations such as back child support.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="BILLING STATEMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Documents detailing charges for services or products, which can include past-due amounts and late fees, useful for filling in a debt log.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="FEDERAL STUDENT LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Loans for education that are originated or guaranteed by the Department of Education, encompassing various types like Direct Loan, Stafford, PLUS, and Perkins, and typically offering flexible repayment options.</data>
  <data key="d2">14</data>
</node>
<node id="NATIONAL STUDENT LOAN DATA SYSTEM">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An online centralized database managed by the Department of Education (nslds.ed.gov) that allows individuals to view a comprehensive list of their federal student loans and associated servicers.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT COLLECTOR">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual or entity that attempts to collect outstanding debts, with specific guidance provided by the CFPB on how to respond to them via the "Dealing with Debt Collectors" tool.</data>
  <data key="d2">13</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCOUNTANT">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">A professional who provides financial guidance related to accounting and financial record-keeping, whose advice the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection states is not replaced by its materials.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CERTIFIED FINANCIAL ADVISOR">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">A professional who provides financial advice and planning services, whose guidance the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection states is not replaced by its materials.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMER FINANCIAL PROTECTION BUREAU">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A U.S. government agency that regulates the offering and provision of consumer financial products and services under Federal consumer financial laws, educates and empowers consumers, and provides tools and resources like the "Your Money, Your Goals" toolkit.</data>
  <data key="d2">17</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL EMPOWERMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial concept that encompasses financial literacy but goes further by building practical skills to manage money, choose financial products and services, and increase confidence in financial decision-making.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL EMPOWERMENT SELF-ASSESSMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool within the Your Money, Your Goals toolkit designed to help individuals understand their financial knowledge, skills, and confidence across three parts: 'What you know', 'How you feel', and 'Your experiences'.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="MY MONEY PICTURE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific diagnostic tool included within the "Your Money, Your Goals Toolkit" designed to help individuals assess their current financial situation and future goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="SETTING GOALS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A module and fundamental activity within the toolkit focused on defining specific financial objectives such as hopes and dreams, and large purchases.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="SMART GOALS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An effective method for setting goals that ensures they are Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, and Time-bound, bringing structure and increasing the likelihood of accomplishment.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="PUTTING GOALS INTO ACTION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool within the toolkit designed to help individuals develop practical steps to achieve their financial goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="PLANNING FOR LIFE EVENTS AND LARGE PURCHASES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A strategic process or module within the toolkit focused on preparing financially for significant personal life occurrences and substantial acquisitions.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="REVISING GOALS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A handout from the toolkit that provides guidance on how to adjust or update financial goals as circumstances change.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SAVING">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The financial practice of setting aside money in the present for use in the future, aimed at achieving financial goals or covering unexpected expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">13</data>
</node>
<node id="PUBLIC BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Government assistance programs, such as SSDI, SSI, SNAP, TANF, LIHEAP, and Public Housing, which often have specific asset limits that recipients must adhere to.</data>
  <data key="d2">8</data>
</node>
<node id="SAVINGS PLAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool or strategy designed to help individuals set a weekly savings target, build a personal safety net, and achieve financial goals by breaking down saving into manageable steps</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="SAVING AND ASSET LIMITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool created to help individuals understand and determine the asset limits applicable to their public benefits, ensuring they can save without jeopardizing eligibility</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="FINDING A PLACE FOR SAVINGS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool within the toolkit guiding individuals on various secure options for depositing and holding their saved money.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SAVING AT TAX TIME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A handout providing strategies and information on opportunities for saving money or managing finances around the tax period.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="TRACKING INCOME AND BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The systematic process of monitoring, recording, and managing all forms of income and financial assistance received to ensure financial stability.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The money individuals and families earn, identified as a critical factor influencing their ability to prepare financially for unexpected events, with higher income generally correlating with greater preparedness.</data>
  <data key="d2">42</data>
</node>
<node id="INCOME AND BENEFITS TRACKER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial tool or document designed to help individuals track their monthly income and benefits, used for planning expenses and savings goals, and is part of the 'YOUR MONEY, YOUR GOALS TOOLKIT'.</data>
  <data key="d2">8</data>
</node>
<node id="CHOOSING HOW TO GET PAID">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A section or activity within the toolkit that provides guidance on selecting optimal payment methods, detailing their advantages and disadvantages.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="INCREASING INCOME AND BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial tool or guide, part of the 'YOUR MONEY, YOUR GOALS TOOLKIT', offering strategies and tips to help individuals boost their income and benefits.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYING BILLS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of settling financial obligations, such as regular bills, often enabled by consistent income or savings.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="SPENDING TRACKER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool designed to monitor and categorize monthly expenditures, helping users identify areas where they might reduce costs and manage their finances more effectively.</data>
  <data key="d2">15</data>
</node>
<node id="BILL CALENDAR">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool or system for tracking when payments are due, helping to avoid late fees and manage recurring bills and expenses by planning ahead.</data>
  <data key="d2">9</data>
</node>
<node id="CHOOSING HOW TO PAY BILLS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool within the toolkit guiding individuals on selecting efficient and secure payment methods for their bills.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CUTTING EXPENSES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial strategy involving identifying and implementing ways to reduce spending, such as minimizing car, eating out, financial service, furniture, clothing, grocery, home energy, insurance, and membership costs.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="PRIORITIZING BILLS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A strategic approach to managing expenses when funds are limited, focusing on identifying and paying the most critical obligations first to protect necessities like housing, income, and insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="GETTING THROUGH THE MONTH">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The thematic focus of MODULE 5, emphasizing strategies and tools for maintaining financial stability and managing money effectively over a monthly period.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="CASH FLOW BUDGET">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial plan that systematically records and projects the movement of money into and out of an individual's finances over a specific period, covered in Module 5.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPROVING CASH FLOW">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific tool within the toolkit designed to help users brainstorm and develop strategies to address weeks where expenses exceed income and benefits, thereby getting their finances back on track.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="ADJUSTING YOUR CASH FLOW">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">The primary activity described in the text, involving modifying the timing of income and expenses to better align them and manage finances more effectively.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="DEALING WITH DEBT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The overarching process of understanding, planning for, and actively managing financial obligations to alleviate the burden of debt, which is the subject of Module 6.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="CO-SIGNERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual who agrees to repay a loan if the primary borrower defaults, sharing the same obligation as a co-borrower</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="STUDENT LOAN DEBT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">The financial obligation incurred from student loans, which can be difficult to eliminate, especially federal student loan debt, even in bankruptcy.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYDAY LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of short-term, high-cost loan, typically due in 14 days, with an average loan amount of $350 and fees around $15 per $100 borrowed.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="AUTO TITLE LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of short-term loan where the borrower uses their car title as collateral, often for amounts equal to 25-50% of the car's value and with high annual percentage rates.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="RENT-TO-OWN ARRANGEMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A contractual agreement where a consumer rents an item (e.g., furniture, electronics) with the option to purchase it by continuing payments or paying a lump sum.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="PROBLEMS WITH DEBT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Potential negative consequences, such as default, high interest, or collection issues, associated with financial obligations.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="AVOIDING PROBLEMS WITH DEBT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Strategies and practices outlined in the toolkit to prevent negative financial consequences related to borrowing money.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT-TO-INCOME CALCULATOR">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial tool used to determine the ratio of an individual's total monthly debt payments to their gross monthly income, indicating financial stress.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPARING AUTO LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of evaluating different auto loan offers from various lenders to identify the most advantageous terms and conditions.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="REPAYING STUDENT LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">The active process of making payments on student loans to fulfill financial obligations, often involving the evaluation of various repayment plans.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="WHEN DEBT COLLECTORS CALL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool within the toolkit providing advice and steps to take when contacted by agencies seeking repayment of overdue debts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="AVOIDING MEDICAL DEBT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A handout from the toolkit offering strategies to prevent or minimize financial obligations arising from healthcare costs.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UNDERSTANDING CREDIT REPORTS AND SCORES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">This is a financial concept referring to the knowledge and interpretation of credit reports and the methodology behind credit scores, as detailed in Module 7.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT REPORTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Comprehensive documents compiled by credit reporting companies that detail an individual's credit history, including accounts, payment behavior, and public records. They are essential for assessing creditworthiness and can be obtained free once every 12 months from each company.</data>
  <data key="d2">19</data>
</node>
<node id="USING CREDIT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of borrowing money or obtaining goods/services with the promise of future payment, a topic covered in the toolkit.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="REQUESTING YOUR FREE CREDIT REPORTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">The procedure for consumers to obtain their credit reports free of charge, typically on an annual basis from each nationwide credit reporting company to check for accuracy.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="REVIEWING YOUR CREDIT REPORTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">The activity of carefully examining the contents of one's credit reports for accuracy, completeness, and potential errors, recommended annually.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="DISPUTING ERRORS ON YOUR CREDIT REPORTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">The formal process of challenging and seeking correction for any inaccuracies identified in a credit report with the respective credit reporting company.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="GETTING AND KEEPING A GOOD CREDIT HISTORY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">The ongoing effort to establish and maintain a positive record of borrowing and repayment, leading to better financial opportunities, lower costs, and easier access to services.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="CHOOSING FINANCIAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of evaluating and selecting appropriate financial instruments and offerings based on individual needs, comparing aspects like fees, rates, and services.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial Products and Services encompass a wide range of offerings from financial institutions, such as accounts, loans, and insurance, designed to help individuals manage their money.</data>
  <data key="d2">9</data>
</node>
<node id="OPENING A CHECKING OR SAVINGS ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of establishing a new bank account for managing daily transactions or accumulating savings, a topic covered in the toolkit.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CHECKING OR SAVINGS ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of bank account used for managing daily transactions (checking) or accumulating funds (savings), discussed in the toolkit.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="AVOIDING CHECKING ACCOUNT FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool within the toolkit providing strategies to prevent incurring charges associated with checking accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="EVALUATING YOUR PREPAID OR PAYROLL CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool within the toolkit for assessing the terms, fees, and features of different prepaid and payroll cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYROLL CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A prepaid card onto which an employer directly deposits an employee's salary or wages, allowing access to funds like a prepaid or debit card. It may have service or inactivity fees but offers full consumer protections.</data>
  <data key="d2">21</data>
</node>
<node id="KNOWING YOUR PREPAID CARD RIGHTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A handout or guide, found in Module 8 of the toolkit, that informs individuals about their consumer rights pertaining to various types of prepaid cards, including payroll, government benefits, and EBT cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="SENDING MONEY ABROAD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of transferring funds to recipients in other countries, which is subject to specific federal protections and disclosure requirements for providers.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="PROTECTING YOUR MONEY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Module 9 of the "Your Money, Your Goals" toolkit, which provides guidance on safeguarding finances, including avoiding scams, guarding information, and handling identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="SCAMS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Deceptive practices and fraudulent schemes, particularly those related to disaster assistance, against which FEMA provides warnings and safeguards, as mentioned in the EFFAK.</data>
  <data key="d2">11</data>
</node>
<node id="AVOIDING SCAMS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Strategies and practices outlined in the toolkit to prevent individuals from falling victim to fraudulent schemes.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PROTECTING YOUR IDENTITY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">The preventative measures and actions taken to safeguard personal information from being compromised by identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="HOW TO HANDLE IDENTITY THEFT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A handout from the toolkit providing steps and resources for individuals to take if they become victims of identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CFPB">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The Consumer Financial Protection Bureau is an entity that takes action against organizations, provides information on financial products like student debt, and handles complaints regarding banks, debt collectors, bank accounts, credit cards, student loans, and consumer loans. It also offers "Ask CFPB" for money questions and publishes the "Your Money, Your Goals" toolkit.</data>
  <data key="d2">25</data>
</node>
<node id="CFPB YMYG TOOLKIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A toolkit developed by the CFPB (Consumer Financial Protection Bureau) to empower consumers with financial knowledge and protection strategies.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="MODULE 4: PAYING BILLS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A section within the "YOUR MONEY, YOUR GOALS TOOLKIT" containing five tools to help users understand spending, manage bills, and cut expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="BILLS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial obligations or payments that are due, which, when accumulating, can lead to stress and financial difficulties, and are addressed by CFPB tools like the Bill Calendar and Prioritizing Bills.</data>
  <data key="d2">20</data>
</node>
<node id="EXPENSES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Costs incurred for various necessities and wants, such as food, rent, and transportation, which can be difficult to cover when trapped in a borrowing cycle.</data>
  <data key="d2">24</data>
</node>
<node id="BILL PAYMENT SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial product or feature that provides a low-cost, easy way to pay and manage bills online, from a mobile device, or in person at various retail locations.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT UNIONS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Member-owned financial cooperatives that provide similar services to banks, such as checking and savings accounts, often with a focus on community and member benefits.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMERFINANCE.GOV">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The official website of the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, providing resources, tools, and information regarding consumer finance topics, including debt collection and consumer rights.</data>
  <data key="d2">12</data>
</node>
<node id="SPENDING">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of disbursing money for goods or services, which can be tracked and analyzed using tools like the Spending Tracker to identify areas for cutbacks.</data>
  <data key="d2">11</data>
</node>
<node id="NEEDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Essential requirements for living, such as shelter, utilities, food, medication, clothing, and transportation, which are prioritized in financial planning.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="WANTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Non-essential desires or preferences that improve quality of life but are not strictly necessary for survival, and can be adjusted to cut expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="OBLIGATIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Responsibilities or duties that individuals have regarding financial agreements, accounts, or services, often incurring consequences if not met.</data>
  <data key="d2">8</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial obligations owed to another party, such as loans or credit card bills, which can be covered by a life insurance death benefit.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="CHILD SUPPORT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Court-mandated payments made by one parent to the other for the financial care of a child, which can be either a source of income or a debt payment.</data>
  <data key="d2">12</data>
</node>
<node id="SPOUSAL SUPPORT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial assistance provided to a former spouse after a divorce or separation, categorized as an obligation.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="JUDGMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Judgments are official court orders that typically require one party to pay a monetary award to another, often appearing on credit reports if related to debts.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="DIGITAL MONEY APPS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Mobile applications used for tracking bills, monitoring spending, or making digital payments, offering convenience but requiring security awareness.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="DIGITAL WALLET">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A secure electronic service that allows individuals to make payments online or in stores via a mobile device, often integrated within digital money apps.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Charges levied by financial institutions for various services or conditions, such as monthly maintenance, per-check transactions, or overdrafts. Strategies can be employed to reduce or avoid these charges.</data>
  <data key="d2">29</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT CARD INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Details related to a credit card, which is a financial account, often required by financial apps and considered sensitive personal information.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL ACCOUNTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Accounts (e.g., bank accounts, credit cards) that may be linked to financial apps, requiring password protection and potentially two-factor authentication. Users should not save passwords for these accounts on mobile devices.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="PROBLEM WITH BILL PAYMENT SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A difficulty or issue encountered when using a bill payment service provided by a bank or credit union, for which complaints can be submitted to the CFPB.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="STRUGGLE TO COVER EXPENSES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial hardship experienced when income is insufficient or irregular, making it difficult to pay bills and living costs, highlighting the need for budgeting.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL TRANSACTIONS ON PUBLIC WI-FI">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of conducting money-related activities over unsecured public wireless internet, which poses a significant security risk to personal and financial information.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SAFEGUARDING PERSONAL INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of protecting sensitive personal data from unauthorized access or misuse, particularly when using digital financial tools, through measures like password protection.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PASSWORD-PROTECTING MOBILE DEVICES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of securing mobile phones and other devices with strong passwords or other authentication methods to prevent unauthorized access to financial accounts and personal data.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="IDENTIFY YOUR RISK">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A fundamental step in emergency preparedness where individuals or organizations assess and recognize the specific hazards and vulnerabilities they face.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DEVELOP A PLAN">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A key step in emergency preparedness that involves creating a structured strategy, outline, or set of procedures to follow in response to identified risks.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="TAKE ACTION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A step in emergency preparedness that involves implementing the developed plans and measures to prepare for and respond to emergencies effectively.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="EMERGENCY PREPAREDNESS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The proactive process of preparing for emergencies and disasters, encompassing activities like learning about risks, developing plans, building supply kits, and engaging in community readiness efforts.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DISASTER ASSISTANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial or other forms of aid and support provided by government agencies or other organizations to help individuals and businesses recover from the devastating effects of a disaster.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="CLEANUP">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of removing debris, clearing damaged areas, and restoring cleanliness after a disaster event.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RECOVERY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The long-term process of rebuilding, restoring, and rehabilitating communities and individuals to their pre-disaster or improved state after an incident.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEDERAL ASSISTANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial or other support provided by the U.S. federal government to individuals, businesses, and state/local governments in response to a declared federal disaster.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEMA’S ONLINE DISASTER APPLICATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A digital platform provided by FEMA for disaster survivors to apply for federal assistance conveniently.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HOMEOWNERS OR RENTERS INSURANCE POLICIES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Contracts that provide financial protection against loss or damage to a home or its contents, essential for recovery after a disaster.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BANK ACCOUNT DATA">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Information related to a person's bank accounts, including account and routing numbers, often required for receiving disaster assistance funds.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INSURANCE INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Details about insurance coverage, policies, and providers that are critical for filing claims and recovering losses after a disaster.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TOTAL HOUSEHOLD ANNUAL INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The combined gross earnings of all individuals residing in a household over a year, often a factor in determining eligibility for disaster assistance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ROUTING AND ACCOUNT NUMBER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Specific banking codes used to identify a financial institution and a particular account for electronic transactions, such as direct deposit of disaster funds.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DISASTER ASSISTANCE FUNDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Monetary resources disbursed by government agencies or other organizations to help disaster survivors cover expenses for housing, repairs, and other needs.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEMA APPLICATION NUMBER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A unique identification code assigned to an individual's application for federal disaster assistance, used for tracking and reference.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOCAL AUTHORITIES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Governmental bodies, such as police or municipal agencies, operating at the local level, responsible for law enforcement and community safety.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MINIMUM BALANCE REQUIREMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific minimum amount of money that must be kept in a bank account to avoid service fees or to qualify for certain account features.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="SHOP AROUND">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of comparing prices, services, and offers from multiple providers before making a decision, especially concerning financial services.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FUNDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">General term for money, particularly when held in an account or designated for a purpose, some of which are protected from garnishment.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="OPT IN">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of affirmatively choosing to participate in a service or agree to specific terms, often required for certain overdraft services.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OPT OUT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process by which individuals can request to be removed from lists used for pre-screened credit offers, either temporarily or permanently.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="NETWORK LOGO">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A visual identifier or brand mark representing a payment network (e.g., Visa, Mastercard) on a financial product like a card.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REGISTRATION PROCESS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The procedure by which a cardholder provides information to the card provider to activate full card features or to change a card's status, such as making a non-reloadable card reloadable.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="WAGES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Monetary compensation paid by an employer to an employee for work performed, typically on an hourly, daily, or weekly basis, and can be paid via payroll card.</data>
  <data key="d2">9</data>
</node>
<node id="NEEDS-BASED PROGRAMS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Government or social welfare initiatives designed to provide assistance to individuals or families based on their financial need, such as Temporary Assistance for Needy Families or Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="JAIL">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A correctional facility where individuals may be held before or during trial or sentencing, or for shorter sentences.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PRISON">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A place for the confinement of people convicted of serious crimes, used for long-term confinement.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMERS">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals who receive financial products and services, may be subject to various risks and fees, and can submit complaints to the CFPB.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="EST">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">Eastern Standard Time, the time zone specified for the operating hours of the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau's toll-free and TTY/TDD phone services.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="ENGLISH LANGUAGE">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">One of the languages in which the Newcomer's Guides to Managing Money are available, targeting a specific linguistic demographic.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SPANISH LANGUAGE">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">One of the languages in which the Newcomer's Guides to Managing Money are available, targeting a specific linguistic demographic.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TRIAL">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A formal examination of evidence by a judge, and typically before a jury, in order to decide guilt in a case, relevant for criminal justice-involved individuals.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SENTENCING">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">The judicial determination of a criminal punishment, relevant for criminal justice-involved individuals.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="BACKGROUND SCREENING REPORTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Documents compiled by third parties that provide personal and financial information about an individual, used by employers for job applications.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial arrangement or record, such as a credit card account, that a minor can be an authorized user or joint owner on, and which has a payment status and can be closed or become delinquent.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="PAPERWORK">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">General term for documents, particularly official forms and records, often required for financial transactions or agreements.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DEDUCTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Amounts subtracted from an individual's gross income for purposes such as taxes, insurance premiums, or retirement contributions.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="INDIVIDUAL RIGHTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Legal and ethical entitlements that protect a person's interests in financial matters and employment processes, such as background screenings.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BENEFICIARY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual or entity designated to receive assets or benefits from a will, trust, or financial policy.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="COLLATERAL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An asset pledged by a borrower to a lender to secure a loan, which can be seized by the lender if the borrower defaults, such as a house for a mortgage or an item for a pawn loan.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An accounting entry that represents a decrease in assets or an increase in liabilities, often associated with a withdrawal or payment from an account.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FAIR MARKET VALUE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The estimated price at which an asset would change hands between a willing buyer and a willing seller, neither being under any compulsion to buy or sell.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL LANGUAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Specialized terminology and jargon used within the finance industry, which can be confusing to those unfamiliar with it.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MONEY DECISIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Choices and judgments made regarding the management, allocation, and use of personal or household funds.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial transactions involving money paid out, which should be regularly checked on statements to ensure they were authorized and agreed upon.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Advantages or positive outcomes derived from particular financial choices, products, or strategies.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL PITFALLS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Hidden dangers or potential problems in financial management that can lead to losses, debt, or other negative consequences.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RISKS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The potential for adverse outcomes, such as loss, theft, or financial complications, associated with different payment methods.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="FOCUS ON REENTRY COMPANION GUIDE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A guide designed to financially empower criminal justice-involved individuals and their families, covering topics like preparing finances for incarceration, managing debt, and understanding credit reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PREPARING FOR RELEASE: DOCUMENTS AND IDENTIFICATION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool or guide that helps incarcerated individuals prepare for their release by organizing necessary documents and identification.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SETTING SMART GOALS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool provided within the "Focus on Reentry" guide for setting specific, measurable, achievable, relevant, and time-bound financial goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="UNDERSTANDING YOUR PAY STUB">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool or guide to help individuals interpret the information provided on their pay stub, including gross pay and deductions.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREATING A CASH FLOW BUDGET">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific tool or activity within the toolkit that guides users through the process of tracking income and expenses to build a cash flow budget.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="LOWERING YOUR DEBT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool or guide providing strategies and steps to reduce an individual's outstanding financial obligations.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REQUESTING YOUR FREE CREDIT REPORTS BY MAIL FROM A CORRECTIONAL FACILITY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A handout detailing the specific process for incarcerated individuals to request their free credit reports via mail.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DISPUTING ERRORS ON YOUR CREDIT REPORT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A handout or guide on the process for challenging and correcting inaccuracies found on an individual's credit report.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REVIEWING YOUR BACKGROUND SCREENING REPORTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool or guide on how to examine and understand the information contained within an individual's background screening reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SUBMIT A COMPLAINT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of formally registering an issue or grievance with the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection, especially concerning financial products or services, via cfpb.gov/complaint.</data>
  <data key="d2">10</data>
</node>
<node id="ONLINE PAYMENT METHOD">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of making payments electronically via the internet, as opposed to physical methods.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT CARD PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments made towards outstanding balances on credit cards, which can affect credit reports and interest rates if paid late.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYDAY LOAN PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments made towards payday loans, listed as a type of debt payment category.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PAWN LOAN PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments made towards pawn loans, listed as a type of debt payment category.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="AUTO TITLE LOAN PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments made towards auto title loans, listed as a type of debt payment category.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="HEALTH INSURANCE PREMIUMS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Regular payments made for health insurance coverage, categorized under health expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial product that provides protection against specific risks, helping individuals and families recover financially from losses incurred during disasters or emergencies, implicitly part of the EFFAK's guidance.</data>
  <data key="d2">20</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT RECORD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A detailed history of an individual's borrowing and repayment behavior, used by lenders to assess creditworthiness.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="NEGATIVE ENTRY IN CREDIT RECORD">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A detrimental mark on an individual's credit history, resulting from missed or late payments, which can affect future borrowing ability.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="MODULE 5: GETTING THROUGH THE MONTH">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A section within the 'Your Money, Your Goals Toolkit' that offers information and strategies for managing finances throughout the month, including cash flow budgets.</data>
  <data key="d2">10</data>
</node>
<node id="RECEIPTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Written or printed acknowledgments that something has been received, used as documentation for tracking spending.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CATEGORY TOTALS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The aggregated sum of money spent within specific classifications of expenses for a given period, used in a spending tracker.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TOTAL SPENDING FOR THE MONTH">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The overall sum of all expenditures made over a single month, calculated from weekly amounts per category.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Regular payments made to a landlord or property owner for the use of housing, which is an expense but generally not included in debt-to-income ratios for renters.</data>
  <data key="d2">14</data>
</node>
<node id="CAR PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Recurring payments made towards the financing or leasing of a vehicle, typically with fixed due dates.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="CELL PHONE PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Regular payments for mobile phone services or device costs, identified as a need or obligation.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="NEEDS AND OBLIGATIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Essential and unavoidable expenses and financial commitments that must be met regularly, such as rent or car payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CELL PHONE (CATEGORY)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A spending category for all costs related to having and using a cell phone.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT PAYMENT (CATEGORY)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A spending category encompassing various loan and credit payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EDUCATION + CHILDCARE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A spending category for childcare costs, school supplies, fees, and other activity fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ENTERTAINMENT + PERSONAL CARE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A spending category for leisure activities, sports, lottery tickets, subscriptions, and personal grooming.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GROCERIES + OTHER SUPPLIES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A spending category for food and beverages brought into the home, and household supplies.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="HOUSING + UTILITIES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A spending category for rent, mortgage, insurance, property taxes, and various utility services.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="OTHER SPENDING CATEGORY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A broad spending category for expenses not covered by specific categories, including court-ordered expenses, household items, savings, and job-related expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OTHER LOAN PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A general classification for payments made on various types of loans not specifically detailed, falling under the debt payment category.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CO-PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A fixed amount paid by an insured person for a healthcare service, part of health expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MEDICATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Costs associated with purchasing prescribed or over-the-counter drugs, part of health expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DONATIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Acts of giving money or goods to a charitable cause or religious organization, part of helping others.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RELIGIOUS ORGANIZATIONS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Groups or institutions established for religious purposes, often recipients of donations.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OTHER CHARITIES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Non-profit organizations dedicated to helping others, often recipients of donations.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GIFTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Items or money given to someone without expectation of payment, often a discretionary expense under helping others.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="PROPERTY TAXES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Taxes levied by a governing authority on the value of real estate, which may or may not be included in a monthly mortgage payment.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="ELECTRICITY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments for electrical power utility service for a household, part of housing and utilities.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GAS (UTILITY)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments for natural gas or other fuel utility service for heating or cooking, part of housing and utilities.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WATER AND SEWAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments for municipal water supply and waste removal services, part of housing and utilities.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LANDLINE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments for traditional wired telephone service, part of housing and utilities.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TELEVISION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments for television broadcasting services, such as cable or satellite, part of housing and utilities.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="INTERNET SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Subscription services providing internet access, for which eligibility, terms, or required deposits might be influenced by an individual's credit history.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="GAS (FUEL)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments for vehicle fuel, part of transport expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TRANSIT FARES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments for public transportation, such as bus or train tickets, part of transport expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RIDE SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments for on-demand transportation services, like ride-sharing apps, part of transport expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CABS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments for taxi services, part of transport expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COURT-ORDERED EXPENSES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial obligations mandated by a legal court, falling under the 'Other' spending category.</data>
