<node id="HOME INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Home Insurance is a type of property insurance that covers losses and damages to an individual's residence and its contents, also providing liability coverage.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="CAR INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Car insurance is a type of insurance policy designed to cover vehicles against damages, theft, or liability, with specific requirements and coverages varying by state.</data>
  <data key="d2">11</data>
</node>
<node id="HEALTH INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of insurance coverage that pays for medical and surgical expenses incurred by the insured, influencing what costs are covered for procedures.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="DISABILITY INCOME INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Insurance that provides income replacement if an individual becomes disabled due to illness or injury, protecting finances.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PROPERTY AND LIABILITY INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of insurance that covers property damage and legal liability, often relevant for businesses.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COMMERCIAL VEHICLE INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Insurance specifically designed for vehicles used for business operations.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WORKERS' COMPENSATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Coverage that provides wage replacement and medical benefits to employees injured in the course of employment, required for businesses with employees.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HEALTHCARE PLAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A structured program that provides health benefits, often offered by employers.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MEDICARE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A federal health insurance program for people 65 or older, younger people with certain disabilities, and people with End-Stage Renal Disease, with local help available via SHIP programs.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="SUPPLEMENTAL COVERAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Additional insurance designed to cover out-of-pocket medical costs not fully covered by primary insurance like Medicare.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INSURANCE REVIEW">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A comprehensive process of evaluating existing insurance policies (coverage, premiums, beneficiaries) to ensure they align with current life, needs, and goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COVERAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Coverage refers to the scope of protection provided by an insurance policy, detailing what risks, losses, or expenses are included or excluded from reimbursement.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="PREMIUMS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Premiums are the regular payments made to an insurance company in exchange for coverage, with the amount often influenced by factors like chosen coverages and deductibles.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="BENEFICIARIES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The individuals or entities designated to receive the benefits of an insurance policy, whose designations need updating after life changes.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REPLACEMENT COST">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The cost to replace damaged or lost property with new property of similar kind and quality, a key factor in home insurance assessments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PERSONAL PROPERTY PROTECTION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The aspect of insurance that covers an individual's movable possessions against loss or damage, often found in home or renters insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LIABILITY PROTECTION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The aspect of insurance that covers legal responsibility for injury or damage to others, a crucial component of many insurance types.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OUT-OF-POCKET COSTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Out-of-Pocket Costs are expenses that an individual must pay directly from their own funds, rather than being covered by insurance, often including deductibles.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL SHIFTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Changes in an individual's monetary situation that can impact insurance needs and require a policy review.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GAPS IN PROTECTION">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Insufficient or missing insurance coverage that can leave individuals vulnerable to financial loss, which annual reviews aim to avoid.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SOMETHING UNEXPECTED HAPPENS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Unforeseen events that could lead to financial losses or require coverage, highlighting the need for comprehensive insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UNDER-INSURED">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The state of having insufficient insurance coverage, meaning potential losses may exceed coverage limits.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYING FOR MORE COVERAGE THAN NEEDED">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The financial risk of overpaying for insurance due to having excessive coverage for current needs.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UNCOVERED (IN CASE OF CLAIM OR ACCIDENT)">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk of lacking insurance protection for a specific event, leading to significant personal financial responsibility.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NEW RISKS AND RESPONSIBILITIES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Additional potential dangers and duties, particularly associated with starting a business, requiring new insurance considerations.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ILLNESS OR INJURY">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Health-related incidents that can lead to inability to work and financial loss, addressed by disability insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UNEXPECTED COSTS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Unforeseen expenses that can arise from coverage gaps or events not adequately insured, mitigated by regular policy reviews.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REVIEWING INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The active process of examining and evaluating existing insurance policies to ensure they meet current needs and goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UPDATING COVERAGE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of modifying the terms, limits, or types of insurance coverage to align with changes in life or property.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHANGING BENEFICIARY DESIGNATIONS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of formally altering the individuals or entities designated to receive benefits from an insurance policy.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SCHEDULE A CONVERSATION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of arranging a meeting or discussion, typically with an insurance agent, to review policy options.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CUSTOMIZING COVERAGE OPTIONS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of tailoring specific insurance policy features and amounts to suit individual or family requirements.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="KEEPING INSURANCE UP TO DATE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The ongoing effort to maintain insurance policies that accurately reflect current assets, liabilities, and life circumstances.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OVERSPENDING">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk of spending more money than available, which can occur with a debit card if a user opts into an overdraft program, leading to bank-covered purchases and associated fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="REPAY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of paying back borrowed money or a debt, often done monthly over a set period for loans and mortgages.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="BORROWING MONEY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of receiving funds from a lender, such as through a credit card, with the obligation to pay it back, typically with interest if a balance is carried.</data>
  <data key="d2">8</data>
</node>
<node id="CARRYING A BALANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of not paying off the full amount owed on a credit card statement by the due date, resulting in interest charges on the remaining amount.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RIGHTS AND RESPONSIBILITIES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The legal entitlements and duties of consumers when using financial products or services, such as prepaid cards or sending money abroad.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DOCUMENTATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Official papers or records that provide evidence or information, essential for various financial processes and applications.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL GOAL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific objective related to managing money, such as building savings, improving credit history, or efficiently accessing paychecks.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPROVE CREDIT HISTORY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of taking steps to enhance one's record of financial reliability, often by using certain financial products responsibly.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCESS PAYCHECK">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of gaining convenient entry to one's earned wages, often through direct deposit into an account or onto a card.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TURN PAYCHECK INTO CASH">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of converting one's earned wages, typically received as a check or direct deposit, into physical currency.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SECURE PLACE TO KEEP MONEY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial goal referring to the desire for a safe and protected location for one's funds, often achieved through products like CDs, checking, or savings accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MAKE PURCHASES WITHOUT CARRYING CASH">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of buying goods or services using electronic payment methods like debit cards or prepaid cards, avoiding the need for physical currency.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="AVOID DEBT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of managing finances to prevent or minimize the accumulation of borrowed money, often achieved by using prepaid cards or debit cards instead of credit.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOW-COST WAY TO PAY BILLS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial goal focused on efficiently managing and paying expenses with minimal service charges or transaction fees, often through services like bill payment or money orders.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EASY WAY TO PAY BILLS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial goal emphasizing convenience and simplicity in managing and paying expenses, potentially through online banking or mobile devices.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAY BILLS ONLINE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of settling financial obligations over the internet, typically through a bank's bill payment service or a linked account.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PAY BILLS FROM MOBILE DEVICE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of settling financial obligations using a smartphone or tablet, often through mobile banking apps or specific payment services.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCESS ONLINE BANKING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of using internet-based services provided by a financial institution to manage accounts, check balances, or perform transactions.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCESS MOBILE BANKING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of using a smartphone or tablet to manage bank accounts, check balances, and perform transactions via a dedicated app or mobile website.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHECK BALANCE ONLINE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of reviewing the current amount of funds available in an account through an internet-enabled device or mobile application.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEPOSIT CHECK USING PHONE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of digitally submitting a check for deposit into an account by capturing images of the check with a smartphone or mobile device camera.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DIRECT PAYCHECK DEPOSIT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of having one's salary or wages automatically transferred electronically into a bank account or onto a card by an employer.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SAVE FOR EDUCATION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of setting aside money specifically to cover future educational expenses, such as tuition or living costs for schooling.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The general concept of credit, which relates to a borrower's ability to obtain goods or services before payment, based on the trust that payment will be made in the future. It is linked to credit reports and scores.</data>
  <data key="d2">19</data>
</node>
<node id="DISPUTE FORM">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A standardized document provided by credit reporting companies for consumers to formally submit and detail errors found on their credit reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LETTER TEMPLATE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A pre-formatted guide for consumers to write a formal letter to credit reporting companies or furnishers when disputing errors on credit reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CLEAKS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Checks that have been successfully processed through the banking system and the funds have been transferred from the payer's account to the payee's account, serving as proof of payment.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MONEY ORDER STUBS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Receipts or records provided when purchasing a money order, serving as proof of the transaction and payment.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BIRTH CERTIFICATE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An official document issued by a government authority recording an individual's birth, frequently used as a primary form of identification in financial and legal contexts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LENDER">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual or financial institution that provides funds to another party with the expectation that the funds will be repaid, usually with interest, and often performs a credit review.</data>
  <data key="d2">14</data>
</node>
<node id="GOVERNMENT BENEFITS CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of prepaid card loaded by a government agency with benefits, offering full federal consumer protections against unauthorized transfers or other errors, and allowing fund access in various ways.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="ELECTRONIC BENEFITS TRANSFER (EBT) CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of government benefits card used by government programs to electronically transfer benefits, such as SNAP, to recipients.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="BUDGETING">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The financial practice of planning how to spend and save money, which can be made more challenging by certain payment methods like cash.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="TAX PURPOSES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial considerations and requirements related to taxes, which necessitate accurate tracking of income and spending.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAPER CHECK">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A physical written order to a bank to pay a stated sum of money from the drawer's account to the payee, requiring deposition or cashing, and susceptible to delays, fees, and waiting periods for funds to clear.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="CHECKING ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of bank account that allows for frequent transactions using checks, debit cards, and online banking. It may be subject to various fees, minimum balance requirements, and can incur overdraft charges if funds are insufficient. Some checking accounts may or may not earn interest.</data>
  <data key="d2">27</data>
</node>
<node id="DEPOSITING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of placing money or a financial instrument into an account, such as depositing a check or direct deposit of funds.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CASHING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of converting a check or other financial instrument into physical cash.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WAITING PERIOD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specified duration during which deposited funds, particularly from checks, are held by a financial institution before becoming fully accessible, allowing for processing.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RISK OF LOSS OR THEFT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The danger that money, financial instruments, or funds may be lost, stolen, or otherwise become inaccessible.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UNAUTHORIZED TRANSFERS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of unauthorized activity where funds are moved out of an account without permission, leading to limited responsibility for the cardholder if reported quickly under the Electronic Fund Transfer Act.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL ERRORS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Mistakes or inaccuracies in financial transactions or account management that can lead to unexpected charges or discrepancies, often covered by federal protections.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYDAY">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">The scheduled date on which an individual receives their wages or salary from an employer, often coinciding with the availability of direct deposits.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ATM">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An Automated Teller Machine, which is a terminal that allows bank customers to perform transactions such as withdrawals, deposits, and balance inquiries. Access to convenient, free ATMs is a consideration for account holders.</data>
  <data key="d2">13</data>
</node>
<node id="ONLINE BILL PAY SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An electronic service offered by financial institutions enabling users to pay bills from their accounts directly to vendors, often simplifying financial management.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PERSONAL CHECKS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Checks issued by an individual from their own checking account to make payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PROTECTIONS FOR UNAUTHORIZED TRANSFERS OR OTHER ERRORS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Safeguards, frequently mandated by federal regulations, designed to shield consumers from financial liabilities arising from fraudulent activity or administrative mistakes in their accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SUFFICIENT FUNDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The necessary balance of money in an account to cover a specific transaction, the absence of which can lead to additional charges like overdraft fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="MERCHANT">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A business or individual engaged in the sale of goods or services, where payment methods like debit cards, payroll cards, or cash can be used.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="EMPLOYER">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An organization that pays wages to its employees, potentially offering options such as payroll cards, direct deposit, or traditional paper checks.</data>
  <data key="d2">15</data>
</node>
<node id="FULL FEDERAL PROTECTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Comprehensive legal and regulatory safeguards provided by the federal government to protect consumers' financial interests, especially regarding issues like unauthorized transactions.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CARD PROVIDER">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An organization that issues and manages prepaid cards, setting terms and conditions, and potentially charging various fees for card usage and services.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="SERVICE OR INACTIVITY FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Charges levied by financial institutions for maintaining an account or due to a lack of activity over a specified period, typically associated with prepaid or payroll cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GOVERNMENT AGENCY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A general term for official bodies, such as the CFPB or others, that may be better able to assist with a consumer's complaint by having it forwarded to them.</data>
  <data key="d2">10</data>
</node>
<node id="FULL FEDERAL CONSUMER PROTECTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Extensive legal safeguards enacted by the federal government to protect the rights and interests of consumers in financial transactions and services.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NEEDS-TESTED PROGRAMS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Government assistance initiatives where eligibility for benefits is determined by an applicant's income, assets, and other financial circumstances.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="LOST OR STOLEN CARD">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk event of a prepaid card being misplaced or taken without authorization, which requires immediate reporting to the card provider or agency to secure protections and potentially replace benefits.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BENEFIT REPLACEMENT RISK">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk that government benefits on a prepaid card will not be replaced if the card is used by an unauthorized person who also knows the PIN number after the card is lost or stolen.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CARD REGISTRATION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The administrative action of officially registering a prepaid card, which is recommended to unlock more comprehensive legal protections against loss, theft, errors, and unauthorized transactions.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REPORTING LOST/STOLEN CARD">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The immediate action of contacting the card provider or the benefit-providing agency to notify them of a lost or stolen prepaid card, crucial for invoking cardholder protections.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INVESTIGATION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process conducted by a card provider when an error or an unauthorized transaction is reported, during which the disputed amount is generally credited to the cardholder's account by federal law if it takes longer than 10 business days.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="GOVERNMENT BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial aid, support, or services provided by governmental bodies, which can be distributed via various methods, including prepaid cards, and may or may not be needs-tested.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="GOVERNMENT-ARRANGED CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of prepaid card that is arranged and provided by a government entity for the purpose of distributing benefits.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMER RIGHTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The legal entitlements and protections afforded to individuals when engaging with financial products and services, such as the rights pertaining to prepaid card use, errors, and unauthorized transactions.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MANDATORY DEDUCTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Required withholdings from wages, such as social security, federal, state, and local taxes, which are subtracted before calculating disposable income for garnishment purposes.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="VOLUNTARY DEDUCTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payroll deductions that an employee chooses to have subtracted from their pay, such as contributions for health insurance premiums, retirement accounts, or union dues.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEFAULTED FEDERAL STUDENT LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">The financial risk arising from a failure to repay federal student loans according to their terms, making the borrower subject to garnishment actions by a government agency.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBTS TO GOVERNMENT AGENCY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial obligations owed to a governmental entity (other than taxes or defaulted student loans), which can result in legal collection methods like wage garnishment.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHOOSING PAYMENT METHOD">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The decision-making process an individual undertakes to select the most suitable way to receive their income, considering associated costs, advantages, and disadvantages.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT REPAYMENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of fulfilling a financial obligation by paying back the money owed to a creditor or agency, which, when complete, can terminate actions like wage garnishment.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE OR LOCAL PROGRAM">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An organized initiative or scheme established under the jurisdiction of a state or local government, often responsible for administering specific needs-tested benefits.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEDERALLY ADMINISTERED PROGRAMS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Programs that are directly managed and operated by the federal government, often providing needs-tested benefits like SSI, which typically come with federal protections.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PROTECTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Safeguards and rights established by law (e.g., federal law) for consumers, particularly for users of registered prepaid cards, covering issues like errors and unauthorized transactions.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL EMPOWERMENT TOOLKIT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A resource designed to provide steps, information, and tools to help individuals achieve financial empowerment, manage their money, and reach their financial goals by addressing specific challenges and providing referrals to community resources.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LARGE PURCHASES">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">Significant acquisitions such as training, educational expenses, tools or equipment for a job, a car, or a home, which typically require advance financial planning.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="LIFE EVENTS">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">Significant occurrences in a person's life, both planned and unplanned, that often require financial planning and saving (e.g., marriage, birth of a child, illness, retirement).</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="SAVING MONEY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of accumulating funds to cover unexpected expenses and avoid debt when responding to the costs of rebuilding after an emergency.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="EMERGENCY SAVINGS FUND">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A dedicated reserve of money specifically set aside for unexpected or urgent financial needs, recommended as a primary alternative to borrowing.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="TAX REFUNDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Funds returned to taxpayers that the toolkit helps individuals acquire and strategically use towards their financial goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="CASH FLOW BUDGETS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial tool for tracking income and expenses, which the toolkit helps individuals learn to bring into balance.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL DECISIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Choices made regarding how money is earned, spent, saved, and invested, which are influenced by values, culture, and emotions.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="VALUES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The things that are meaningful to an individual and their family, which help shape how they prioritize their time, energy, and money, making it more likely goals will be achieved if aligned.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="CULTURE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Shared beliefs, customs, and behaviors of a group that can shape an individual's attitudes and decisions about money.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EMOTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Feelings such as security, failure, love, or status that are intertwined with attitudes and behaviors around money, influencing financial decisions.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DISABILITY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A physical or mental condition that may impair an individual's ability to work or care for themselves, affecting eligibility for certain public benefits and representing a financial risk.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="GROCERIES AND HOUSEHOLD EXPENSES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A program category for financial assistance, under which Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP) and Temporary Assistance for Needy Families (TANF) are classified.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HOUSING AND HOME ENERGY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A program category for financial assistance, under which Low Income Home Energy Assistance Program (LIHEAP) and Public Housing are classified.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MEDICAL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A program category for financial assistance, under which Family Medicaid, Medicare Part D Extra Help, Medicare Savings Programs, and State Child Health Insurance Program (SCHIP) are classified.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MONEY PROTECTION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The concept of safeguarding funds from loss, theft, or destruction, often provided by federal insurance for bank and credit union accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEDERALLY INSURED">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A status indicating that a financial institution's deposits are guaranteed by a government agency, such as the FDIC or NCUA, up to a certain limit.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COSTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Expenses or charges associated with financial products and services, often used interchangeably with fees but can refer to a broader range of outlays.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ELECTRONIC MEANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Methods of conducting financial transactions or accessing funds digitally, often used for recovering stolen money from accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ACTIVATION FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Charges incurred when initially activating a financial product, such as a prepaid card.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FUND LOADING FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Charges incurred when adding money to a financial product, such as a prepaid card.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CARD USAGE FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Charges incurred for using a financial product, such as a prepaid card, for transactions.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CARD AGREEMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A contractual document outlining the terms, conditions, and fees associated with a prepaid card, which users should review.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PREVIOUS BANKING HISTORY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual's record of past interactions with financial institutions, which can influence the ability to open new bank or credit union accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OTHER DISASTER">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A general category of unforeseen events, beyond fire or natural disasters, that could lead to the loss or destruction of savings.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NATURAL DISASTER">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">An event resulting from natural processes of the Earth, such as floods, earthquakes, or hurricanes, which can cause the loss or destruction of savings.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL INSTITUTION FAILURE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk that a bank or credit union ceases to operate, potentially leading to the loss of uninsured deposits, though often mitigated by federal insurance like FDIC or NCUA.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCOUNT OPENING DIFFICULTY">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk of being unable to open a new bank or credit union account due to factors such as previous banking history.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CARD OR ACCOUNT INFORMATION LOSS/THEFT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk that sensitive financial details are compromised, potentially leading to unauthorized access or fraudulent use of funds.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SHORT-TERM LOAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of loan intended to meet immediate needs, often leading to frequent re-borrowing, typically small dollar amounts (under $500) and must be repaid quickly (e.g., 14 days).</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="NON-SUFFICIENT FUNDS FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Fees charged by banks or credit unions when an account does not have enough money to cover an automatic payment.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REPAYMENT PLAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A formal, often written agreement detailing the terms by which a debt will be paid off over time, including specified installments, interest, and handling of late payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="INTEREST RATES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The cost of borrowing money, expressed as a percentage of the principal, which can increase for credit card debt if payments are more than 60 days late.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="EMERGENCY SAVINGS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Funds specifically accumulated and reserved for unexpected financial emergencies, vital for financial resilience and a key aspect of preparedness.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT COUNSELOR">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual or organization that provides advice and guidance to consumers on managing their debts and finances, often offering certified services.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL COACH">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual who can provide guidance and support in managing personal finances.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMER FINANCIAL PROTECTION BUREAU (CFPB)">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A government agency that provides resources and information for consumers, including a tool to find credit counselors (referenced by consumerfinance.gov/askcfpb/1451).</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="COMMUNITY-BASED LENDING CIRCLE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A formalized group of friends and neighbors who lend money to each other.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CYCLE OF BORROWING">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A problematic pattern where a borrower repeatedly takes out new loans to cover payments on existing ones, leading to accumulating fees and prolonged debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="UNEXPECTED CAR REPAIR">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A scenario used as an example of an emergency expense costing $350, which can be covered by emergency savings, a credit card, or a payday loan.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ANNUAL PERCENTAGE RATE (APR)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The annual rate charged for borrowing or earned by an investment, expressed as a single percentage number that represents the actual yearly cost of funds over the term of a loan.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="REPAYMENT TERMS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The conditions under which a loan must be repaid, including the amount, schedule, and duration.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TOTAL INTEREST AND FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The combined amount of interest and additional charges incurred when borrowing money.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ACTIVE DUTY SERVICEMEMBERS">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals currently serving in the military and their dependents, who are entitled to special protections under the Military Lending Act for certain consumer loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MILITARY LENDING ACT (MLA)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A federal law providing special protections to active duty servicemembers and their dependents for certain credit products by limiting interest rates and setting terms.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMER LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A broad category of loans, including payday loans, deposit advance products, auto title loans, overdraft lines of credit, installment loans, and credit cards, subject to regulations like the Military Lending Act.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DEPOSIT ADVANCE PRODUCTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A short-term loan offered by banks that is typically repaid directly from the customer's next incoming direct deposit, covered by the Military Lending Act for servicemembers.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="OVERDRAFT LINES OF CREDIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A credit facility that allows a checking account holder to withdraw more than their available balance, up to an approved limit, covered by the Military Lending Act for servicemembers.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="INSTALLMENT LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Loans repaid over a set period through a series of scheduled, fixed payments, covered by the Military Lending Act for servicemembers with some exceptions.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="EMERGENCY FUND">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A dedicated pool of savings, recommended to start at $500-$1,000, specifically set aside to cover unexpected expenses and emergencies, serving as a financial foundation.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT COLLECTORS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Third-party entities that attempt to collect overdue debts when companies no longer wish to pursue them, operating under specific legal regulations.</data>
  <data key="d2">10</data>
</node>
<node id="EMPLOYMENT INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Money earned from working a job, typically received as a paycheck, payroll card, or direct deposit.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYCHECK">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A payment for work, often received regularly, which can be turned into cash via a check cashing service or directly deposited into a checking account.</data>
  <data key="d2">14</data>
</node>
<node id="REWARDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The positive benefits or gains anticipated from financial choices, evaluated against potential risks.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE AND LOCAL CONSUMER AGENCIES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Government bodies operating at the state or local level that protect consumer rights and handle complaints against businesses.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE AND FEDERAL LICENSING OR REGULATORY AGENCIES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Government bodies responsible for overseeing and regulating specific industries, businesses, or professions, often receiving complaints against companies.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPANY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A commercial entity or business that needs to be financially prepared for emergencies and disasters to increase the likelihood of reopening and resuming normal operations.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE'S CONSUMER PROTECTION OFFICE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A government office at the state level dedicated to protecting consumers and providing resources, accessible via usa.gov/state-consumer.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAPERWORK/ELECTRONIC DOCUMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Formal records or agreements, either physical or digital, that outline the terms of a financial deal and should accurately reflect promises made.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEAL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial transaction, business agreement, or opportunity for investment that should be fully understood before participation.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OPPORTUNITY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A potential financial venture or investment, which should be carefully reviewed and understood.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="JOB OFFERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Proposals for employment, which can sometimes be fraudulent, requiring upfront money for inventory or supplies.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INVENTORY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Goods or stock held by a business for sale, often a component of fraudulent job offer scams requiring upfront purchase.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SALES SUPPLIES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Materials or equipment needed for conducting sales activities, sometimes required for upfront purchase in deceptive job offers.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="STATEMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A periodic record of financial transactions, such as a bank statement or credit card statement, which can provide legitimate contact numbers for companies.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CUSTOMER SATISFACTION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The degree to which a product or service meets a customer's expectations, which can be gauged through reviews to assess a company's legitimacy.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PASSWORDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Security credentials used to protect mobile devices and financial accounts. They should be long, strong, unique, not saved in browsers or on devices, and not common words or phrases.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="SECURITY QUESTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Pre-selected personal questions used as an additional layer of identity verification, the answers to which should be kept private.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SECURE WEBSITE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A website that uses encryption and other security measures (like HTTPS and a lock symbol) to protect user data during online transactions.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="URL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Uniform Resource Locator, the address of a web page; an "https:" prefix and a lock symbol indicate a secure site, though not a guarantee of legitimacy.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SECURITY AUTHENTICATIONS AND CERTIFICATES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Digital credentials and processes used to verify the identity and security of a website, contributing to a secure online experience.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EMAIL ADDRESS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A unique identifier for sending and receiving electronic mail, which can be hacked and used by spammers.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SCHEMES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Deceptive plans or operations used by con artists and scammers to illicitly obtain money from individuals.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WARNING SIGN">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">An indicator or clue, such as discrepancies in paperwork, that suggests a potential fraud or problem with a deal.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPLAINT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of formally reporting a problem or dissatisfaction with a savings account to the CFPB, either online at consumerfinance.gov/complaint or by calling (855) 411-2372.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="PEOPLE YOU DON'T KNOW">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Unknown individuals whose requests for money or involvement in deals should be treated with extreme caution due to high fraud risk.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL LOSS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The depletion or reduction of an individual's money or assets, often a consequence of falling victim to scams or fraudulent schemes.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FAKE EMAIL">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">An email designed to impersonate a legitimate sender, used by scammers for phishing to steal personal information or install malware.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EMAIL SPAM">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Unsolicited and often deceptive electronic messages, typically used by spammers as a method for phishing or spreading malware.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EMAIL ATTACHMENTS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Files appended to emails, which can be dangerous if unexpected or from unknown senders, as they may contain viruses.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HACKED">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The state of having unauthorized access gained to a digital system or account, often affecting email addresses used by spammers.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FAKE WEBSITES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Fraudulent websites designed to mimic legitimate ones, used by scammers to trick users into revealing personal or financial information.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SPAMMERS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals or entities that send unsolicited mass messages, often with malicious intent to spread scams or malware.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INVESTING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of committing money or capital to an asset with the expectation of generating income or profit, often misrepresented by scammers.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SOCIAL MEDIA">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The use of online platforms for social interaction and sharing of information, which scammers may exploit to request personal data.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CLICKING ON LINKS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of selecting a hyperlink on a webpage or within an email, a risky action if the link is malicious and leads to fake websites or malware.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL HARDSHIP">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A state where an individual struggles to meet financial obligations, potentially qualifying for temporary repayment options like deferment or forbearance on student loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TEMPORARY REPAYMENT OPTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A category of options available to borrowers to temporarily stop or reduce student loan payments, including deferment and forbearance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOAN SERVICER">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An entity responsible for managing loan accounts, including processing payments, providing information on repayment plans, and handling inquiries for both federal and private loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">9</data>
</node>
<node id="DEFERMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A temporary option that allows borrowers to stop making principal and interest payments on their student loans. For subsidized federal loans, the government pays the interest during this period; for unsubsidized loans, interest accrues.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="FORBEARANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A temporary option that allows borrowers to stop or reduce monthly student loan payments. Interest accrues during this period. Available for federal student loans and often offered by private student loan lenders.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="PRIVATE STUDENT LOAN LENDERS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial entities distinct from the federal government that offer student loans and may also provide temporary repayment options like forbearance.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SUBSIDIZED FEDERAL LOAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of federal loan where the government pays the interest during approved deferment periods, preventing interest from accruing for the borrower.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="GOVERNMENT">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The overarching authority that can be owed debts or provide benefits and protections related to garnishment, encompassing federal, state, and local levels.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="UNSUBSIDIZED LOAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of loan where the borrower is responsible for paying any accruing interest during deferment, or it will be added to the principal balance.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PRINCIPAL LOAN AMOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The original sum of money borrowed on a loan, distinct from the interest, whose payment can be temporarily delayed during a deferment.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CAPITALIZATION OF INTEREST">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A process where unpaid accrued interest is added to the principal loan amount, leading to the borrower paying interest on interest and ultimately owing more.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COLLEGE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A major life event and educational pursuit that often serves as a long-term financial goal, requiring significant savings and planning.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="TRADE SCHOOL">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An educational institution whose half-time enrollment can be a specific circumstance for granting deferment on student loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GRADUATE FELLOWSHIP">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A program or period of study at the graduate level that can qualify an individual for deferment on student loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REHABILITATION PROGRAM FOR INDIVIDUALS WITH DISABILITIES">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A program designed for individuals with disabilities that can qualify an individual for deferment on student loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UNEMPLOYMENT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A state of not having a job, which can be a specific circumstance for granting deferment on student loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MILITARY SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A period of active duty in the armed forces that can be a specific circumstance for granting deferment on student loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ECONOMIC HARDSHIP">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A severe financial difficulty affecting an individual or a region, which can be a specific circumstance for granting deferment on student loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PEACE CORPS SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A period of volunteer work with the Peace Corps that can be a specific circumstance for granting deferment on student loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL DIFFICULTIES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">General problems related to managing money, which can be a reason for a loan servicer to grant forbearance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MEDICAL EXPENSES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Medical expenses are costs associated with medical treatment, hospital stays, and rehabilitation for injuries, which can be covered by Bodily Injury Liability, Personal Injury Protection, or Medical Payments Coverage.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CHANGE IN EMPLOYMENT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A transition in one's job situation, which can be a reason for a loan servicer to grant forbearance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOSS OF JOB">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">An unexpected event where an individual becomes unemployed, significantly impacting their financial situation and requiring adjustment of financial goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="LOAN FORGIVENESS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A program where certain federal student loan amounts are cancelled, meaning the borrower no longer has to repay them, often due to disability, school closure, or specific types of employment.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SCHOOL CLOSURE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">An event where a school permanently closes or shuts down before a borrower completes their program, potentially qualifying the borrower for loan forgiveness.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="QUALIFIED PUBLIC SERVICE EMPLOYER">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An employer type, including government organizations or specific non-profits, working for whom can make an individual eligible for the Public Service Loan Forgiveness Program.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="STUDENTAID.ED.GOV">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A website (studentaid.ed.gov) provided by the U.S. Department of Education, offering information on federal student aid, including loan forgiveness programs.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="TEACHER LOAN FORGIVENESS PROGRAM">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A federal program offering loan forgiveness for teachers who have taught full-time for five consecutive academic years in a low-income school or educational service agency, up to $17,500.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DIRECT LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of federal student loan that may be eligible for forgiveness under programs like the Teacher Loan Forgiveness Program or Public Service Loan Forgiveness Program.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="STAFFORD LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of federal student loan that may be eligible for forgiveness under programs like the Teacher Loan Forgiveness Program.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DIRECT CONSOLIDATION LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of federal loan formed by combining multiple federal student loans, which can be eligible for forgiveness in certain cases under the Teacher Loan Forgiveness Program.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEDERAL CONSOLIDATION LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of federal loan formed by combining multiple federal student loans, which can be eligible for forgiveness in certain cases under the Teacher Loan Forgiveness Program.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PUBLIC SERVICE LOAN FORGIVENESS PROGRAM">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A federal program that may forgive the remaining balance of Direct Loans for individuals working full-time for a qualifying government or non-profit organization and making 120 qualifying monthly payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GOVERNMENT ORGANIZATION">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of employer that qualifies individuals for the Public Service Loan Forgiveness Program.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NON-PROFIT">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of employer that qualifies individuals for the Public Service Loan Forgiveness Program.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EMPLOYMENT CERTIFICATION FORM">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A document that must be completed and submitted to verify employment for eligibility in programs like the Public Service Loan Forgiveness Program.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="THIRD-PARTY DEBT COLLECTORS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of debt collector to whom companies may assign or sell overdue debts for collection.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FAIR DEBT COLLECTIONS PRACTICES ACT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A federal law that provides specific rights to consumers regarding how debt collectors must operate and what actions they are prohibited from taking when collecting a debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="LAWYER">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal professional who can advise individuals on their rights and responsibilities regarding garnishment and debt collection, and represent them in court.</data>
  <data key="d2">10</data>
</node>
<node id="STOP MAKING PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A temporary action allowed under deferment or forbearance, where a borrower ceases regular loan payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REDUCE PAYMENT AMOUNT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A temporary action allowed under forbearance, where a borrower decreases the usual loan payment amount.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MAKING PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The regular act of repaying a loan, which may be temporarily stopped or reduced under certain repayment options.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAY INTEREST">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of covering the cost of borrowing money, required of borrowers on unsubsidized loans during deferment and on all loans during forbearance to avoid capitalization.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WORK FULL-TIME">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">An employment status required for eligibility in programs such as the Teacher Loan Forgiveness Program and Public Service Loan Forgiveness Program.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MAKE QUALIFYING MONTHLY PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Specific loan payments that must be made for a certain period (e.g., 120 payments) to qualify for programs like the Public Service Loan Forgiveness Program.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SUBMIT EMPLOYMENT CERTIFICATION FORM">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of sending in a required document to verify employment for eligibility in loan forgiveness programs.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HARASSMENT BY DEBT COLLECTORS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">An illegal action by debt collectors, such as calling repeatedly, as prohibited by the Fair Debt Collections Practices Act.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ABUSIVE LANGUAGE BY DEBT COLLECTORS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">An illegal action by debt collectors, such as using obscene language, as prohibited by the Fair Debt Collections Practices Act.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="THREATS BY DEBT COLLECTORS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">An illegal action by debt collectors, such as threatening to take action they can't or don't intend to, as prohibited by the Fair Debt Collections Practices Act.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DECEPTION BY DEBT COLLECTORS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">An illegal action by debt collectors, such as lying or misleading, as prohibited by the Fair Debt Collections Practices Act.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PUBLISHING NAME FOR DEBT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">An illegal action by debt collectors, where they publish a person's name for not paying a debt, as prohibited by the Fair Debt Collections Practices Act.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEED OF TRUST">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal document used in some states to secure a real estate loan, requiring contact with the lending institution, similar to a mortgage.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOAN IN DEFAULT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The state where a borrower has failed to meet the terms and conditions of a loan agreement, potentially leading to consequences like foreclosure.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCOUNT HOLDER">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">The individual or entity legally owning a financial account, whose name is included in account statements.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCOUNT NUMBER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A unique identifier assigned to a financial account, used to track transactions and balances, and often requested for debt verification.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="CONTACT PHONE NUMBERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Telephone numbers provided for communication, especially for financial institutions or reporting lost/stolen cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCOUNTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">General term for financial holdings, such as bank accounts or credit card accounts, for which statements are provided.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ELECTRIC">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of utility service, proof of payment for which can demonstrate residence.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WATER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of utility service, proof of payment for which can demonstrate residence.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GAS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The cost of fuel, typically for transportation, an example of a living expense not usually covered by public benefits but can be paid with freed-up cash.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PROOF OF UTILITY PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Documentation showing that payments have been made for utility services, used as evidence of residence.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PROOF OF RESIDENCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Documentation used to verify an individual's current living address, often required for assistance or services.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="LOAN AGREEMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A formal contract between a lender and a borrower outlining the terms and conditions of a loan, including repayment schedule and fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="ROUTING NUMBER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A nine-digit code that identifies the financial institution when processing electronic transactions, such as for bank accounts or credit cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="VERIFICATION CODES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Security codes used to authenticate transactions or identify credit cards, such as CVV codes.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYMENT AGREEMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A contract that specifies the terms of regular payments for various obligations like alimony, child support, or elder care facilities.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHECK STUBS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Portions of checks retained by the payer as a record of payment, useful for documenting child support or other payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RECEIPTS OF PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Written acknowledgments that a payment has been received, serving as proof of transaction for various financial obligations.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OTHER ASSETS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Valuable possessions or resources owned by an individual, beyond typical financial accounts, that can be converted into cash.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCOUNT STATEMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Periodic summaries provided by financial institutions detailing account activity, balances, and transactions, available in paper or electronic format.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="BANKING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The activity of managing financial affairs at a bank, including deposits, withdrawals, and other transactions, often done online.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL BUSINESS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Activities related to managing money, investments, and other financial assets or obligations, often conducted online.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EMERGENCY FINANCIAL FIRST AID KIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A kit or collection of an individual's financial, legal, and contact information, designed for emergency preparedness, and referred to as EFFAK. It is crucial to keep this information safe and secure.</data>
  <data key="d2">8</data>
</node>
<node id="POLICY NUMBERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Unique identifiers assigned to insurance policies, used for claims and administration.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CLAIMS NUMBERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Specific contact numbers provided by insurance companies for reporting and processing insurance claims.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INSURANCE POLICIES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Contracts that provide financial protection against various potential future losses, requiring regular review for accuracy and currency to ensure adequate emergency support.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="RIDERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Optional additions or modifications to an insurance policy that provide extra coverage or alter its terms.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="POLICY COVERAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The scope of protection provided by an insurance policy, detailing what risks or losses are covered and to what extent.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CLAIMS CALL NUMBER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific telephone number to contact an insurance provider for initiating or inquiring about claims.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PHOTOS OF PROPERTY AND CONTENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Visual documentation of assets, often kept for insurance purposes, especially for valuable items.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="VALUABLE ITEMS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Items of significant monetary worth, which may be separately covered by insurance due to their high value.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PROFESSIONAL APPRAISALS OF PERSONAL PROPERTY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Evaluations conducted by experts to determine the monetary value of personal possessions, used for insurance or estate planning.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FLOOD DAMAGE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Physical harm or destruction caused by flooding, often not covered by standard homeowners insurance and requiring specific flood insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SOURCES OF INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Means by which individuals receive money, important to document as proof of income for disaster assistance.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="PAY STUBS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Documents provided by an employer to an employee, detailing earnings and deductions for a specific pay period, serving as proof of income.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="EMERGENCY">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">An Emergency is an unforeseen and urgent financial situation that requires immediate attention and can deplete financial resources if not prepared for.</data>
  <data key="d2">8</data>
</node>
<node id="GRANTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Non-repayable funds disbursed by a grantor, often a government department, corporation, foundation or trust, to a recipient, often a non-profit entity, educational institution, business or an individual, for a specific purpose.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL AID">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Monetary assistance provided to students for educational expenses, which does not need to be repaid, or other forms of financial support.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAPER CHECKS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Physical checks used as a method of payment, as opposed to electronic transfers, specifically mentioned for federal benefits.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="AUTOMATIC BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Government benefits that are received through an automated system, typically via direct deposit, as encouraged by programs like Go Direct.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FREQUENT FLYER PROGRAMS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Loyalty programs offered by airlines to reward regular travelers with benefits like free flights or upgrades, a type of rewards account.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HOTEL REWARDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Loyalty programs offered by hotel chains to reward frequent guests with benefits like free stays or upgrades, a type of rewards account.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TAX STATEMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Documents provided by tax authorities or financial institutions detailing tax-related information, such as income, deductions, or property taxes.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="NEW LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Additional credit or borrowed money applied for, often requiring previous tax returns as part of the application process.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INCOME-BASED ASSISTANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial support programs where eligibility and the amount of assistance are determined by an individual's or household's income level.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TAX EXPERTS">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Professionals knowledgeable in tax law and regulations who provide advice and assistance with tax-related matters, recommending record retention.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TAX RETURNS AND RECORDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">All documents related to an individual's or entity's tax filings, including the returns themselves and supporting records, recommended to be kept for seven years.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CAR TAX">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific tax levied on vehicles, often referred to as personal property tax, requiring a statement.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ESTATE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The sum of an individual's assets, including property, money, and other valuable items, less their liabilities, used in discussions of wills and inheritance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT BUREAU">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An organization that collects and reports information about consumers' creditworthiness, which debt collectors may report disputed debts to.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBTOR">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">The individual who owes the debt and is requesting information from or disputing the debt with the debt collector, as represented by the "Name" in the letter template.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="INSURER">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A company that provides health insurance coverage, determining what medical procedures and costs are covered for the debtor.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="HEALTHCARE PROVIDER">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An entity, such as a hospital or doctor's office, that delivers medical services, performs procedures, and issues bills, which may lead to medical debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDITOR">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The party to whom a debt is currently owed, or the original party from whom the debt originated. The text requests information about the name, address, account number, and amount owed to the creditor.</data>
  <data key="d2">13</data>
</node>
<node id="LOAN APPLICATION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The formal process by which an individual requests a loan from a lender, involving the submission of financial information for assessment, including debt-to-income ratios.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="THIRD-PARTY COLLECTION AGENCY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An external organization that a healthcare provider or creditor may turn over unpaid debt to for collection purposes.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CHARITY CARE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial assistance programs offered by hospitals to patients who are unable to pay their medical bills, often requiring application within a specific timeframe.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MEDICAL PROCEDURE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A medical intervention or test performed by a healthcare provider, which generates medical bills and potentially medical debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="RISK">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The potential for negative consequences, such as financial loss from high-interest debt, damage to credit scores, or ineligibility for payment plans.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT COLLECTION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process and practice of pursuing and obtaining payments of debts owed by individuals or businesses, often carried out by debt collectors.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="BILL DISPUTE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of formally challenging or questioning the accuracy or validity of a medical bill or debt by sending a written notice to the provider.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="BILL NEGOTIATION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of discussing and agreeing upon a reduced or alternative payment arrangement for a bill with a healthcare provider, possibly including installment plans.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MEDICAL BILL PAYMENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of settling financial obligations for medical services received, which can be done directly, through payment plans, or via credit cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="COLLECTION AGENCY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A Collection Agency is a business that pursues payment of debts owed by individuals or businesses to another entity or creditor.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT DISPUTE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The formal process initiated by a debtor to challenge the validity or accuracy of a debt, typically through written communication with the debt collector.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PHONE CONTACT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A method of communication, specifically by telephone, used by debt collectors to reach debtors.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MAIL CONTACT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A method of communication, specifically by postal mail, used by debt collectors to send notices or bills to debtors.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MEDICAL BILL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A detailed statement of charges for medical services, treatments, or procedures, issued by a healthcare provider, which can be reviewed, disputed, and paid.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OUT-OF-POCKET COST">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The portion of medical expenses that an individual must pay directly from their own funds, not covered by health insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EXPLANATION OF BENEFITS (EOB)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A document provided by an insurance company that explains what medical services were paid for, the amount the insurer covered, and the patient's remaining financial responsibility.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DATE OF SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The specific date on which a particular medical service or treatment was provided to a patient by a healthcare provider.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HOSPITAL">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A medical institution that provides various healthcare services, often directly associated with providers who bill for services rendered during treatment.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="DOCTOR'S OFFICE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A facility or practice where physicians provide medical consultations, examinations, and treatments, issuing bills for their services.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ITEMIZED BILL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A comprehensive medical bill that provides a line-by-line breakdown of every service, procedure, and item charged, along with its specific cost.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BILLING ERROR">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">An inaccuracy or mistake on a medical bill, such as a typographical error or mis-categorization of services, leading to incorrect charges.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYMENT PLAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An arrangement offered by healthcare providers or creditors to allow debtors to pay off their bills in regular, agreed-upon installments, potentially with little or no interest.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="CASH DISCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A reduced price offered by a healthcare provider if a patient pays the entire amount of their medical bill upfront in cash or a single payment.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PROMPT PAYMENT DISCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A reduction in the total bill amount offered by a provider to encourage quick payment, typically by a specified early deadline.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INSTALLMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Partial payments made at regular intervals to gradually pay off an outstanding debt or bill, often as part of a payment or repayment plan.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="MONTHLY STATEMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A periodic report, typically sent monthly, to a debtor detailing payments made and the remaining outstanding balance on a debt or repayment plan.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT SERVICING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The administrative process of managing and collecting payments for a debt, ideally retained by the original healthcare provider to avoid transfer to a third-party collection agency.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DELAY PAYMENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of failing to pay a bill or debt by its due date, which can result in additional charges like late fees, accrual of interest, and negative impacts on credit scores if the debt enters collections.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL ASSISTANCE PROGRAM">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Programs offered by hospitals, such as charity care, designed to help patients who are unable to afford the full cost of their medical bills, often with specific application deadlines.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ENROLLMENT DEADLINES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The specific cutoff dates by which applications for financial assistance programs or charity care must be submitted to be considered for eligibility.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FOCUS ON REENTRY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A program or set of guides designed to help individuals manage their finances before, during, and after incarceration, offering tools for financial decision-making.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INCARCERATION">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The state of being confined in jail or prison, presenting financial challenges for individuals who need to prepare their finances.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="REENTRY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of an individual returning to society after incarceration, which includes navigating financial adjustments and obtaining identification documents.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT FREEZE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial tool used to restrict access to a credit report, protecting against potential fraud or identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="POWER OF ATTORNEY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal instrument granting an appointed agent the authority to make decisions or act on behalf of another person, particularly in financial or medical matters, often related to EFFAK access.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="SOCIAL SECURITY CARDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Official identification documents crucial for establishing financial identity and accessing services in the U.S.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CRIMINAL JUSTICE-RELATED DEBT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial obligations arising from involvement with the criminal justice system, such as fines, fees, or restitution.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMER DEBT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Debts incurred by individuals for personal, family, or household purposes, distinct from criminal justice-related obligations.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="TAKE HOME SALARY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The net amount of pay an employee receives after all deductions (taxes, benefits, etc.) have been withheld from their gross pay.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CORRECTIONAL FACILITIES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Institutions such as jails or prisons where individuals are confined, and where financial tasks like monitoring credit reports may still be necessary.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="BACKGROUND SCREENING PROCESS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A procedure employers use to verify information provided by job applicants and assess their suitability, impacting an individual's rights when applying for jobs.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PUBLIC ARCHIVE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A repository that stores older versions of web pages and content, providing historical information.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MEASURING FINANCIAL WELL-BEING TOOL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool provided within the "Focus on Reentry" program to help individuals assess their financial health.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PREPARING YOUR MONEY SITUATION TOOL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool from "Focus on Reentry" to guide individuals in managing their finances before or during incarceration.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REENTRY DEBT LOG TOOL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool from "Focus on Reentry" designed to help individuals track and manage debts specifically related to their reentry into society.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REQUESTING YOUR FREE CREDIT REPORT TOOL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A guide from "Focus on Reentry" providing instructions on how to obtain a free credit report, including options for those in correctional facilities.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OPENING A CHECKING OR SAVINGS ACCOUNT TOOL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A guide from "Focus on Reentry" on the process and requirements for opening a bank or credit union account.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EVALUATING YOUR PREPAID OR PAYROLL CARD TOOL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A guide from "Focus on Reentry" to help individuals understand and assess prepaid or payroll cards for financial transactions.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="IDENTITY THEFT HANDOUT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A handout from "Focus on Reentry" providing guidance on how to manage and address identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SUBMITTING A COMPLAINT HANDOUT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A handout from "Focus on Reentry" detailing the process for submitting a complaint about financial products or services.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NEWCOMER’S GUIDES TO MANAGING MONEY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A series of guides providing straightforward financial information and tips for recent immigrants and people new to the U.S. banking system.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LIMITED ENGLISH PROFICIENCY">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A characteristic describing individuals who have difficulty communicating effectively in English, which can increase their vulnerability to financial frauds and schemes.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FRAUDS AND SCHEMES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Deceptive practices or plots designed to trick individuals out of money or assets, often targeting vulnerable populations like those with limited English proficiency.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="IMMIGRANTS">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals who have come to live permanently in a foreign country, specifically referring to recent immigrants to the U.S. who may need financial guidance.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="U.S. BANKING SYSTEM">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The network of banks, credit unions, and other financial institutions and regulations operating within the United States.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL PRODUCT (GENERIC)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A broad term referring to various types of financial instruments or offerings provided by financial institutions, such as loans, accounts, or insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL SERVICE (GENERIC)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Services provided by the finance industry, such as banking, investing, and wealth management.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHECK">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial instrument used to make payments by instructing a bank to pay a specific amount from the account holder's funds, which can result in fees if it bounces due to insufficient funds.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A plastic card, such as a debit, credit, prepaid, or payroll card, used for financial transactions or receiving payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MONEY ORDER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A secure, pre-funded payment instrument, similar to a check, used to guarantee payment up to a certain amount, typically available without a checking account.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="DIRECT DEBIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An arrangement with a bank that allows a third party to automatically withdraw money from an account, typically for recurring bill payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ATM CASH WITHDRAWALS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of taking out physical cash from an Automated Teller Machine, a common financial transaction.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBIT CARD PURCHASES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Transactions made using a debit card, where funds are directly deducted from a linked bank account.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMER PROTECTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Rules and regulations designed to safeguard the rights and interests of individuals when using financial products and services, such as payroll cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPLAINT SYSTEM (GENERIC)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A formal process or mechanism for individuals to register grievances or problems concerning financial products or services.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COLLISION COVERAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Collision coverage is a type of auto insurance that covers damage to your own car resulting from it overturning or an accident with another vehicle or object, applying regardless of who is at fault and often involving a deductible.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPREHENSIVE COVERAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">This coverage helps pay for loss of or damage to a covered vehicle not caused by a collision or vehicle rollover, including risks like fire, wind, hail, flood, vandalism, theft, or hitting an animal. It usually requires a deductible, but a no-deductible option may be available.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="UNINSURED MOTORIST COVERAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">This coverage helps pay for damages if an insured person is injured in an auto crash or struck as a pedestrian by a driver who does not have liability insurance. It may also cover property damage in some states, varies by state and policy, and does not typically require a deductible.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="UNDERINSURED MOTORIST COVERAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">This coverage helps pay for damages if an insured person is injured in an auto crash or struck as a pedestrian by a driver considered underinsured as defined by the policy. It varies by state and policy and is subject to a policy limit chosen by the insured.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="RENTAL REIMBURSEMENT COVERAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">This coverage helps pay for rental expenses if a car is disabled due to a covered loss, with daily allowances based on selected coverage.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EMERGENCY ROADSIDE SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">This coverage helps pay for roadside assistance, such as towing a vehicle due to a breakdown or getting back into a locked car.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RIDESHARE DRIVER COVERAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">This coverage extends an existing personal auto policy to cover personal vehicle use for a rideshare company like Lyft or Uber, with state-specific variations and requirements.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEDUCTIBLE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A deductible is the predetermined amount of money that an insured person agrees to pay out-of-pocket for a covered insurance claim before their insurer begins to pay the remaining costs, and it influences premium amounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="POLICY LIMIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A policy limit is the maximum amount an insurance policy will pay for a specific type of coverage, often chosen by the insured, such as for uninsured motorist coverage.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FIRE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Fire is an event that can cause damage or loss to a covered vehicle, and is typically covered under comprehensive auto insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="WIND">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Wind is a weather event that can cause damage or loss to a covered vehicle, and is typically covered under comprehensive auto insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="HAIL">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Hail is a weather event that can cause damage or loss to a covered vehicle, and is typically covered under comprehensive auto insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FLOOD">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Flood is a natural disaster event involving water damage or loss to a covered vehicle, and is typically covered under comprehensive auto insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="VANDALISM">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Vandalism is an act of malicious destruction or damage inflicted upon a covered vehicle, and is typically covered under comprehensive auto insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="THEFT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk of money being stolen, particularly electronically, which may be protected by federal rights. Money orders can be cancelled or reissued if stolen.</data>
  <data key="d2">8</data>
</node>
<node id="HITTING AN ANIMAL">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Hitting an animal is an incident where a covered vehicle collides with an animal, causing damage, and is typically covered under comprehensive auto insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="AUTO CRASH">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">An auto crash is a specific type of accident involving vehicles, often resulting in injuries or damages, and is a key event covered by various auto insurance policies like Personal Injury Protection and Medical Payments Coverage.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="BREAKDOWN">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">An event causing a vehicle to become inoperable, for which Emergency Roadside Service can provide assistance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COVERED LOSS">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A general term for an event or damage for which insurance coverage applies, such as a disabled car leading to rental reimbursement.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UNINSURED DRIVER">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A driver who does not have liability insurance, posing a risk that Uninsured Motorist coverage helps address.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UNDERINSURED DRIVER">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A driver considered to be underinsured as defined by policy, posing a risk that Underinsured Motorist coverage helps address.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DISABLED CAR">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A vehicle that is inoperable due to a covered loss, for which Rental Reimbursement coverage helps pay for rental expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LYFT">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A rideshare company whose drivers can extend their personal auto policy with Rideshare Driver Coverage.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UBER">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A rideshare company whose drivers can extend their personal auto policy with Rideshare Driver Coverage.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOCAL INSURANCE AGENT">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">A professional who can be contacted for current quotes and personalized service regarding insurance needs.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INSURED">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">The insured is the individual who purchases an auto insurance policy and is covered by its provisions, being responsible for selecting coverage limits and paying deductibles.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="AUTO + RENTERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A bundled insurance product offered by State Farm, combining auto and renters insurance, listed as a selectable option for starting a quote.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="MEDICARE SUPPLEMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific insurance product offered by State Farm for Medicare Supplement, listed as a selectable option for starting a quote.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="CONTACT US">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">An action for customers to get in touch with State Farm.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RATING PLANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Methods or formulas used by insurance companies to determine premiums, which vary by state and influence the cost of insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="COVERAGE LIMITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Coverage limits are the maximum amounts that an insurance policy will pay out for specific types of damages or losses under a given coverage.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="LIABILITIES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Liabilities refer to an individual's legal responsibility for damages or injuries to others, often covered by specific insurance policies like liability insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="DISCOUNTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Reductions in the standard cost of insurance premiums. These are a primary benefit of bundling, where multiple policies can "stack" discounts, such as multiline and multi-car discounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="APPLYING FOR CAR INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of seeking and obtaining car insurance coverage.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UNITED STATES">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">The country from which money transfers abroad are regulated by federal law, requiring specific disclosures from remittance transfer providers.</data>
  <data key="d2">8</data>
</node>
