<node id="MONEY TRANSFER SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Organizations that facilitate the transfer of funds, often competing with card providers for inter-card transfers and subject to federal protections when sending money abroad.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="SAVINGS WALLET FEATURE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific capability, often part of a prepaid card, that allows users to designate and set aside a portion of their funds specifically for savings goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="CARDHOLDER AGREEMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal contract between the card issuer and the cardholder, detailing the rights, responsibilities, policies, terms, and specific conditions for using the card.</data>
  <data key="d2">8</data>
</node>
<node id="GOVERNMENT-ARRANGED PREPAID CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A prepaid card chosen or provided by a government agency for the efficient and mandated distribution of benefits.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="UNAUTHORIZED TRANSACTION">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial activity on a prepaid card that was not approved by the cardholder, for which protections exist if the card is registered and the transaction is reported promptly.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="ERROR">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial risk or mistake occurring during a transaction, for which federal protections may offer recourse if reported promptly.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="SNAP">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program, a needs-tested government benefit administered by state or local governments, which may have limited fraud and error protections when provided on a prepaid card.</data>
  <data key="d2">11</data>
</node>
<node id="TANF">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The Temporary Assistance for Needy Families program, a needs-tested government benefit administered by state or local governments, potentially lacking full fraud and error protections on prepaid cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">11</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE OR LOCAL GOVERNMENT">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Government entities responsible for administering certain needs-tested benefits like SNAP and TANF, sometimes distributing them via prepaid cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEDERAL GOVERNMENT">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The central government responsible for administering certain benefits like SSI and establishing federal laws that provide protections for financial services and consumers.</data>
  <data key="d2">12</data>
</node>
<node id="SSI">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Supplemental Security Income, a specific needs-tested program administered by the Federal Government, whose benefits can be loaded onto government benefits cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="REMITTANCE TRANSFER PROVIDERS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A category of financial organizations (including money-transfer companies, banks, credit unions, and other financial services companies) that facilitate sending money to other countries, subject to specific federal disclosure requirements.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="EXCHANGE RATE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The rate at which the currency sent in a money transfer is converted into the foreign currency to be received, which must be disclosed by the provider.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="TAXES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Government levies associated with a money transfer, potentially paid by the sender or deducted from the amount received by the recipient in a foreign country.</data>
  <data key="d2">10</data>
</node>
<node id="OVERDRAFT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A situation where an account transaction exceeds the available balance, leading to the bank covering the transaction and potentially incurring fees for the account holder.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="CHECKS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Written orders instructing a bank to pay a specific sum of money from a checking account to a named payee. There may be a cost associated with ordering checks or per-check transaction fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="ONLINE BANKING">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A service that allows customers to manage their bank accounts and perform transactions over the internet. Access may come with a cost and often includes features like online bill paying and account monitoring.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="ONLINE BILL PAYING SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A feature typically integrated into online banking platforms that enables customers to electronically pay bills from their bank account. This service may incur costs.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="OPENING AN ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of establishing a new checking or savings account with a bank or credit union. This typically requires identification, supporting documents, and an initial deposit, and involves understanding the terms and associated costs.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="MINIMUM BALANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The smallest amount of money a borrower is required to pay on a debt each month. Paying only this amount can make it difficult to significantly reduce overall debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="MOBILE APP">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A software application provided by banks or credit unions for smartphones or tablets, allowing customers to monitor their account balances, transactions, and manage their finances on the go.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="TRACKING ACCOUNT BALANCE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The proactive process of monitoring the amount of money available in a checking or savings account, either manually or via online/mobile banking, to prevent overdrafts and avoid fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ASSET LIMITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Rules that define the maximum value of assets an individual can possess to qualify for and maintain eligibility for certain public benefits, which can vary by program and state.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="INSURANCE DEDUCTIBLE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The out-of-pocket amount an insured person must pay before their insurance coverage starts, which an emergency fund can help cover.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GENERAL EDUCATIONAL DEVELOPMENT (GED) TEST">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A high school equivalency examination, identified as a goal for which individuals may save for education or training.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TAX-ADVANTAGED">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A characteristic of certain financial products, like a 529 savings plan, that offers specific tax benefits to encourage saving.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT BUILDING PRODUCTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial instruments specifically designed to help individuals establish or improve their credit history, such as secured credit cards or credit builder loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SECURED CREDIT CARDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of credit card that requires an upfront cash deposit as collateral, making it accessible to those with limited or no credit history and serving as a tool to build credit.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DEPOSIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A sum of money paid upfront as a guarantee or collateral, as is typically required for a secured credit card.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT LIMITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The maximum amount of money that a credit card issuer or lender will allow a borrower to charge or borrow.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT UTILIZATION RATE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The ratio of the amount of credit a consumer is using compared to the total credit limit available on their credit accounts, often advised to be kept below 30% to maintain a good credit score.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="GETTING TOO CLOSE TO USING THE FULL LIMIT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The financial risk associated with a high credit utilization rate, which can negatively impact an individual's credit score and indicate financial strain.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OPEN A SECURED CREDIT CARD">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of applying for and activating a new secured credit card account.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT BUILDER LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Loans specifically designed to help individuals establish or improve their credit by making regular payments, often with the loan amount disbursed only after the loan is fully paid off.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="TAKING ON DEBT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of borrowing money or incurring financial obligations, which can be a risk if not managed properly, potentially leading to financial strain.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYMENT RECORD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A documented history of an individual's timely and consistent fulfillment of financial obligations, crucial for building a positive credit profile.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="LOAN AMOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The principal sum of money borrowed in a loan, onto which interest and costs of add-on products are typically incorporated.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="NON-PROFIT ORGANIZATIONS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Entities that operate for charitable, educational, religious, or other public service purposes rather than for profit, some of which provide financial literacy and access to credit-building tools.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="TERMS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The specific conditions, rules, and agreements governing a financial product or service, including interest rates, fees, and repayment schedules.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="BUILD A POSITIVE CREDIT HISTORY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The ongoing process of establishing a strong and favorable track record of responsible credit usage and timely payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="AVOID TAKING ON DEBT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The deliberate decision or strategy to prevent or minimize the accumulation of new financial obligations.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MAKE MONTHLY PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The regular act of remitting required installment payments on a loan or credit product, typically on a monthly basis.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RECEIVE THE LOAN AMOUNT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of obtaining the principal sum of money that was borrowed, often after fulfilling certain conditions or payment schedules (as with credit builder loans).</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ASK ABOUT THE TERMS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of inquiring about and seeking clarification on the specific conditions and details of a financial product or service.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EQUIFAX">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">One of the three major nationwide credit reporting companies in the United States, responsible for collecting and maintaining consumer credit information and providing credit reports and scores. It offers additional free credit reports through its "myEquifax" platform.</data>
  <data key="d2">14</data>
</node>
<node id="EXPERIAN">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">One of the three major nationwide credit reporting companies; it allows minors age 14 and older (or their guardians) to obtain their own credit report, and guardians of minors 13 and under to request reports by mail or electronically.</data>
  <data key="d2">14</data>
</node>
<node id="TRANSUNION">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">One of the three major nationwide credit reporting companies; it allows parents or legal guardians to order a minor’s credit report if the minor has a legitimate credit history, and provides an email and a Child Identity Theft Inquiry Form for such purposes.</data>
  <data key="d2">14</data>
</node>
<node id="REQUESTING CREDIT REPORTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process by which individuals obtain copies of their credit reports from credit reporting companies, which can be done online, by phone, or via mail through federally authorized channels like AnnualCreditReport.com.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SENSITIVE PERSONAL INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Private data, such as financial account numbers and personal identifiers, that must be protected to prevent misuse, identity theft, or fraud, especially when accessing financial records.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MONITORING CREDIT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The proactive practice of regularly checking one's credit reports and scores for any changes, inaccuracies, or suspicious activity that could indicate fraud or identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="REVIEWING CREDIT REPORTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of carefully examining the details within a credit report to verify accuracy, identify potential errors, and look for signs of fraud or identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="ANNUALCREDITREPORT.COM">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The only website authorized by federal law to provide consumers with one free copy of their credit report from each of the three major credit reporting companies every 12 months.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="ANNUAL CREDIT REPORT REQUEST SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The service responsible for processing physical mail requests for free annual credit reports, with a mailing address in Atlanta, Georgia.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ATLANTA">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">A major city in the state of Georgia, USA, which serves as the mailing address for the Annual Credit Report Request Service.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="GEORGIA">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">A state in the southeastern United States, home to the city of Atlanta where the Annual Credit Report Request Service's mailing address is located.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="ERRORS ON CREDIT REPORTS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Mistakes or incorrect information present on a credit report that can negatively impact an individual's credit score and their ability to obtain loans or other financial products, and may indicate fraud.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="DISPUTING ERRORS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Disputing Errors is the formal process of challenging incorrect or fraudulent information found on a credit report with credit reporting companies and the original furnishers of that information.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="MYEQUIFAX">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A secure online platform provided by Equifax that allows consumers to establish an account, access their credit reports, and monitor their credit activity, offering six free reports every 12 months.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="CAR PAYMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A regular monetary installment paid towards an auto loan, which may be used as a security verification question when requesting credit reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCURATE INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Verified and correct data found within credit reports, which is crucial for maintaining a healthy credit score and financial standing.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MANUAL REQUEST FORM">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A downloadable physical form from AnnualCreditReport.com that consumers can complete and mail to request their free credit reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OLDER ACCOUNTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial accounts that have been open for a long period, which may not always be consistently listed across all three nationwide credit reporting companies' reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CLOSED ACCOUNTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A general category of financial accounts that an individual previously held but are no longer active, whose details are included in account information reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="INCONSISTENCIES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Differences or discrepancies in information across credit reports from the various credit reporting companies, which can result from varying reporting practices.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHECKLIST">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A structured guide used by consumers to methodically review their credit reports for potential errors or inaccuracies.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EQUIFAX.COM">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The official website of Equifax, where consumers can access credit reports, create a "myEquifax" account, and manage other credit-related services.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="UNAPPROVED ACCESS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A risk that refers to unauthorized entry or use of one's financial accounts, which can be detected by reviewing credit reports and scores, and is a potential sign of identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PERSONAL SECURITY QUESTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Questions used to verify an individual's identity for electronic banking, bill paying, purchasing, and other financial activities, providing an additional layer of protection alongside passwords and PINs.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEPOSITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Upfront payments required by service providers (e.g., landlords, utility companies), the amount of which can be higher for individuals with poor credit histories.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPORTANT DOCUMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Valuable papers containing sensitive financial or personal information, such as those kept in an EFFAK, which require protection and immediate action if stolen or illegally accessed.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="UNAUTHORIZED ACTIVITY">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Any transaction or action performed on an account without the account holder's permission, specifically mentioned in the context of debit or ATM cards and covered by the Electronic Fund Transfer Act.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCOUNT INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Details related to a financial account, such as account numbers, which are crucial to provide when reporting the loss of a card to a financial institution.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="NEW ACCOUNT NUMBERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Replacement account numbers issued by financial institutions as a security measure, especially after an account has been compromised or its documents stolen.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REPORT LOSS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The immediate action of notifying a financial institution about the disappearance or theft of a debit or credit card, or other important financial documents.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHECK STATEMENTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The routine action of reviewing financial statements to identify any unapproved payments or deposits and to monitor account activity.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REVIEW CREDIT REPORT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The annual action of examining one's credit report and score to detect potential unapproved access to accounts and signs of identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHOOSE SECURE PASSWORDS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The critical action of selecting passwords that are difficult for others to guess or discover, essential for protecting accounts and personal identity.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONTACT FINANCIAL INSTITUTIONS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The immediate action of getting in touch with banks, credit card companies, and insurance agencies if an EFFAK or important documents are believed to be stolen or illegally accessed.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MODULE 2 SAVING">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific section within the Your Money, Your Goals Toolkit dedicated to the principles and strategies of saving money.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UNEXPECTED EXPENSES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Costs that arise suddenly and without prior anticipation, such as medical emergencies or car repairs, which can impact personal finances.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="SERVICES TURNED OFF">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The suspension of essential utilities or other services due to non-payment, often incurring extra costs for reconnection.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BORROW MONEY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of taking funds from a lender with the intention of repaying it, typically with interest, often backed by a deposit for secured credit cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="AMERICASAVES.ORG">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An organization cited as a source for recommendations regarding emergency fund target amounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PERIODIC EXPENSES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Costs that occur regularly but not necessarily monthly, such as annual insurance premiums or school supplies, requiring planned savings.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INCOME TAXES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Mandatory government levies on an individual's or entity's income, often requiring planned savings to pay.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INCOME FLUCTUATES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The variability or inconsistency in an individual's earnings over time, posing a financial challenge that saving can mitigate.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TECHNICAL TRAINING">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Specialized education focused on practical skills for a specific trade or occupation, often a long-term savings goal.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CERTIFICATES OF DEPOSIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of savings financial product where money is deposited for a fixed period at a fixed interest rate, used for saving for education.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="INVESTMENT PRODUCTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial instruments or vehicles used to invest money with the expectation of generating a return, including those specifically for education savings.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="529 SAVINGS PLAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A tax-advantaged savings plan designed to encourage saving for future education costs, managed by parents, guardians, or grandparents.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="SBA">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The Small Business Administration, a U.S. government agency that provides resources and guidance for small businesses on topics like disaster preparedness.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PERSONAL DISASTER PREPAREDNESS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The actions individuals take to prepare themselves and their families for potential disasters, including having necessary documents and resources ready.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="OTHER PHOTO ID">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A general category for any photo identification document not specifically named (e.g., driver's license, passport) used for proving identity.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE HEALTH OR SOCIAL SERVICES ADMINISTRATION OFFICE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Generic term for state-level government offices responsible for providing copies of vital records such as birth, adoption, death, marriage, and divorce certificates.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PROVE IDENTITY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of demonstrating or confirming who a person is, often through official documents, especially after a disaster.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MAINTAIN CONTACT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of staying in communication with family, employers, or other essential contacts, especially important during and after a disaster.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RE-ESTABLISH CONTACT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of restoring communication with family, employers, or other essential contacts after a disruption, such as a disaster.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="APPLY FOR DISASTER ASSISTANCE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of formally submitting a request for aid or support from government agencies or other organizations after an emergency or disaster.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="IDENTIFICATION DOCUMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A broad category encompassing various official papers and cards used to verify a person's identity, often crucial for post-disaster recovery efforts.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ATMS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Automated Teller Machines, which are self-service banking terminals often operated by financial institutions or networks, allowing customers to perform transactions like cash withdrawals or balance inquiries.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="FICO SCORE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of credit score used by lenders to assess a borrower's credit risk, crucial for preparing for emergency borrowing and potentially requiring improvement.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT SCORE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A numerical representation of an individual's creditworthiness, used by financial institutions to make lending decisions. It is calculated by scoring companies based on information in credit reports and typically ranges from 300 to 850.</data>
  <data key="d2">13</data>
</node>
<node id="LENDERS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals or financial institutions, such as banks or credit unions, that provide loans and credit cards, and use credit reports and scores to assess risk and determine terms.</data>
  <data key="d2">10</data>
</node>
<node id="RISK OF OFFERING CREDIT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The potential financial exposure or loss that lenders undertake when extending credit to borrowers, mitigated by assessing credit scores like the FICO Score.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EMERGENCY BORROWING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of obtaining funds, potentially under urgent circumstances, to cover unforeseen financial needs, for which a favorable credit score is highly beneficial.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="USA.GOV">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A U.S. government website that provides official information and services, including guidance and tips on property insurance like homeowners and renters insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="WILL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal document specifying how a person's assets and estate should be distributed after their death, recommended for inclusion in an Emergency Financial First Aid Kit.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LIVING WILL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal document that communicates a person's desires regarding medical treatment in situations where they are incapacitated, to be filed with healthcare providers.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LIFE INSURANCE POLICY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A contract where an insurer agrees to pay a designated beneficiary a sum of money upon the insured person's death, in exchange for premiums, recommended for review and inclusion in an EFFAK.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HEALTH INSURANCE PLAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of insurance coverage that assists in covering medical and surgical expenses for the insured individual, recommended for review and inclusion in an EFFAK.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BANK SAFE DEPOSIT BOX">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A secure storage container provided by banks for rent, used to safeguard valuable paper documents from an Emergency Financial First Aid Kit, subject to state laws regarding access.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE LAWS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Legal statutes enacted by state governments that dictate various regulations, including who can access a bank safe deposit box under specific circumstances like the owner's death or illness.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="SECURE OFFSITE STORAGE SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A commercial service offering secure storage facilities for physical or electronic documents at a remote location, an option for safeguarding EFFAK copies.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HURRICANE FINANCIAL TOOLKIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specialized resource offered by the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau to guide individuals through addressing their financial needs after a disaster like a hurricane.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BANKING APP">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A mobile software application developed by banks, allowing customers to manage accounts, pay bills, and monitor financial statements electronically, which can supplement an EFFAK.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HOSPITALS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Healthcare facilities where important medical documents, such as living wills and advanced directives, should be filed to ensure medical wishes are known.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PRIMARY CARE DOCTORS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">General medical practitioners with whom patients should file living wills and advanced directives to ensure their medical wishes are accessible.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ADVANCED DIRECTIVES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Legal documents that permit individuals to express their preferences for medical care in anticipation of future incapacitation, to be filed with healthcare providers.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL ADVISOR">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">A professional providing financial guidance and planning services, who can be entrusted with a copy of an Emergency Financial First Aid Kit for safekeeping.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="NEXT OF KIN">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual's closest relative, who can be authorized to access or manage an Emergency Financial First Aid Kit in emergencies, potentially through a power of attorney.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TAX PREPARATION TIME">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A recurring annual period for individuals to prepare and submit their tax returns, recommended as a time to review and update the Emergency Financial First Aid Kit.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DAYLIGHT SAVINGS TIME">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">The semi-annual practice of adjusting clocks, suggested as a reminder to review and update the Emergency Financial First Aid Kit.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHANGE IN MARITAL STATUS">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A significant life event, such as marriage or divorce, that necessitates immediate updates to the Emergency Financial First Aid Kit to reflect new circumstances.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RETIREMENT PLANNING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The strategic process of preparing financially for life after ceasing employment, during which the Emergency Financial First Aid Kit should be reviewed and updated to align with new goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEATH WITHIN THE HOUSEHOLD">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A somber life event that requires prompt and sensitive updates to financial and legal documents contained within the Emergency Financial First Aid Kit.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HOUSEHOLD IDENTIFICATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A section within the EFFAK for writing down important information to prove identity of household members after a disaster, maintain contact, and apply for FEMA disaster assistance.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL AND LEGAL DOCUMENTATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A section within the Emergency Financial First Aid Kit for recording information on key accounts and obligations, important for disaster recovery and re-establishing financial stability.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="MEDICAL INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A component of the Emergency Financial First Aid Kit comprising health records, insurance details, and emergency medical contacts, such as health insurance cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="HOUSEHOLD CONTACTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A list of important individuals and organizations (e.g., family, doctors, insurance agents) to contact during an emergency, a category within the EFFAK.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="DRIVER'S LICENSE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An official government-issued document verifying identity and authorizing the holder to operate a motor vehicle, often included in an Emergency Financial First Aid Kit as household identification.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="BANK STATEMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Periodic records from banks summarizing account activity, crucial for financial tracking and included in the Emergency Financial First Aid Kit as financial documentation.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="HEALTH INSURANCE CARDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Identification cards issued by health insurance providers, containing policy details for accessing medical services, included in the Emergency Financial First Aid Kit as medical information.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FEDERAL RIGHTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Legal protections established by federal law that safeguard consumers, particularly concerning electronic financial transactions and potential loss or theft of money.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="SECURED CREDIT CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of credit card that requires a cash deposit as collateral, primarily used by individuals to build or rebuild their credit history. It typically incurs interest, late fees, and often an annual fee.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT CARD COMPANY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of financial institution that issues credit cards and should be contacted immediately if an EFFAK or important documents are stolen.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL SERVICE PROVIDERS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A general term for companies or institutions that offer a range of financial products and services to consumers, such as banks, credit unions, and credit card companies.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL PRODUCT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A general category of services or instruments (like accounts, cards, loans) designed to help individuals achieve financial goals, build savings, improve credit, or manage income.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="BANK ACCOUNTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A general term for financial accounts held at banks or credit unions, which may include checking and savings accounts, often linked to debit cards, and subject to various fees and interest rates.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="OVERDRAFT FEES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Fees charged when an account holder spends or withdraws more money than is available in their checking account, often resulting from bounced checks.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="BANK FAILURE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk that a bank or credit union becomes insolvent, resulting in its inability to meet its financial obligations, though deposits are typically insured against this event.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ELECTRONIC MONEY LOSS/THEFT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk of funds being lost or stolen electronically from an account through errors or unauthorized digital transactions, against which federal rights offer protection.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBIT CARD INFORMATION THEFT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The unauthorized acquisition and fraudulent use of a debit card's details, for which consumers may be protected by federal rights and potential reimbursement.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CASH FLOW">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The movement of money into and out of an individual's financial accounts, which the provided text describes how to align by adjusting income and expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">8</data>
</node>
<node id="WEEKLY CASH FLOW">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The net flow of money (income minus expenses) over a one-week period, which the document aims to help users make positive.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MODULE 5">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A structured educational unit or section titled "GETTING THROUGH THE MONTH" within the larger "YOUR MONEY, YOUR GOALS TOOLKIT", providing guidance on financial management.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MODULE 3">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific module within the Your Money, Your Goals Toolkit that provides tools and guidance, including the Income and Benefits Tracker, for financial management.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="MODULE 4">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific module within the Your Money, Your Goals Toolkit that provides tools and guidance, including the Spending Tracker, for financial management.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="HOUSING SUBSIDY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial benefit or assistance provided to individuals or families to help cover the costs of housing.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ENDING BALANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The final calculated amount of money remaining at the conclusion of a specified financial period (e.g., a week or month) after all income and expenses are accounted for.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BEGINNING BALANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The initial amount of money available at the start of a specified financial period (e.g., a week or month), carried over from the previous period.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMERFINANCE.GOV/ASKCFPB/1433">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An online resource provided by the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau to help individuals find a lawyer to discuss debt collection issues.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMERFINANCE.GOV/ASKCFPB/1447">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An online resource provided by the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau offering more information on negotiating payment plans for debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMERFINANCE.GOV/CONSUMER-TOOLS/DEBT-COLLECTION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An online resource provided by the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau offering various letter templates and tools for contacting debt collectors.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HARASSMENT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The illegal and prohibited action by a debt collector of repeatedly calling, intimidating, or using abusive tactics towards a debtor.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ABUSIVE OR OBSCENE LANGUAGE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The illegal and prohibited use of offensive, vulgar, or inappropriate language by a debt collector during communication with a debtor.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="THREATS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The illegal and prohibited action by a debt collector of threatening to take actions they cannot legally take or do not intend to execute.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MISLEADING">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The illegal and prohibited act by a debt collector of lying, misrepresenting facts, or providing false information to a debtor.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PUBLISHING NAME">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The illegal and prohibited act by a debt collector of publicly disclosing a person's name for not paying a debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL SITUATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual's financial situation encompasses their overall monetary resources, income, and expenses, which plays a crucial role in deciding the most comfortable and affordable auto insurance deductibles and coverages.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT SETTLEMENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of negotiating with a debt collector or creditor to agree on paying a reduced lump sum to fully satisfy and close an outstanding debt account.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="LAWSUIT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal proceeding initiated by a debt collector against a debtor in court to legally compel the payment of an outstanding debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="COURT DOCUMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Official legal papers, such as a summons or complaint, served upon a debtor in connection with a debt collection lawsuit, requiring a formal response.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COURT">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A governmental body that administers justice, capable of hearing legal disputes and issuing judgments, such as money judgments, regarding debts.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="MONEY JUDGMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A court order that legally obligates one party to pay a specific sum of money to another party, typically issued against a debtor who fails to respond to a lawsuit.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="COURT HEARING">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A formal session held in a court of law where evidence is presented, arguments are made, and legal procedures are followed in a case, such as a debt collection lawsuit.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="STATUTE OF LIMITATIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A law that sets the maximum time after an event within which legal proceedings may be initiated, affecting how long certain negative information remains on a credit report.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL CHALLENGES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial Challenges are difficulties or obstacles encountered in managing one's finances, which may include insufficient funds, unexpected expenses, or debt issues.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL PRODUCT OR SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A broad category encompassing various offerings in the financial sector, such as mortgages, student loans, or credit reports, about which consumers may submit complaints to the CFPB.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL COUNSELING">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial Counseling is the provision of advice and guidance to individuals on managing their finances, debts, and investments, often to address financial challenges.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="FREE TAX FILING ASSISTANCE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The provision of complimentary help and support to individuals for preparing and submitting their income tax returns.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CHECK CASHING BUSINESS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A commercial establishment that provides a service of converting checks into cash for a fee, primarily to individuals without traditional bank accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL SERVICES PROVIDER">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An organization or company that offers a broad range of financial products and services, such as banks, insurance companies, or investment firms.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The scheduled or actual monetary amounts transferred to a creditor or lender to reduce the outstanding balance of a loan or credit obligation.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="APARTMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A rented residential unit, often requiring a credit check for leasing.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="JOB">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A paid position of employment, the attainment of which can be made easier by a positive credit history and more difficult by a poor one.</data>
  <data key="d2">8</data>
</node>
