  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The activity of obtaining one's credit reports for free, recommended annually to check for accuracy and identify potential issues.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPLAINT SUBMISSION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of formally reporting a problem with credit reporting to a relevant authority, such as the CFPB, for investigation and resolution.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT REPORTING COMPANIES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Organizations that compile and maintain consumer credit information, used by lenders for creditworthiness assessment. Though not explicitly named, the context of credit reports implies their existence, providing definitions of terms they use.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="FURNISHERS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Entities, such as lenders, utility companies, and landlords, that provide individuals' credit, banking, and payment history information to credit reporting companies.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="POOR CREDIT HISTORY">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A negative record of borrowing and repayment behavior, which can lead to significant difficulties in obtaining jobs, housing, loans, insurance, and other essential financial services.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOW CREDIT SCORES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A numeric indicator reflecting a low level of creditworthiness, typically resulting from a poor credit history, leading to less favorable loan terms, higher deposits, and other financial disadvantages.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SECURITY CLEARANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An official authorization, often required for specific jobs (including military positions), where eligibility can be negatively impacted by an individual's credit history.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INSURANCE COVERAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A service that provides financial protection or reimbursement against losses, where eligibility or the cost of premiums can be influenced by credit history.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CELL PHONE PLANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Service agreements for mobile communication, where the availability of certain plans, terms, and required deposits can be influenced by an individual's credit history.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CABLE TV">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Subscription-based television services, for which eligibility, terms, or required deposits might be influenced by an individual's credit history.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OPTING OUT OF PRE-SCREENED OFFERS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of removing one's name from mailing lists for unsolicited credit offers, which can be done by phone or online.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PRE-SCREENED CREDIT OFFERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Unsolicited solicitations for credit cards or loans sent by mail to individuals who meet certain criteria, from which one can opt out.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="BUSINESSES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Commercial entities that are vulnerable to disasters, with a significant percentage failing to reopen after major events, and are encouraged to prepare financially for emergencies.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="EMERGENCY FINANCIAL FIRST AID KIT (EFFAK)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A kit created in 2004 by Operation HOPE and FEMA to help individuals and families collect and organize critical financial, medical, and household contact information for disaster recovery. It includes checklists and forms for household identification, financial and legal documentation, medical information, and household contacts.</data>
  <data key="d2">7</data>
</node>
<node id="OPERATION HOPE, INC.">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">America’s first nonprofit social investment bank and a national leader in providing financial literacy and economic empowerment programs, working with government, private sector, and community interests to revitalize inner-city communities.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="READY.GOV">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A website that provides resources and information on how to prepare for emergencies and disasters, including making a family emergency plan, building an emergency supply kit, and community involvement.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="DANIEL KANIEWSKI">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">The Deputy Administrator for Resilience at FEMA, who co-signed and contributed to the Emergency Financial First Aid Kit document.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="JOHN HOPE BRYANT">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">The CEO and Founder of Operation HOPE, Inc., who co-signed and contributed to the Emergency Financial First Aid Kit document.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DISASTERS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Catastrophic events (also referred to as emergencies) that pose significant risks to individuals and businesses, necessitating preparedness to mitigate impact and aid recovery.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="RAINY-DAY FUND">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial reserve specifically intended to cover unexpected expenses or emergencies, a key component of financial preparedness that is difficult to build without sufficient income and savings.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL WELLNESS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The state of having basic knowledge of one's finances and making informed decisions to manage financial resources, which is essential for planning for emergencies and disasters.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="FOUR SIMPLE STEPS TO FINANCIAL PREPAREDNESS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A structured approach or guide presented within the EFFAK to help individuals effectively prepare their finances for emergencies.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="HOUSEHOLD IDENTIFICATION MANAGEMENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of organizing and safeguarding identity documents and personal information for all household members, as recommended by the EFFAK for emergency readiness.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL AND LEGAL DOCUMENTATION MANAGEMENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The systematic organization and secure storage of critical financial and legal documents, essential for recovery and financial stability after a disaster, as advised by the EFFAK.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL ACCOUNT INFORMATION MANAGEMENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The compilation and security of details for all financial accounts, ensuring accessibility and management during emergencies, a key component of the EFFAK's guidance.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MEDICAL INFORMATION MANAGEMENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The structured collection and protection of essential medical records and contact information for healthcare providers and family, recommended by the EFFAK for emergencies.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="HOUSEHOLD CONTACTS MANAGEMENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The compilation and maintenance of contact details for family members, friends, and important service providers for emergency communication, as outlined in the EFFAK.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PROTECTING INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The practice of safeguarding personal and financial data through various methods, including securing electronic records and using strong passwords, to prevent identity theft and fraud, as detailed in the EFFAK.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PERSONAL DISASTER PREPAREDNESS GUIDE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A guide published by Operation HOPE that outlines various types of information to store for use after a disaster, covers likely emergencies, and includes plans of action.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="FEMA MOBILE APP">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A mobile application developed by FEMA to provide disaster alerts, safety tips, and resources, recommended by the EFFAK for enhancing preparedness.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DISASTER ASSISTANCE RESOURCES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The availability and guidance on accessing support, information, and services provided by government agencies and other organizations after a disaster, detailed within the EFFAK.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL LITERACY AND EDUCATION COMMISSION">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A commission established under the Fair and Accurate Credit Transactions Act of 2003, tasked with developing a national financial education website (www.mymoney.gov), a hotline, and a national plan, and chaired by the Secretary of the Treasury.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="DEPARTMENT OF HOMELAND SECURITY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The U.S. federal executive department responsible for public security, encompassing agencies like FEMA, and referenced in the EFFAK document regarding visual identities.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="STOCKPILING SUPPLIES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of accumulating essential goods and resources in advance, recommended as a preparedness measure for emergencies and disasters.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="KEEPING ELECTRONIC RECORDS SAFE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of safeguarding digital information and documents against loss, damage, or unauthorized access, as advised for emergency preparedness.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MANAGING PASSWORDS AND PINS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The practice of creating, securing, and organizing passwords and personal identification numbers to protect sensitive financial and personal information.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RESPONDING TO EFFAK THEFT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A set of recommended steps to take if the Emergency Financial First Aid Kit, containing sensitive information, is stolen.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="VISITING READY.GOV">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of accessing the Ready.gov website to obtain emergency preparedness information and resources.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COMMUNITY PREPAREDNESS ACTIVITIES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Engaging in local initiatives and programs designed to enhance the readiness of a community for various emergencies and disasters.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FOLLOWING TIPS FOR EMPLOYERS AND BUSINESS OWNERS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Implementing specific recommendations and advice tailored for businesses to ensure continuity and safety after a disaster.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOW-BALANCE ALERT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A bank service that provides notifications (text or email) to account holders when their balance drops below a predetermined amount, helping them prevent overdrafts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOW-FEE CHECKING ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A checking account designed to have reduced monthly service fees, often achievable by maintaining a minimum balance or utilizing services like direct deposit.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FREE CHECKING ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A checking account that does not charge monthly service fees, often available to specific customer segments such as seniors or students, or under certain conditions.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ATM WITHDRAWAL OVERDRAFT SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An optional service that permits ATM withdrawals and debit card purchases to overdraw an account, potentially leading to the account balance dipping below zero and incurring overdraft fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OVERDRAFT PROTECTION (LINKED TO SAVINGS)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A service that automatically transfers funds from a linked savings account to cover transactions in a checking account when it would otherwise be overdrawn, typically for a transfer fee that is lower than an overdraft fee.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MODULE 8: CHOOSING FINANCIAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An educational module within the "Your Money, Your Goals Toolkit" designed to help users understand and evaluate financial products and services to find suitable ones.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="OVERDRAFT FEE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A charge imposed by a bank or credit union when a withdrawal or payment exceeds the available balance in an account, which can be collected directly by the bank.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="BOUNCED CHECK FEE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A charge incurred when a check is written for an amount greater than the available funds in the account, resulting in the check being returned unpaid.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NON-SUFFICIENT FUNDS FEE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A fee charged by a financial institution when an account lacks enough money to cover a payment or withdrawal, distinct from an overdraft fee which allows the transaction to go through but charges a fee.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MONTHLY SERVICE FEES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Recurring charges levied by banks for maintaining a checking or savings account, which can sometimes be waived based on certain account activities or balances.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TRANSFER FEE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A cost associated with moving money between different bank accounts, such as from a savings account to a checking account for overdraft coverage.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="AVOIDING FEES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The overarching goal or set of strategies detailed in the document, aimed at preventing various financial charges from banks and credit unions.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MONITORING ACCOUNT BALANCE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The proactive practice of regularly checking an account's available funds to prevent overspending and ensure compliance with minimum balance requirements.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SETTING UP LOW-BALANCE ALERT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of activating a bank's notification service to receive alerts when an account's balance falls below a specified amount.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OPTING OUT OF OVERDRAFT SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The decision to decline specific bank services that permit ATM withdrawals and debit card purchases to overdraw an account, thereby avoiding associated fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LINKING CHECKING TO SAVINGS ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of connecting two types of bank accounts to facilitate automatic fund transfers for overdraft protection.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="VISITING ATMS IN BANK'S NETWORK">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The strategy of exclusively using Automated Teller Machines affiliated with one's own bank or its network to circumvent external ATM charges.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REVIEWING BANK STATEMENTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The regular examination of bank-issued account summaries (both digital and paper) to verify transaction accuracy, identify unauthorized activity, and stay informed about account terms and fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MAINTAINING SUFFICIENT FUNDS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The diligent practice of ensuring an adequate balance in an account to cover all planned expenditures, checks, and automatic payments, thereby preventing overdrafts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MODULE 1: SETTING GOALS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The first module of the "Your Money, Your Goals Toolkit," which focuses on teaching individuals how to set, adjust, and achieve short-term and long-term goals, including SMART goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="SHORT-TERM GOALS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Objectives intended to be achieved in a relatively near future, part of a larger plan to reach overall life and financial goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="LONG-TERM GOALS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Goals that may take many months or even years to reach, such as sending a child to college or paying off a large debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMERFINANCE.GOV/COMPLAINT">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The official website and online service provided by the CFPB for consumers to submit complaints about financial products or services.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="BOSTON">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific geographical location used as an example to illustrate the concept of a "specific" goal for travel, making it easier to plan than a general one.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EAST COAST">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">A general geographical region used as an example to illustrate a "general" goal for travel, which is harder to plan for than a specific destination like Boston.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ANXIETY">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A feeling of worry, nervousness, or unease, typically about an event or something with an uncertain outcome, specifically concerning large purchases or financial planning.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="UNCERTAINTY">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The state of being unsure or unknown, particularly concerning future financial stability or the ability to meet large purchase or life event goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="STRESS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A state of mental or emotional strain or tension resulting from adverse or demanding circumstances, often exacerbated by financial uncertainty or lack of planning.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="ANNUAL CREDIT REPORT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of credit report that consumers are entitled to receive once every 12 months for free from each of the three nationwide credit reporting companies.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT CARD ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial account that an authorized user is permitted to use, and whose payment status is reported on credit reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="MODULE 7: UNDERSTANDING CREDIT REPORTS AND SCORES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An educational module designed to help consumers comprehend the importance and mechanics of credit reports and scores, containing various tools and handouts.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="CHARGE OFF">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A business decision that an account is uncollectible, although the consumer remains legally responsible for the debt, which may subsequently be pursued by a collection agency.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CLOSED DATE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The specific date on which an account is closed, either by the business or the consumer, with any outstanding balance remaining the consumer's responsibility.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DELINQUENT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The status of an account that has not been paid on time and is late, usually categorized by specific durations such as 30, 60, 90, or 120 days or more.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="DISCHARGE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A court order that releases a consumer from the legal responsibility for a debt, typically as part of the bankruptcy process.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="DISPUTE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of formally challenging inaccurate information on a credit report, typically by sending a letter and supporting documentation to the credit reporting company and/or the furnisher.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="END USER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The business or individual that ultimately receives and uses a credit report.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="INFORMATION PROVIDER OR FURNISHER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A business or individual that regularly reports credit-related data to credit reporting companies.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYMENT STATUS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The historical record of an account's payments, encompassing on-time payments, delinquencies, and other negative items, as reflected on a credit report.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="U.S. CONSUMERS">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals residing in the United States who are entitled to free credit reports and are protected by federal and state laws regarding credit records.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="STATES">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">States are geographic administrative divisions within a country where insurance laws and the availability of specific coverages, such as Personal Injury Protection, can vary significantly.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT OR FINANCIAL FRAUD">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A broad category of fraudulent activities related to an individual's credit or financial accounts, especially a concern for minors with unauthorized credit reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="PROTECTED CONSUMERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal designation for minors under the age of 16, for whom federal law provides specific protections regarding credit records and identity theft, allowing authorized persons to request a security freeze.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="MINORS">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals under the age of 18 who typically do not have a credit report unless specific conditions are met, such as being an authorized user or having student loans, and who are vulnerable to identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCOUNT'S OWNER">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">The individual who is legally responsible for making payments on a credit card account, whose payment status is also shown on their credit report.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMER'S ASSETS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Tangible or intangible property owned by an individual consumer, which may be used to pay off creditors in legal processes like Chapter 7 bankruptcy.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ELIGIBLE DEBTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Specific financial obligations that can be discharged or restructured under bankruptcy laws, as outlined in the definitions of Chapter 7 bankruptcy.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PUBLIC RECORDS SECTION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific part of a credit report where significant legal events, such as bankruptcies, are recorded and displayed.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMER">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual who enters into financial agreements, takes out loans, and whose credit activity is tracked by credit reports, disputes information, and is responsible for debts.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="COURTS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Legal bodies that arrange payment plans in Chapter 13 bankruptcies, discharge debts, and enforce laws.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FUTURE INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Earnings expected to be received by a consumer in the future, used to pay off creditors in a Chapter 13 bankruptcy.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="30-DAY BILLING CYCLES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Regular periods used for billing and determining delinquency status of accounts, contributing to default if missed.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INDIVIDUAL">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">A single person who may receive a credit report as an end user, report information as a furnisher, or act on behalf of others.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ON-TIME PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A positive financial behavior indicating consistent and timely repayment of debts, reported as positive information on a credit report.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="NEGATIVE ITEMS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Adverse entries on a credit report, such as delinquencies, that reflect negatively on a consumer's credit history and payment status.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WEBSITES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Online platforms that may offer free credit reports, sometimes with an underlying sales objective, including official credit report ordering sites.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPANIES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Businesses that offer various products or services, including free credit reports, sometimes requiring additional purchases, encompassing credit reporting companies and lenders.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PRODUCT OR SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Commercial offerings that consumers might be required to buy to receive free credit reports from some companies, or which are provided by companies.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UNEMPLOYED">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A state of not having a job, which entitles a consumer to additional free credit reports if they plan to seek employment.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PUBLIC ASSISTANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Government aid received by individuals, which qualifies them for additional free credit reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DISPUTED ERROR">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">An inaccuracy on a credit report that a consumer has challenged, which can lead to additional free credit reports if changed, and requires investigation.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMER REPORTING COMPANY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A business that collects and maintains credit information on consumers and is responsible for placing fraud alerts on credit files, often synonymous with credit reporting company.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EMPLOYMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The state of being employed or seeking a job, which can be denied based on information in a credit report.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NOTICE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A formal communication indicating a denial of credit, employment, or insurance due to credit report information, triggering a right to request a report.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE LAW">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Legislation enacted at the state level that may grant consumers additional rights, such as a second free annual credit report or allowing minors to enter contracts.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="JOINT OWNER">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual who shares legal ownership and responsibility for a financial account, which is one way a minor might legitimately acquire a credit report.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="EMANCIPATED MINOR">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">A minor who has been legally freed from control by their parents or guardians, enabling them to enter contracts and potentially have a credit report.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CONTRACTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Legally binding agreements between two or more parties, the ability to enter into which can affect whether a minor has a credit report.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT RECORDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A collection of a consumer's credit history and related information, protected by federal law, especially for minors, and subject to identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PERSONS WITH AUTHORITY">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals legally empowered to act on behalf of protected consumers, such as requesting a security freeze on their credit file.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHARITY CARE REDUCTION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A discount or waiver on hospital bills offered by hospitals to patients who meet certain financial eligibility criteria.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="HOSPITAL BILL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial document detailing charges for medical services provided by a hospital, which can be subject to a charity care reduction.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONTACT THE HOSPITAL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The recommendation to reach out to a hospital to find out about a charity care reduction on a hospital bill.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="“YOUR MONEY, YOUR GOALS” TOOLKIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An online resource provided by the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection for service providers, accessible at cfpb.gov/your-money-your-goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="REFER TO TOOLKIT ONLINE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action for service providers to access the "Your Money, Your Goals" toolkit online for more information.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMER LOAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of financial product about which consumers can submit complaints to the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau if they encounter problems.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL PRODUCTS OR SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A general category of financial offerings (including bank accounts, credit cards, student loans, and consumer loans) about which consumers can submit a complaint to the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="MONEY MATTERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A general term referring to topics and issues related to personal finance and money, about which the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau provides answers to commonly asked questions.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="VISIT CFPB.GOV/ASKCFPB">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The recommendation to access the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection's website (cfpb.gov/askcfpb) for answers to commonly asked questions about money matters.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="P.O. BOX 2900, CLINTON, IA 52733-2900">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">The complete mailing address for the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CLINTON, IA">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">A city and state in the United States, specified as part of the mailing address for the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection.</data>
  <data key="d2">6</data>
</node>
<node id="OFFSETS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Reductions applied to federal tax refunds to pay off certain types of debt owed to government agencies.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="BANK OR CREDIT UNION">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial institution that holds customer accounts, processes deposits, and may be involved in garnishments or set-offs.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCOUNT FREEZE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">An action taken by a bank or credit union to prevent access to funds in an account, often in response to a garnishment request.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OVERDUE LOAN PAYMENT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A loan payment that has not been made by its due date, which can enable a bank to collect the amount directly from an account via set-off.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SET-OFF">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A bank's action to collect an amount owed, such as an overdue loan payment or overdraft fee, directly from a customer's account.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NOTICE OF GARNISHMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A formal document sent by a bank to an account holder when funds in their account have been frozen due to a garnishment order.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EXEMPTION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal provision under federal or state law that protects certain funds or income from garnishment or set-off.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SOURCE OF INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The origin of an individual's earnings or benefits, which can be a factor in determining if funds are protected from garnishment.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LEGAL RIGHTS AND RESPONSIBILITIES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The entitlements and obligations individuals have under the law, particularly concerning debt collection and garnishment.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LEGAL SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Assistance provided by legal professionals, such as advice, representation, or help in understanding legal rights.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MODULE 3: TRACKING INCOME AND BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A section within the 'YOUR MONEY, YOUR GOALS TOOLKIT' that focuses on identifying and monitoring various sources of income and benefits, featuring the 'Income and benefits tracker'.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYMENT METHODS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Various systems or options available for transferring funds for goods, services, or obligations, such as cash, checks, direct deposit, or cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="RIGHTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Entitlements provided to consumers by laws like the Fair Debt Collections Practices Act, defining appropriate conduct for debt collectors.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="ABUSE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of mistreatment or harm, specifically verbal or psychological abuse from debt collectors, which is explicitly stated as a violation of the law.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="ANONYMOUS CALLS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The prohibited action of a debt collector calling a debtor without disclosing their identity.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="QUESTIONS TO ASK">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of inquiring about specific details, fees, and services related to financial products and services before making a decision.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="REQUEST MORE INFORMATION (ACTION)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of formally asking a debt collector for specific details and documentation regarding a claimed debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT COLLECTION LETTER TEMPLATES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Pre-designed, standardized letters available for consumers to use when communicating with debt collectors for various purposes.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INFORMATION REQUEST TEMPLATE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific pre-written document used by consumers to formally request detailed information about a debt from a debt collector.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT DISPUTE TEMPLATE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific pre-written document used by consumers to formally challenge the validity or accuracy of a debt with a debt collector.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="KEEP RECORDS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The practice of maintaining written or digital documentation of all communications, transactions, and documents related to debt collection, useful for disputes or court proceedings.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="PERSONAL FINANCIAL INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Sensitive data, such as bank account details, that debtors are advised to protect from debt collectors.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ORIGINAL CREDITOR">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The initial financial institution or entity that extended credit or to whom a debt was first owed, before it might be sold to a debt collector.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="AMOUNT OWED">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The specific sum of money that a debtor is legally required to pay, which can be disputed if believed to be incorrect.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="DATE ACCOUNT BECAME DELINQUENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The specific date when a debt payment was missed, marking the beginning of the account's overdue status.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DATE DEBT OBTAINED (BY COLLECTOR)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The specific date when a debt collector acquired the legal right to pursue collection of a particular debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="AMOUNT OF DEBT WHEN OBTAINED (BY COLLECTOR)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The specific monetary value of the debt at the time it was transferred to or purchased by the debt collector.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DOCUMENTATION PROVING PAYMENT OBLIGATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Official records or papers requested by a debtor to confirm their legal responsibility to pay a debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LAST BILL COPY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A duplicate of the most recent statement or invoice sent to a debtor regarding an outstanding balance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOSS OF DISPUTE RIGHTS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The potential consequence of delaying or failing to formally dispute a debt, which may result in forfeiting the ability to challenge its legitimacy.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NEGOTIATE A PAYMENT PLAN">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of discussing and agreeing upon a structured schedule of installment payments with a debt collector or creditor.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAY THE DEBT IN FULL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of completely satisfying an outstanding debt by remitting the entire outstanding balance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RESPOND TO COURT DOCUMENTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of formally replying to legal papers received from a court, such as a summons or complaint in a debt-related lawsuit, which is crucial to avoid a default judgment.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="SETTLEMENT OFFER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A proposal, typically from a debt collector, detailing a reduced amount they are willing to accept to fully resolve an outstanding debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="OTHER BUSINESSES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Entities besides lenders that use credit reports to decide on offering insurance, approving rentals, or providing utility and communication services.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UTILITY SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Services like cable TV, Internet, electricity, water, or a cell phone plan, whose provision may depend on credit report information.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EMPLOYMENT DECISIONS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Actions taken by employers, such as hiring, promotion, or granting security clearances, which can be influenced by a candidate's credit history and reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="NEGATIVE INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Adverse data reported by checking account reporting companies, such as unpaid negative balances, suspected fraud, or involuntary account closures, which can hinder opening new accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="LATE PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments made after their scheduled due dates, which significantly harm an individual's payment history and overall credit score.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="BANKRUPTCY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal status or process indicating inability to repay debts, which is reported as negative information on a credit report and can remain for up to 10 years.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CIVIL JUDGMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Legal rulings against an individual for monetary damages, which can appear as negative information on a credit report for seven years or longer.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BACK CHILD SUPPORT PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Overdue child support payments that can lead to a civil judgment and be reported as negative information on a credit report.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="POSITIVE INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Favorable entries on a credit report, such as a history of on-time payments, which can remain on the report indefinitely.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMER REPORTING COMPANIES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Organizations that collect, maintain, and provide credit information on consumers, compiling credit reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LARGE CREDIT APPLICATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An application for credit of $150,000 or more, for which negative information can be kept in consumer reporting company files indefinitely.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LARGE LIFE INSURANCE POLICY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A life insurance policy with a face value of $150,000 or more, for which negative information can be kept in consumer reporting company files indefinitely.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HIGH-SALARY JOB APPLICATION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">An application for a job with an annual salary of $75,000 or more, for which negative information can be kept in consumer reporting company files indefinitely.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
