<node id="DISPUTE LETTER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A formal written communication drafted by a consumer to notify a checking account reporting company about specific errors in their report and request correction.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SUPPORTING DOCUMENTS (FOR DISPUTE)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Any additional records, statements, or evidence provided by a consumer to validate their claim when disputing errors on a banking history report.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SAMPLE DISPUTE LETTER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A pre-written template or example letter, available for download, designed to guide consumers in drafting their own communications to dispute errors on banking history reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMERFINANCE.GOV/ASKCFPB/2029">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific web page on the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau's website offering resources, such as a sample dispute letter for banking history report errors.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CERTIFIED MAIL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A postal service option that provides documented proof of sending and delivery, recommended for formal communications like dispute letters.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MANAGING A CHECKING OR SAVINGS ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The ongoing oversight and administration of a financial account, including monitoring balances, transactions, and adherence to account terms.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TERMS AND FEES (ACCOUNT)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">The comprehensive set of conditions, rules, and associated charges that govern a specific financial account as outlined by the financial institution.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SHOP AROUND (FOR BANKS)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of comparing offerings (e.g., terms, fees, services) from multiple financial institutions before making a decision on where to open an account.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPARING FINANCIAL SERVICE PROVIDERS TOOL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A utility or guide designed to assist consumers in evaluating and selecting suitable financial institutions and their product offerings based on various criteria.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MONTHLY MAINTENANCE FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Recurring charges levied by financial institutions for the general upkeep and administration of a checking or savings account.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="NON-SUFFICIENT FUNDS (NSF) FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Charges imposed by financial institutions when an account lacks the necessary funds to cover a transaction, and the transaction is typically declined.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="OVERDRAFT SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Optional services offered by financial institutions that allow transactions to be completed even if they exceed the available account balance, typically for a fee.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="TRANSACTION (ACCOUNT)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Any financial activity that affects the balance of an account, such as deposits, withdrawals, transfers, or payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ELECTRONIC FUND TRANSFER ACT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal act that provides consumer protections regarding electronic fund transfers, particularly limiting responsibility for unauthorized transactions on debit or ATM cards if reported promptly.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FTC">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A governmental organization that advises individuals to regularly review and monitor their financial statements and account activity for unusual or suspicious activity, especially when banking online.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEMA APP">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A free mobile application offered by FEMA, available on App Store and Google Play, which provides safety tips for emergencies and weather alerts from the National Weather Service for locations across the United States.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OPERATION HOPE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An organization that publishes the Personal Disaster Preparedness Guide, which outlines additional types of information individuals should store for use after a disaster.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="READY BUSINESS PROGRAM">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A program available through Ready.gov (www.ready.gov/business) that offers business leaders step-by-step guides to build hazard-specific preparedness plans within their organizations.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="U.S. SMALL BUSINESS ADMINISTRATION">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A U.S. government agency that maintains an emergency preparedness website (www.sba.gov/emergencypreparedness) providing resources for business owners on topics such as disaster assistance, continuity of operations, and recovery.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="NATIONAL WEATHER SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An organization that issues weather alerts, which are integrated into and provided by the FEMA app.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="APP STORE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A digital distribution platform where users can download the FEMA app for free.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GOOGLE PLAY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A digital distribution platform where users can download the FEMA app for free.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ATM CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial card for which the Electronic Fund Transfer Act limits user responsibility for unauthorized activity if loss is reported quickly.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MISUSE OF CHECKING ACCOUNTS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">An unauthorized activity or fraudulent use of a checking account, highlighted as a component of identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="THEFT OF FINANCIAL DOCUMENTS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of stealing documents containing sensitive financial information, identified as a component of identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOSS OF DEBIT/CREDIT CARDS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The physical disappearance or misplacement of debit or credit cards, which requires immediate reporting to financial institutions.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GOVERNMENT-ISSUED IDENTIFICATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Official documents provided by a government agency, used for identification purposes, whose loss can contribute to identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CARD ISSUER">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An organization that issues credit or debit cards and may require written confirmation from a cardholder within 10 days of calling to report a card loss.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HOMEOWNERS OR RENTERS INSURANCE POLICY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An insurance product that may provide liability coverage for card loss or theft, and whose terms should be checked by policyholders.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="IDENTITY MONITORING SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A service individuals can subscribe to in order to help ensure their personal information is protected in the future and to safeguard against identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PERSONAL IDENTIFICATION NUMBER (PIN)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A numerical code used to verify user identity for electronic banking, bill paying, purchasing, and other financial activities, providing an extra measure of protection.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ELECTRONIC BANKING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of performing banking transactions digitally, which requires protection through strong passwords and PINs.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BILL PAYING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of settling financial obligations, often performed electronically and requiring secure access measures like passwords and PINs.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PURCHASING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of acquiring goods or services, particularly when done electronically, requiring secure access measures like passwords and PINs.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INSURANCE AGENCY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An organization that provides insurance services and should be contacted if an EFFAK or important documents are believed to be stolen or illegally accessed.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBIT OR ATM CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial instrument used for electronic transactions, whose unauthorized activity liability is governed by the Electronic Fund Transfer Act.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OPEN ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of financial account, exemplified by account #3629 from ABC Megastore, currently placed with Reliable Collections.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SPECIALTY CONSUMER REPORTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A category of consumer reports, distinct from standard financial reports, that often includes sensitive information like arrests and convictions, used for purposes such as employment background screenings.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OPEN ACCOUNTS (GENERAL)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A general category of active financial accounts that an individual currently possesses, whose details are included in account information reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DISPUTING THE DEBT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of formally challenging the validity or accuracy of a debt, often by sending a letter to the debt collector.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SETTLING WITH THE DEBT COLLECTOR">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of negotiating with a debt collector to pay a smaller amount than originally owed to fully resolve an account.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SUED BY A DEBT COLLECTOR">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal action initiated by a debt collector against an individual to recover an unpaid debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="VERIFY DEBT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of confirming the legitimacy and details of a debt, often by requesting information from the debt collector.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CFPB.GOV/DEBT-COLLECTION">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An official website of the Bureau providing resources, including sample letters, related to debt collection.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SHORT-TERM PLAN">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A temporary strategy developed to manage finances and meet obligations when there is insufficient money to cover all needs.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYING BILLS LATE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of remitting payment for a bill after its due date, often resulting in fees or negative impacts on credit.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MISSING A BILL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of failing to pay a bill entirely, which can lead to collection efforts, late fees, and negative credit reporting.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SQUEAKY WHEEL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A metaphorical term referring to the most insistent or demanding bill or creditor.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PRIORITIZE BILLS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of ranking bills and financial obligations by their importance and the potential consequences of non-payment, to determine the order in which they should be paid.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MISS A PAYMENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of failing to make a scheduled payment by its due date, which can result in late fees and negatively impact credit history.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="CERTIFIED HOUSING COUNSELOR">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">A professional providing guidance and assistance with housing-related financial challenges, including preventing foreclosure and managing rent/mortgage payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REPOSSESSION OF CAR">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk that a lender will seize a car from a borrower due to failure to make loan payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NEGATIVE ENTRY ON CREDIT RECORD">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A damaging notation on a credit report indicating a missed payment, default, or other undesirable financial behavior, which can lower credit scores.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOWERED CREDIT SCORES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A decrease in an individual's credit score, indicating a higher credit risk and potentially leading to difficulty obtaining future credit or higher interest rates.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOSING YOUR JOB">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk of becoming unemployed, which directly impacts income and the ability to meet financial obligations.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GAS OR BUS FARE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Costs associated with transportation, either for fuel for a personal vehicle or tickets for public transit, essential for getting to work.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EQUIPMENT OR UNIFORM">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Costs associated with necessary items for employment, such as specific tools or required clothing.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RENTERS OR HOME INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Insurance that protects personal belongings (renters) or the structure and contents of a home (homeowners) from damage or theft, safeguarding assets.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RENT, MORTGAGE, OR PROPERTY TAXES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Regular payments made for the occupancy (rent), purchase (mortgage), or ownership (property taxes) of real estate, crucial for housing.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RELATIONSHIP WITH LANDLORD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The dynamic between a tenant and their landlord, which can be strained by late payments or other issues, potentially impacting housing security.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LANDLORD">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">The owner of a property (such as a house, apartment, or land) who leases or rents it to another individual or entity.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="UTILITY COMPANIES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Companies that provide essential services such as gas, electricity, water, and waste management.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RECONNECTION FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Charges imposed by utility companies to restore services after they have been disconnected due to non-payment.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HIGHER INTEREST RATES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">An increase in the percentage charged on borrowed money, making debt more expensive over time, often a consequence of late payments or poor credit.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LEGAL CONSEQUENCES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Potential legal repercussions, such as lawsuits or fines, that can arise from delaying or failing to make required payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="LOANS (STUDENT, PAYDAY)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial products where money is borrowed and repaid with interest over time, including student loans for education and high-interest payday loans for short-term needs.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COURT-ORDERED FINES AND FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Monetary penalties and charges imposed by a court as a result of legal judgments or violations.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MYMONEY.GOV">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A national financial education website developed by the Financial Literacy and Education Commission.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DIRECTOR OF THE CONSUMER FINANCIAL PROTECTION BUREAU">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">The person who serves as the vice chair of the Financial Literacy and Education Commission.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DISASTER-RELATED SCAMS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Fraudulent schemes that occur in the context of disasters, which individuals are warned to be aware of and safeguard against.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BANK ACCOUNT NUMBERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Identifiers for bank accounts, considered sensitive financial information that consumers are advised not to share with debt collectors.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="BRANCHES">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">Physical locations, often associated with banks or credit unions, where financial services are offered.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MORTGAGES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of loan used to finance the purchase of real estate, requiring regular payments over a set term.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="ELECTRIC BILL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A periodic statement of charges for electricity consumption, which becomes debt if past due.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAST DUE BILL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A bill that has not been paid by its due date, which then converts the owed amount into a debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MANAGING DEBT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of overseeing and controlling financial obligations to ensure timely payments, reduce balances, and avoid financial distress.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REDUCING DEBT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of decreasing the total amount of money owed, often by paying more than the minimum required or by strategically prioritizing certain debts, leading to improved financial health.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DEPARTMENT STORES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Retail establishments that sell a wide range of consumer goods and may offer store-specific credit, thus acting as creditors.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYDAY LENDERS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Companies that specialize in offering payday loans, which are typically short-term, high-interest loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="COURT-ORDERED CHILD SUPPORT PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments mandated by a legal court order for the financial maintenance of a child, becoming debt if past due.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAST DUE RENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Rental payments that have not been made by the agreed-upon due date, resulting in a debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOCAL GOVERNMENT">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The administration of a particular town, county, or district, which can be owed money for taxes or fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE GOVERNMENT">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The government of a subnational administrative division, which can be owed money for taxes or fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BACK INCOME TAXES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Income taxes that were not paid in a previous tax period and are now overdue, representing a debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOAN STATEMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Documents detailing the current status, payments, interest, and balance of a loan account.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REQUESTING YOUR FREE CREDIT REPORTS TOOL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific resource or utility designed to assist individuals in obtaining copies of their free credit reports, located in Module 7.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COLLECTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The process where unpaid debts are turned over to a collection agency, resulting in substantial damage to an individual's credit score.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="MORTGAGE AGREEMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal contract outlining the terms and conditions of a mortgage loan, including interest rate, payment schedule, and property collateral.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT-TO-INCOME RATIO">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial metric that represents the percentage of gross monthly income that goes toward paying debts, typically with guidelines between 28% and 35%. If this ratio is too high, it is advisable to seek help from a housing counselor.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="HIGH DEBT-TO-INCOME RATIO">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial state where a significant portion of an individual's income is consumed by debt payments, indicating potential financial strain and higher risk to lenders.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FOOD COSTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Expenses specifically related to purchasing food and groceries.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REGULAR INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Income that is received consistently and predictably, often on a fixed schedule and in a similar amount.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="IRREGULAR INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Earnings that vary significantly in amount and timing from one period to another, making it difficult to predict consistently.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="SEASONAL INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Income that is earned or received primarily during specific periods or seasons of the year, rather than consistently throughout.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="ONE-TIME-ONLY INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Income received just once, not expected to recur, such as a bonus, inheritance, or sale of an asset.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INCOME YOU CAN COUNT ON">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Predictable and reliable income that individuals can confidently factor into their financial planning each month.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WEEKLY TOTAL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The sum of all income or benefits received within a single week, as calculated in the Income and Benefits Tracker.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TOTAL PAY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The full amount of money earned by an individual before any deductions are subtracted, equivalent to gross income.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ADVANTAGES OF PAYMENT METHODS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The positive outcomes or favorable aspects associated with different ways of receiving income or benefits.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BENEFITS PROGRAMS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Government-sponsored initiatives that provide various forms of financial or other assistance to eligible individuals or families.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TOTAL MONTHLY INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The sum of all income received in a given month, calculated by adding up weekly totals.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BENEFITS STATEMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Documents that provide detailed information about the types and amounts of benefits an individual receives.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="RECORDS OF ELECTRONIC PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Documentation or transaction histories of payments made or received through electronic means, such as direct deposits or card transactions.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RISKS OF PAYMENT METHODS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Potential negative outcomes or disadvantages associated with different methods of receiving income or benefits, such as security concerns or fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOST OR STOLEN CASH">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The specific danger that physical cash may be misplaced, lost, or unlawfully taken by theft, mentioned as a risk for cash.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PICK BEST PAYMENT METHOD">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of selecting the most suitable option for receiving income and benefits based on individual needs and preferences.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPLETE THE &quot;INCOME AND BENEFITS TRACKER&quot;">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of filling out or finishing the "Income and benefits tracker" to record financial details.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="USE &quot;INCREASING INCOME AND BENEFITS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of utilizing the "Increasing income and benefits" tool or guide to explore strategies for boosting earnings.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PLAN EXPENSE PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of scheduling when to pay various financial obligations or living expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SAVE TOWARD GOALS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of accumulating money over time with the specific purpose of achieving future financial objectives.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GATHER FINANCIAL RECORDS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of collecting necessary financial documents such as pay stubs, benefits statements, and electronic payment records.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ENTER INCOME AND BENEFITS AMOUNTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of inputting specific monetary values for income and benefits into a tracking system or document.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BOOST INCOME">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of taking steps to increase the amount of money one earns or receives.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPLETE THE &quot;SPENDING TRACKER&quot;">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of filling out the "Spending tracker" to monitor and record expenditures.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BUILD A CASH FLOW BUDGET">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of creating a financial plan that details the inflows and outflows of cash over a period to manage money.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PLAN SAVING AND SPENDING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of strategically scheduling financial activities to optimize both savings and expenditures.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FILL IN NET INCOME AMOUNT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of recording the net income figure in a financial tracker or document.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ADD UP AMOUNTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of calculating the sum of multiple monetary figures, such as weekly income amounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FIGURE OUT MONTHLY INCOME">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of calculating the total income received over the course of a single month.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MAKE COPIES OF TRACKER">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of duplicating the financial tracker document for ongoing use.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FOLLOW INCOME MONTH-TO-MONTH">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of continuously monitoring and observing income trends and changes over successive months.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RECEIVE INCOME AND BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The general act of acquiring money and financial or non-financial aid.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MANAGE MONEY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of overseeing and controlling one's financial resources, including income, expenses, savings, and investments.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MAKE PAYMENT DECISION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of choosing among available options for how to receive income or benefits.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REVIEW BENEFITS AND RISKS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of carefully examining the advantages and potential negative outcomes of various financial options.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WRITE DOWN QUESTIONS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of documenting inquiries or points of clarification regarding financial options.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REVIEW &quot;KNOWING YOUR PREPAID CARD RIGHTS&quot; HANDOUT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of reading and studying the informational document about prepaid card rights.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EVALUATE BENEFITS AND RISKS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of critically assessing the positive and negative aspects of each payment method.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHOOSE PAYMENT METHOD">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of selecting a preferred way to receive income or benefits after evaluating options.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EMPLOYERS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals or entities that employ people, who are encouraged to follow tips for financially preparing their companies for emergencies and disasters.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="GOVERNMENT AGENCIES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Official departments or bodies of a government responsible for administering various public services and programs.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MODULE 8">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A section within the 'YOUR MONEY, YOUR GOALS TOOLKIT' that contains information and resources, such as the 'Knowing your prepaid card rights' handout.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="REPAYING STUDENT LOANS TOOL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific tool or resource described in Module 6 that helps individuals learn about options to reduce student loan payments, such as income-based repayment plans.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SPENDING POWER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The ability of an individual to purchase goods and services, which can be increased by benefit payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ONE-TIME INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A single, non-recurring payment or financial gain, such as a bonus, inheritance, or tax refund.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="MANAGING INCOME">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of handling and organizing one's income to ensure financial stability and cover expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PLANNING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of organizing a schedule or strategy for future financial activities, such as saving and spending.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CAREERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Long-term professional paths that individuals pursue, often involving specific education and training.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="APPLYING FOR JOBS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of formally seeking employment by submitting applications and resumes.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INTERVIEWS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Meetings conducted to assess a candidate's suitability for a job, typically part of the job application process.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HUD">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A governmental department (likely the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development) that offers resources and programs, including housing counseling services.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="HOUSING COUNSELOR">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">A professional certified by HUD who provides guidance and assistance with managing debt, especially when an individual's debt-to-income ratio is higher than recommended guidelines.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PAY SMALLEST DEBT FIRST">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A debt repayment strategy where, after making all minimum payments, extra funds are applied to the smallest debt first. Once paid off, that extra amount is added to the minimum payment of the next smallest debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAY HIGHEST INTEREST RATE FIRST">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A debt repayment strategy where, after making all minimum payments, extra funds are applied to the debt with the highest interest rate first. Once paid off, that extra amount is added to the minimum payment of the next highest-rate debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOAN CONTRACT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal agreement provided by lenders that explains the terms and conditions of a loan, including the APR, amount financed, finance charges, and total payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="AMOUNT FINANCED">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The total principal amount of money borrowed for a loan, which should be accurately stated in the loan contract.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TOTAL OF ALL PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The cumulative sum of all payments a borrower will make over the entire term of a loan, as specified in the loan contract.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CAR DEALERSHIP">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A business establishment where consumers can shop for cars and auto loans, and negotiate the terms of a purchase or financing.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MODULE 9">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Module 9 is a specific section or unit within a larger document or toolkit, dedicated to the topic of protecting your money, including information on identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="OWING MORE ON THE CAR THAN IT'S WORTH">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial risk associated with auto loans, particularly those with long terms and low monthly payments, where the outstanding loan balance exceeds the current market value of the vehicle.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EXTENDED WARRANTIES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Optional service contracts that provide coverage for vehicle repairs and parts beyond the manufacturer's standard warranty, often offered as an add-on during a car purchase.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="UPGRADED PACKAGES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Optional bundles of additional features or enhancements for a vehicle that can increase its overall purchase price.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SERVICE PLANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Optional plans that cover routine maintenance or specific services for a vehicle, often offered as an add-on during a car purchase.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="OVERDRAFT PROGRAM">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A service offered by banks that covers debit card purchases or ATM withdrawals exceeding the account balance, typically charging a fee and requiring repayment from the account holder.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="ATM WITHDRAWAL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of taking cash from an Automated Teller Machine, which may be covered by a bank's overdraft program if the account lacks sufficient funds.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="VISA">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A global payment technology company that facilitates electronic funds transfers throughout the world, often associated with credit, debit, and open-loop prepaid cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="MASTERCARD">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A global payment technology company that processes payments between banks and merchants worldwide, commonly associated with credit, debit, and open-loop prepaid cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="AMERICAN EXPRESS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A multinational financial services corporation known for its credit card, charge card, and traveler's cheque businesses, operating its own payment network.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="DISCOVER">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An American financial services company that operates the Discover Bank and issues the Discover credit card, including its own payment network.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="KNOWING YOUR PREPAID CARD RIGHTS HANDOUT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An educational handout that provides information on the rights and responsibilities associated with buying or using a prepaid card.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SENDING MONEY ABROAD HANDOUT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An educational handout that provides information on the rights and responsibilities when sending money to another country.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINDING FINANCIAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES (TOOL)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool designed to help users identify financial products that meet their specific needs, understand how they work, and where to obtain them, serving as a starting point for selection.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OPENING A CHECKING OR SAVINGS ACCOUNT (TOOL)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool to guide users in preparing all necessary documentation and answers required for successfully opening checking or savings accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="AVOIDING CHECKING ACCOUNT FEES (TOOL)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool that offers practical strategies and tips users can employ to lower or entirely eliminate fees associated with their checking accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPARING FINANCIAL SERVICE PROVIDERS (TOOL)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool used to compare different companies that offer financial products or services, helping users ask the right questions and choose the most suitable provider.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EVALUATING YOUR PREPAID OR PAYROLL CARD (TOOL)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A tool designed to help users thoroughly understand all the specific details and fees associated with using their prepaid or payroll cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A general category of services (like bill payment, check cashing, banking) that assist individuals in managing their money and achieving financial objectives.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CERTIFICATE OF DEPOSIT (CD)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of savings product where money is deposited for a fixed period at a fixed interest rate, providing a secure place to keep money and build savings.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CHECK CASHING SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A service that allows individuals to receive cash for their paycheck without first depositing it into an account, often incurring a fee.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="PREPAID CARD (WITH SAVINGS WALLET FEATURE)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of prepaid card that includes a dedicated feature or wallet designed to help users build up savings separately from their spending funds.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MYEQUIFAX ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A myEquifax account is an online service provided by Equifax that allows consumers to access and monitor their credit information, including free credit reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TAX LIENS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Tax Liens are legal claims made by a government entity against a taxpayer's assets when taxes are unpaid, serving as a public record of debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FURNISHER OF INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A Furnisher of Information is any entity, such as a bank, credit card company, or landlord, that provides information about a consumer's accounts to credit reporting companies.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="POST OFFICE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The Post Office is a governmental or quasi-governmental agency responsible for providing postal services, including certified mail.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CERTIFIED MAIL WITH RETURN RECEIPT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Certified Mail with Return Receipt is a postal service that provides proof of mailing and proof of delivery, including the date and recipient's signature, often used for important legal or financial communications.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SAFEGUARDING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of protecting oneself or one's assets from harm, danger, or fraudulent activities, specifically mentioned in the context of disaster-related fraud and the EFFAK.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RECOVERY PROCESS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The series of actions or steps taken to restore or return to a normal state after a disaster or emergency, including financial and personal rebuilding.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COLLECT AND ORGANIZE INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of gathering and systematically arranging critical financial, medical, and household contact information as part of disaster preparedness, which the EFFAK facilitates.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REBUILDING LIFE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of reconstructing one's personal and financial stability after being impacted by a disaster, a goal supported by financial preparedness efforts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ASSESS AND COMPILE DOCUMENTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The first step in financial preparedness, involving gathering important financial documents and contacts to complete the EFFAK forms.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPLETE AND DATE EFFAK FORMS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of filling out all the necessary forms and checklists within the Emergency Financial First Aid Kit to create a centralized record of essential household information.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ENROLL IN AUTOMATIC BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of setting up federal benefits to be received automatically, typically through direct deposit, to ensure continuous access to funds.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REQUEST DIRECT DEPOSIT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of asking an employer to send wages or other payments directly to a bank account rather than issuing paper checks.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PRINT OR DOWNLOAD STATEMENTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of obtaining digital or physical copies of bills and account statements for financial record-keeping and preparedness.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DOWNLOAD MOBILE APPLICATIONS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of installing banking or bill pay applications on a smartphone or device for convenient online payment management and financial access.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TAKE PHOTOS OR RECORD VIDEO">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of visually documenting home contents and important documents for insurance claims and record-keeping purposes in case of damage or loss.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="KEEP CASH">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of retaining physical currency in a safe location for emergency purchases when electronic payment systems like ATMs or banks may be unavailable.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEDERAL BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Government benefits, such as Social Security and Veterans’ Assistance, that can be garnished by the Department of Education for unpaid federal student loans without a court order.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="PREPAID DEBIT CARDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Reloadable payment cards that allow users to spend only the money preloaded onto the card, useful for managing finances during emergencies.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RENT OR MORTGAGE PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Regular payments made for the use of a rented property or to repay a loan used to purchase a property, which should be documented for financial preparedness.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MEMBERSHIP FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Recurring charges for belonging to an organization or using a service, important to track for financial planning.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BANKING OR BILL PAY MOBILE APPLICATIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Software applications for smartphones or devices that allow users to manage bank accounts and pay bills electronically, facilitating financial management.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BANK ACCOUNT INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Details pertaining to a bank account, such as account numbers and routing information, vital for financial management and disaster recovery.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="STATEMENTS OF BILLS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Records providing details of financial transactions for services or products, such as utility bills or credit card statements, important for documentation.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PRIMARY JOB">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual's main source of employment and income.&gt;</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="GOVERNMENT PROGRAM">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A term sometimes falsely promoted by debt settlement companies as a "new government program" to bail out personal credit card debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DISABILITY BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial assistance provided to individuals who are unable to work due to a disability, considered a type of benefit.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL SUPPORT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Monetary aid or assistance provided by various sources, which can serve as income.&gt;</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="ALIMONY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial support paid to a former spouse after divorce or separation.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RENT OR MORTGAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Regular payments made for housing, either to a landlord (rent) or a lender (mortgage).`</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GOAL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A desired outcome or objective that an individual aims to achieve, often related to personal finance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INFORMATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Data or knowledge provided to individuals to help them make informed financial decisions.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="TOOLS AND EQUIPMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Physical or digital implements used to facilitate tasks or achieve objectives.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PROFESSIONAL ASSISTANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Expert help or advice from qualified individuals in a specific field.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TRACK SPENDING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of monitoring and recording how money is spent, often using receipts or mobile apps, to understand financial habits.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ANALYZE SPENDING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of reviewing and understanding spending patterns, typically by examining receipts and categorized expenses, to identify trends and areas for change.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="IDENTIFY AREAS TO CUT BACK">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of pinpointing specific categories of spending where reductions can be made.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SET A GOAL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of establishing a specific financial objective or desired change, as part of the Goal Setting process.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PAY BILLS ON TIME">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of remitting payment for financial obligations by their specified due dates.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="AVOID LATE FEES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of preventing the incurrence of additional charges by paying bills promptly.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREATE AN ACTION PLAN">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of developing a detailed, step-by-step strategy to achieve a particular goal.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GOAL SETTING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial planning activity of identifying specific changes an individual wishes to make regarding their financial situation, as outlined in the CFPB's tools.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYMENT DATE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The specific calendar day by which a payment is legally due, typically for a bill or loan installment.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DUE DATE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The specified calendar date by which a payment for a financial obligation, such as a bill or loan installment, is required.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="SECURED DEBT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of debt backed by an asset (collateral) that the lender can seize if the borrower defaults on payments, like home mortgages or auto loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="ASSET">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Something of value owned by an individual or business, which can be built with "good debt" or used as collateral for secured debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="HOME MORTGAGE LOAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of secured loan used to buy a home, with the home itself serving as collateral, subject to foreclosure if payments are not made.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FORECLOSE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action a lender takes to seize and sell a property (like a home) that was used as collateral for a mortgage loan when the borrower fails to make payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="REPOSSESS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act by which a lender takes back an item, such as a car, that was used as collateral for a defaulted loan</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAWN LOAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A small, quick loan obtained by providing a personal item (like jewelry or electronics) to a pawn shop as collateral. If the loan is not repaid, the shop can sell the item.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="PAWNED ITEM">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A physical item given to a lender as collateral for a pawn loan</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RENT-TO-OWN AGREEMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An agreement where an item, like a couch or television, is rented with the option to purchase, and must be returned if payments are not made</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="STORE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A retail business that offers items under rent-to-own agreements</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FUNDS YOU DEPOSIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Money placed into an account, specifically used as security for a secured credit card</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UNSECURED CREDIT CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of credit card that is not backed by collateral, often requiring a good credit history for qualification</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UNSECURED DEBT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of debt, contrasted with secured debt, that does not have an asset (collateral) attached to it.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="DEPARTMENT STORE CHARGE CARD DEBT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Money owed on a credit card issued by a department store, typically unsecured</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CO-BORROWER">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual who shares equal responsibility for repaying a loan with another borrower</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PRIMARY BORROWER">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">The main individual who takes out a loan and is primarily responsible for its repayment</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PROSPECTIVE BORROWER">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual who is considering taking out a loan and whose repayment ability a lender may be concerned about</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REPAYMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of returning borrowed money or covering an incurred debt, such as an overdraft, to a lender or financial institution.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="RISK OF CO-SIGNING">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The potential negative consequences, such as financial liability and damage to credit scores, associated with co-signing a loan</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="JOINT ACCOUNT HOLDER">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual who shares responsibility for a credit card account with another, with full obligation for payments and whose actions can affect shared debt</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAST DUE BALANCES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Amounts of money owed that have not been paid by their due date</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ADDED DEBT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Additional financial obligations incurred, potentially by an authorized user on a credit card account</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REPAYMENT OPTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Various plans offered to borrowers for repaying their student loans, which may differ in monthly payment amounts, loan periods, and eligibility criteria.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="FIXED INTEREST RATE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An interest rate that remains constant for the entire length of a loan, characteristic of federal student loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SUBSIDIZED LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of federal student loan where the government pays the interest while the student is in school, during grace periods, and during deferment periods</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FICA">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">FICA (Federal Insurance Contributions Act) contributions are mandatory deductions from wages for Social Security and Medicare, accurate as of February 2020.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MEDICARE CONTRIBUTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Medicare contributions are mandatory deductions from wages for Medicare, accurate as of February 2020.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="COURT ORDER">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal directive issued by a court that can mandate an employer to take part of an employee's paycheck for wage garnishment.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="BANK ACCOUNT GARNISHMENT">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A process where a creditor or government agency collects debt directly from an individual's bank account, potentially after obtaining a court order.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PENSION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A retirement benefit plan that may offer protections from garnishment under federal and state laws.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="RETIREMENT PLAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A savings vehicle for retirement, which may offer protections from garnishment under federal and state laws.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="STATE CHILD SUPPORT ENFORCEMENT AGENCY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A government organization responsible for enforcing child support payments, which may establish amounts due administratively without a court order for garnishment.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DISPOSABLE INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The amount of income remaining after mandatory deductions like social security and taxes, used to calculate limits on wage garnishments.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FEDERAL MINIMUM WAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The lowest hourly wage an employer can legally pay most workers, set at $7.25 and used in calculations for wage garnishment limits.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SOCIAL SECURITY DISABILITY INSURANCE (SSDI)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A federal insurance program providing benefits to disabled individuals, which can be garnished for certain government debts like back child support or federal student loans.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="SUPPLEMENTAL SECURITY INCOME (SSI)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A federal program providing monthly payments to disabled or blind individuals with limited income and resources, which a social services representative can assist with.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="FEDERAL TAX REFUNDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Money returned by the federal government to taxpayers when they have overpaid taxes, which can be reduced or eliminated by offsets for certain debts.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="TAX REFUND OFFSET">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A reduction or elimination of a federal tax refund by the IRS to pay off certain types of debts owed to a federal or state agency.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SPOUSAL SUPPORT PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payments made by one spouse to another after separation or divorce, which can be subject to garnishment.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL RIGHTS AND RESPONSIBILITIES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The legal entitlements and obligations of consumers when interacting with financial products and services.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL MARKETPLACE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The competitive environment where various financial service providers offer products and services to consumers.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="SPOTTING RED FLAGS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of recognizing and identifying warning signs or indicators that suggest a sales deal or other offer might be a scam or fraudulent activity.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="PRIVATE DEBT COLLECTOR">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A private company authorized by the IRS to collect certain overdue tax debts from individuals.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="US TREASURY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The executive department of the U.S. government responsible for managing federal finances; official payments to the IRS are directed here.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CON ARTISTS">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals who engage in fraudulent or deceptive practices to exploit others, often for financial benefit.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PROBLEM WITH A FINANCIAL PRODUCT OR SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">An issue or negative experience encountered with a financial product or service that may require resolution or complaint submission.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL NEGOTIATIONS AND TRANSACTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The processes of discussing, agreeing upon, and carrying out financial agreements, such as buying or selling financial products or services.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL SERVICES COMPANY">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An organization that provides a range of financial services, including but not limited to banking, investments, and insurance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL COUNSELOR OR ADVISER">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">A professional who provides guidance and advice on financial matters, investments, or debt management to individuals.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FOREIGN PRINCE">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">A hypothetical royal figure often featured in phishing or advance-fee fraud scams, promising wealth in exchange for initial payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOTTERY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A game of chance in which participants buy tickets for a random drawing, often featured in scams promising winnings for a fee.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT OR DEBIT CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A plastic card used for electronic financial transactions, either drawing directly from a bank account (debit) or borrowing money (credit).</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ELECTRONIC CHECK">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A digital version of a paper check, used to make payments directly from a bank account.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WIRING MONEY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The electronic transfer of funds from one person or institution to another, often irreversible and favored by scammers.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PREPAID OR GIFT CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A card pre-loaded with a specific amount of money, often requested by scammers for untraceable payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ROBOCALLS OR PRE-RECORDED MESSAGES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Automated telephone calls or voice messages, often used in scams, which legitimate debt collectors for the IRS will not use.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="AUTHENTICATION NUMBER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A unique identifier or code used to verify the legitimacy of a communication or transaction, particularly from official entities like the IRS.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SCAMMERS">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals who perpetrate scams, using deception and fraud to trick others into parting with money or personal information.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAPERWORK OR ELECTRONIC DOCUMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Formal written or digital records, contracts, or agreements that outline the terms and conditions of financial deals or services.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FAST PROFITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The promise of quick and substantial financial gains, often a characteristic of investment scams.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HIGH RETURNS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A significant financial yield or profit from an investment, frequently used as a lure by scammers.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="LITTLE OR NO RISK">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A claim that an investment or opportunity carries minimal or no potential for loss, often a deceptive characteristic of scams.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPLAINT AGAINST THE COMPANY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A formal expression of dissatisfaction or grievance filed against a business or organization, often recorded by consumer or regulatory agencies.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHOOSING FINANCIAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES MODULE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A module (Module 8) that provides guidance and steps for individuals to select appropriate financial products and services.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ATM TRANSACTION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial activity conducted at an Automated Teller Machine, such as withdrawing cash or checking a balance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBIT CARD PURCHASE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A transaction made using a debit card to buy goods or services, directly deducting funds from an associated account.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="AUTOMATIC BILL PAYMENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A regularly scheduled payment made from an account to a biller without requiring manual initiation for each payment.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ELECTRONIC WITHDRAWAL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The removal of funds from an account through electronic means.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="IN-PERSON WITHDRAWAL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The removal of funds from an account by visiting a physical bank branch or interacting with a teller.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OVERDRAFT PROTECTION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of overdraft service where overdrafts in a checking account are covered by funds transferred from a linked savings account.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ONLINE BILL PAYMENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of paying bills electronically through a bank's online platform, which requires sufficient funds to avoid overdraft fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="RECURRING PAYMENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A payment that is set up to occur repeatedly at predefined intervals, such as monthly or annually.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DIRECT BILLING ARRANGEMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A contractual agreement where a service provider or biller is authorized to directly charge an account for ongoing services or goods.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OPEN-LOOP PREPAID CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of prepaid card featuring a network logo (e.g., Visa, MasterCard) that can be used at any merchant accepting that brand.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GIFT CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of prepaid card, often closed-loop, issued by a retailer or bank for purchases at specific stores or groups of stores.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CLOSED-LOOP PREPAID CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of prepaid card that is restricted for use only at specific locations, such as a particular store or transportation system.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RELOADABLE PREPAID CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of prepaid card that allows additional funds to be loaded onto it multiple times after its initial funding.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="GENERAL PURPOSE RELOADABLE CARD (GPR CARD)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A common type of open-loop and reloadable prepaid card, often used for everyday spending and direct deposit.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GOVERNMENT BENEFIT CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A prearranged prepaid card used by a government agency to disburse benefits to eligible individuals.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="TEMPORARY ASSISTANCE FOR NEEDY FAMILIES (TANF)">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A federal program in the United States that provides temporary financial assistance and work opportunities to families with dependent children.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="SUPPLEMENTAL NUTRITION ASSISTANCE PROGRAM">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A federal food assistance program in the United States that provides benefits to eligible low-income individuals and families to supplement their grocery budgets.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="CON ARTISTS AND SCAMMERS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals or groups who employ creative and innovative schemes and appeals to defraud people of their money.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PROFITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial gain, often promised to be fast and high by scammers to entice investments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="USA.GOV/STATE-CONSUMER">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A government website that provides links to state consumer protection offices for individuals seeking assistance or information.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="VIRUS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Malicious software that scammers can use to infiltrate computers or devices to steal sensitive personal data.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMER.FTC.GOV/SCAM-ALERTS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A website maintained by the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) where consumers can search for and report information about common scams.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="IDENTIFICATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Documents or information required by financial institutions to verify an individual's identity, crucial for activities like opening an account.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ITIN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Individual Taxpayer Identification Number, an alternative identification number that may allow individuals without an SSN to open certain types of bank accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NO-INTEREST ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of bank account that does not earn any interest on the funds held within it, sometimes offered to individuals without an SSN or ITIN.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MONTHLY FEE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A fixed, recurring charge automatically deducted from the card balance each month for maintaining the card account, sometimes waived if certain conditions like direct deposit are met.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="PER-CHECK OR TRANSACTION FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Charges applied by a financial institution for each check written or for individual transactions made from an account.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOW BALANCE ALERTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A service provided by financial institutions that notifies an account holder when their account balance falls below a predefined threshold, helping to prevent overdrafts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OPENING DEPOSIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The initial amount of money required to be deposited into a new account to activate it or meet the minimum opening requirement.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MONITORING ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The regular review and oversight of an account's activities, balance, and transactions, often done online or through a mobile app, to manage finances and detect issues.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GATHERING DOCUMENTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of collecting all necessary paperwork, such as identification and financial records, required for opening a bank account or other financial activities.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RESEARCHING ACCOUNT TERMS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of investigating and understanding the conditions, costs, and limitations associated with a financial product or service before committing to it.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TRACKING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The activity of monitoring and recording financial information, such as income, benefits, and spending, for budgeting or tax purposes.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MANAGE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of overseeing and controlling one's financial resources, including income and benefits, to achieve financial goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYMENT METHOD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A mechanism or system used to transfer money from one party to another, such as cash, checks, or direct deposits, each with its own benefits and risks.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CANCELLATION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of revoking or invalidating a financial instrument, such as a check, often done if it is lost or stolen.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REISSUANCE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of providing a new financial instrument, such as a check, after the original has been lost, stolen, or canceled.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHECK CLEARANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The process by which a financial institution verifies the validity of a check and transfers funds from the payer's account to the payee's account, typically involving a waiting period.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SPLIT DEPOSIT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of dividing a single deposit, such as a direct deposit, into multiple accounts, like checking and savings, to facilitate saving.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TOTAL MONTHLY DEBT PAYMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The sum of all monthly payments for various debts, including credit cards, student loans, auto loans, other loans, and court-ordered fixed payments like child support.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ADDITIONAL CREDIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">New credit opportunities or loans that an individual may seek, the approval for which can be affected by their existing debt obligations and debt-to-income ratio.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COURT-ORDERED FIXED PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Mandatory recurring payments determined by a legal body, such as child support, which are counted as debt for the purpose of calculating an individual's total monthly debt payment.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GROSS MONTHLY INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual's total income before taxes or insurance deductions, representing the full amount of earnings used as a baseline for financial calculations like the debt-to-income ratio.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HOME MORTGAGE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A loan specifically for purchasing real estate, where the property itself serves as collateral, and its payments are a significant component of debt for homeowners.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MORTGAGE LENDERS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial institutions specializing in providing loans for real estate purchases, who specifically evaluate both total debt-to-income and mortgage debt-to-income ratios.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MORTGAGE DEBT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The outstanding principal and interest owed on a home mortgage, used to calculate the mortgage debt-to-income ratio specifically for homeowners.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MORTGAGE DEBT-TO-INCOME RATIO">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial metric specific to homeowners, measuring the portion of gross monthly income allocated solely to the principal and interest payments on a home mortgage.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONDO OR HOMEOWNER ASSOCIATION FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Mandatory recurring payments made by property owners to an association for the maintenance and management of common areas and services, which may or may not be included in a monthly mortgage payment.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HUD HOUSING COUNSELOR">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A certified professional providing guidance and assistance on housing-related financial matters, including mortgage debt management, often sought when debt ratios are high.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REPAYING DEBT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of systematically returning borrowed money to lenders according to an agreed-upon schedule or strategy, with the goal of eliminating financial obligations.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HIGH DEBT-TO-INCOME RATIO RISK">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk that a high debt-to-income ratio may make it difficult for an individual to obtain additional credit due to creditors' concerns about their ability to handle more debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MISSED PAYMENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of failing to make a scheduled payment on a bill or debt by its due date, which can lead to various consequences.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A charge or payment for a service or privilege, such as a fee for check cashing services or a penalty fee for early withdrawal from a CD.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="NEGOTIATE DUE DATE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of discussing and agreeing upon a new date for a bill payment with a creditor to better align with income receipt.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOSS OF ASSETS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk of losing valuable possessions such as a car (repossession) or a house (foreclosure/eviction) due to unpaid debts or late payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HOUSING OR CREDIT COUNSELOR">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">A certified professional who provides guidance on managing housing-related financial issues and debts, helping individuals build payment plans.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DISPUTE DEBT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of formally challenging the validity or accuracy of a claimed debt, asserting that it is not owed or is incorrect. The text outlines steps for the debtor to dispute a debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT COLLECTOR HARASSMENT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk of being subjected to illegal and abusive tactics by debt collectors, such as repeated calls or false statements.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SUBMIT COMPLAINT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of formally reporting an issue or grievance, such as unfair debt collection practices, to a regulatory body like the CFPB.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BEING SUED">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A legal event where an individual is taken to court, potentially related to unpaid debts or other financial obligations.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CHILD IDENTITY THEFT INQUIRY FORM">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific form available on TransUnion's website for parents or legal guardians to inquire about a minor's credit file in cases of suspected identity theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DISPUTE ERRORS TOOL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A resource designed to help individuals initiate the process of challenging inaccuracies or errors found on their credit reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT SCORING COMPANIES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
