  <data key="d1">The overarching federal government body that includes DHS and FEMA, and whose endorsement is not implied by the EFFAK.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="VIOLATION OF FEDERAL LAW">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The prohibited act of using the Department of Homeland Security's seal or other visual identities without proper authorization, which is against Federal law (e.g., 18 U.S.C. §§ 506, 701, 1017).</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CLOSED-LOOP CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of card, often a prepaid card, designed for use within a specific system or location, such as public transportation or a college campus, and typically lacks a network logo.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="OPEN-LOOP CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of card, often a prepaid card, that can be used at any retail location or ATM that accepts its associated network brand.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="GENERAL PURPOSE RELOADABLE CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A common type of open-loop, reloadable prepaid card, often abbreviated as GPR Card.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="GPR CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An abbreviation for General Purpose Reloadable Card, which is a common type of open-loop, reloadable prepaid card.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="NON-RELOADABLE CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of card that initially cannot have additional funds loaded onto it, though some may become reloadable after a registration process.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ELECTRONIC BENEFITS TRANSFER CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of government benefits card used for needs-based assistance programs, such as TANF and SNAP.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="EBT CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An abbreviation for Electronic Benefits Transfer card, which is a specific type of government benefits card used for needs-based programs.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="COLLEGE ID CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An identification card issued by an educational institution that may also function as a prepaid card, either closed-loop for campus use or open-loop for general retail.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCOUNT BALANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The current amount of money available in a financial account or on a card, which can be checked through various methods.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CUSTOMER SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A department or function providing assistance and information to customers regarding their financial products, often by phone or online.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="AUTOMATED PHONE SYSTEM">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A system that allows callers to access information or perform tasks through pre-recorded prompts without direct human interaction, often used for routine inquiries like checking card balances.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CUSTOMER SERVICE AGENT">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">An individual employed by a financial institution or card provider to assist customers with inquiries, issues, or account management.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PREPAID CARD PROVIDER">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The company or institution responsible for issuing, managing, and servicing prepaid cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CELL PHONE CARRIER">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A telecommunications company that provides mobile phone services, which may charge fees for text messages related to financial account alerts.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PAPER STATEMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Printed records or summaries of financial transactions and account activity provided to account holders, which should be reviewed regularly for accuracy.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="VIRTUAL SET ASIDE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A feature on some prepaid cards that allows users to electronically earmark or separate funds for specific savings goals, making them less available for immediate spending.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SAVINGS WALLET">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Another term for a Virtual Set Aside, a feature within a prepaid card account designed to hold funds separate for savings purposes.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SPENDING MONEY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The general action of using available funds to purchase goods, services, or make payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CARD NETWORK LOGO">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A brand symbol (e.g., Visa, MasterCard) displayed on a card, indicating the payment processing network it uses to facilitate transactions.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CARRY A BALANCE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The practice of not paying the full outstanding amount on a credit card statement by the due date, resulting in interest charges on the unpaid portion.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ELECTRONIC PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Methods of transferring funds electronically, records of which are used for income tracking.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GOVERNMENT PROGRAM BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial assistance or services provided by government programs, such as Disability insurance, Social Security, TANF, and SNAP, which are considered sources of income.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DISABILITY INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of government program benefit, including SSI and SSDI, that provides income in the event of an individual becoming disabled.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BENEFITS.GOV">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A government website recommended by the CFPB for individuals to check if they qualify for additional benefits.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CUT BACK">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of reducing spending or expenses in identified areas to improve financial management, as suggested by the Spending Tracker tool.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="JOBS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An example of an income source from employment mentioned in the cash flow management instructions.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SELF-EMPLOYMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The state of earning income directly from one's own business or profession rather than as an employee, serving as an income source.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="SEASONAL WORK">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Employment that is available only during certain seasons of the year, such as shoveling or harvesting, serving as an income source.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="HELP FROM FAMILY OR FRIENDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial assistance or support received from relatives or acquaintances, serving as an income source.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BILL PAYMENT SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Services provided by financial institutions that enable customers to pay their bills electronically or through other methods, potentially incurring fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="NOTARY SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Additional services sometimes offered by financial institutions to authenticate documents and signatures, which may incur a cost.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SAFE DEPOSIT BOXES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Secure containers offered by financial institutions for customers to store valuables, typically for an annual fee.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEE FOR GOING BELOW MINIMUM BALANCE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A penalty incurred by account holders when their balance drops below a specified minimum requirement.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEE FOR INACTIVITY">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A charge applied to an account that has not seen any activity for a specified period, serving as a penalty for non-use.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAY BALANCE IN FULL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of remitting the entire outstanding amount owed on a credit account, usually to avoid interest charges.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHECK CASHING">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The service of converting a check into physical currency, often offered by financial service providers and potentially incurring a fee.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHECK ACCOUNT BALANCES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of verifying the current amount of money in a financial account, which can be done via phone, online, or a mobile app.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPARING FINANCIAL SERVICE PROVIDERS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of evaluating different financial institutions and their offerings to choose the most suitable one based on needs like fees, services, and convenience.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DEPOSIT (ACTION)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of placing money into a financial account, which may incur a fee.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MOBILE APPS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Digital applications used to keep track of bills and spending, and to send money. They may charge fees and require personal information or access to financial accounts. Users should not use them on public Wi-Fi and should protect them with strong passwords.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PUBLIC WI-FI">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">An insecure internet connection that poses a risk for conducting financial transactions, and should be avoided for such activities.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TWO-FACTOR AUTHENTICATION">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A two-step security process (password plus a code sent via text/email) offered by many financial service providers to provide an extra layer of protection for accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REMOTE ACCESS FEATURE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A capability on most mobile devices that allows users to lock the device, delete sensitive information, or activate an alarm if the device is lost or stolen, requiring activation by the user.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL TRANSACTIONS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of transferring money or managing financial resources through digital tools. It should not be conducted on public Wi-Fi due to security risks.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SCORING COMPANIES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Organizations, such as Fair Isaac Corporation and VantageScore Solutions, that develop and implement mathematical formulas to calculate credit scores.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="AMOUNTS OWED">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A significant factor in FICO scores, encompassing an individual's total debts and their credit utilization rate.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LENGTH OF CREDIT HISTORY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A factor in FICO scores that measures the duration of an individual's credit accounts, providing evidence of long-term credit behavior.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NEW CREDIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A factor in FICO scores that tracks recent credit inquiries and newly opened credit accounts, which can indicate a high demand for credit.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TYPES OF CREDIT USED">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A factor in FICO scores that considers the variety of credit accounts an individual manages, such as revolving credit and installment loans, contributing to a "credit mix.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT INQUIRIES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Records of requests for an individual's credit report, made by creditors, which can impact "New credit" and "Recent credit behavior and inquiries" scores.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT MIX">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The combination of different types of credit accounts (e.g., revolving and installment) held by an individual, which can positively influence credit scores.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="AGE AND TYPE OF CREDIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A "highly influential" factor for VantageScore, combining the duration of credit accounts and the variety of credit types.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PERCENT OF CREDIT LIMIT USED">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A "highly influential" factor for VantageScore, representing the proportion of available credit that is currently being utilized.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TOTAL BALANCES/DEBT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A "moderately influential" factor for VantageScore, representing the overall amount of money an individual owes across all accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RECENT CREDIT BEHAVIOR AND INQUIRIES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A "less influential" factor for VantageScore, encompassing recent credit activity and requests for credit reports.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDITWORTHINESS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An evaluation of an individual's ability and reliability to repay financial obligations, primarily assessed through credit scores.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MYFICO.COM">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">An online resource providing information about FICO credit scores, referenced as a source for FICO's calculation methodology.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OFFERING CREDIT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action taken by financial institutions to provide credit products to consumers, with decisions often guided by an applicant's credit score.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CHECKING CREDIT REPORTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of an individual reviewing their own credit reports, which does not negatively affect their credit score.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAYING FOR CREDIT SCORES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of purchasing a credit score from a third-party provider, though these may differ from scores used by lenders.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GETTING FREE CREDIT SCORES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of obtaining a credit score without charge, often provided by credit card companies or when a loan is denied based on the score.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DENYING A LOAN">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The decision by a lender to refuse a loan application, often directly influenced by the applicant's credit score.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BUILDING CREDIT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The ongoing process of establishing, improving, and maintaining a positive credit history to achieve higher credit scores.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FIXING ERRORS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of identifying and correcting inaccuracies or discrepancies found within a credit report.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="APPLYING FOR A LOAN">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The formal process initiated by an individual to request financial borrowing from a lender.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NON-PAYMENT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The failure to make required payments on credit accounts, leading to severe negative consequences for credit scores and financial standing.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HIGH DEMAND FOR CREDIT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A situation indicated by a large number of recent credit inquiries, suggesting financial strain or excessive borrowing, which can lower credit scores.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HIGH CREDIT USAGE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The practice of utilizing a significant portion of available credit, which is negatively viewed by credit scoring models and can lead to lower scores.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ATM WITHDRAWAL FEE (IN-NETWORK)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The fee charged for withdrawing money from an ATM that belongs to the card's designated network.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ATM WITHDRAWAL FEE (OUT-OF-NETWORK)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The fee charged for withdrawing money from an ATM that is outside of the card's designated network.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RELOAD FEE (CASH AT RETAIL)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The charge for adding cash to a prepaid card at a retail store location.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CURRENCY CONVERSION FEE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A fee, usually a percentage, charged for spending or withdrawing money in a foreign country.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAPER STATEMENT FEE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A charge for opting to receive physical, mailed statements of card transactions instead of electronic ones.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="LOST, STOLEN, OR DAMAGED CARD">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The situation where a card is compromised, potentially leading to unauthorized charges and requiring replacement.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UNAUTHORIZED CHARGES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Transactions made on a card account without the cardholder's permission, which can occur if a card is lost or stolen.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ERROR RESOLUTION RIGHTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Protections that allow cardholders to recover money lost due to errors or theft, particularly for registered prepaid cards or payroll cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MONTHLY CARD FEE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A recurring charge for maintaining a card account, which some prepaid cards impose and payroll cards typically do not.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INACTIVITY FEES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Charges applied to an account or card if there is no activity over a specified period, as can occur with payroll cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ADDITIONAL CARD FOR AUTHORIZED USER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A supplementary card issued to another individual, allowing them to spend from the primary card account.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CARD CANCELLATION FEE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A fee that may be charged upon the termination of a card account, or specifically for requesting a check for the remaining balance on a cancelled card.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="UNUSED BALANCE CHECK FEE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The charge for receiving a check for any remaining funds on a card after it has been canceled.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BILL PAYMENT FEE (PROVIDER WEBSITE)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The charge for paying bills through the card provider's official website.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CARD-TO-CARD TRANSFER FEE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A fee for transferring funds electronically from one prepaid card to another, also known as a person-to-person transfer fee.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="TRANSACTION DECLINED DUE TO INSUFFICIENT FUNDS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The rejection of a transaction because the card account lacks sufficient money to cover the purchase or withdrawal.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIAL SHORTFALL">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The condition where an individual or household does not have sufficient funds to cover their necessary expenses, leading to difficulties in "making ends meet.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CREATING A CASH FLOW BUDGET (PROCESS)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The activity of developing a detailed weekly financial plan that projects all expected income and expenses to manage money effectively and avoid shortfalls.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPROVING CASH FLOW (PROCESS)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The activity of implementing strategies, such as cutting expenses or adjusting payment timings, to enhance the balance between incoming and outgoing money and achieve a positive cash flow.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ADJUSTING YOUR CASH FLOW (PROCESS)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The activity of modifying existing financial plans or spending patterns, including setting new target spending levels and rescheduling expenses, to better manage the timing and amount of income and expenses.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="MONTHLY BUDGET">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A Monthly Budget is a financial plan that tracks income and expenses over a one-month period to help manage finances effectively and pay bills on time.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="SUBMIT A COMPLAINT (PROCESS)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The formal procedure of reporting a problem or dissatisfaction regarding a financial product or service to a relevant authority, such as the CFPB.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CASH FLOW BUDGET (TOOL)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A structured financial planning tool or document that itemizes and projects income and expenses on a weekly basis, differing from a traditional monthly budget.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="NEEDS, WANTS, AND OBLIGATIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A categorization system for expenses, distinguishing between essential expenditures (needs), desired but non-essential purchases (wants), and committed payments (obligations).</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
