  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">A US state where State Farm offers services, and where pricing and coverage options may vary.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="WYOMING">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">A US state where State Farm offers services, and where pricing and coverage options may vary.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="AUTO INSURANCE RATES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The costs associated with auto insurance policies, which are calculated based on various factors and can fluctuate.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RISING AUTO INSURANCE PREMIUMS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The financial risk associated with increasing costs of auto insurance premiums, which can impact policyholders.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ELIGIBILITY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The conditions or qualifications that must be met for a customer to be approved for certain insurance coverages or discounts, which may vary by state.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RECURRING BILLS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Regular, repeated expenses such as rent, utilities, car payments, and insurance that typically have fixed due dates.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CASH FLOW TOOLS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Methods or strategies used to manage and balance the inflow and outflow of money over a period, detailed in Module 5.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BILL PAYMENT METHODS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Various ways to pay financial obligations, including cash, checks, credit/debit cards, money orders, online/mobile payments, and prepaid cards, each with benefits and drawbacks.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CREDIT OR DEBIT CARDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Payment cards that allow users to either borrow funds (credit) or spend money directly from their bank account (debit); credit cards may incur interest if not paid in full.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MONEY ORDERS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A payment order for a specified amount of money, useful for making payments without a checking account, but often with fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ONLINE OR MOBILE BILL PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Electronic methods of paying bills via the internet or a mobile device, offering convenience but requiring sufficient funds to avoid rejected payments.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCESS TO CREDIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The ability for an individual to obtain loans or other forms of credit, influenced by their payment and credit record.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REJECTED PAYMENT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A payment that is not processed or accepted, often due to insufficient funds in the account, which can lead to overdraft fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NEGATIVE BANKING HISTORY">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A record of problematic past interactions with banking institutions, such as frequent overdrafts, which may prevent opening a new checking account.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FUNDS STOLEN">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The danger of physical money, particularly cash, being illegally taken from its owner.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COUCH">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An example of an item that can be acquired through a rent-to-own agreement</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CO-SIGNING A LOAN">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of agreeing to repay a loan if the primary borrower defaults</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOAN DOCUMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Official papers containing the terms and conditions of a loan, which should be read carefully</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ADDITIONAL CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A secondary card issued for an authorized user on an existing account.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DATA BREACH">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">An incident where sensitive information is exposed to unauthorized parties, which may lead to identity theft and warrant an initial fraud alert.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OFFERS OF CREDIT OR INSURANCE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Pre-screened solicitations for credit cards, loans, or insurance policies that credit reporting companies are required to remove consumers from when an extended fraud alert is in place.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NO CONSISTENCY">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A red flag where different staff or salespeople provide conflicting information regarding pricing or other essential details of a financial product or service.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WON'T PUT IT IN WRITING">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A red flag where clear information about financial products or services, especially pricing or terms, is not provided in writing despite requests.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PUSHED TO PURCHASE IMMEDIATELY">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A red flag where a consumer is pressured to make an immediate, often big-ticket, purchase with urgency, implying the offer is fleeting.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BIG-TICKET PURCHASE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A term for an expensive item or service, synonymous with a large purchase, that typically demands careful financial consideration.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="STEERING AND COERCING">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A red flag involving aggressive sales tactics used to manipulate a consumer into a high-cost loan, even if they qualify for a regular prime loan.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WARRANTIES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Guarantees on products that promise repair or replacement, which can be unnecessary add-ons pushed by lenders.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MONITORING SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An add-on product that lenders may insist on or imply borrowers must buy, which gets incorporated into the loan amount and accrues interest.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PRICING">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The specific costs and rates associated with financial products and services, which should be consistent and transparent.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INSURANCE AGENCIES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Organizations that provide insurance services and have established rules and procedures for handling situations involving stolen documents or illegally accessed accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="STOLEN OR ILLEGALLY ACCESSED DOCUMENTS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk that important documents or an EFFAK might be taken without authorization or accessed unlawfully, necessitating immediate contact with financial institutions and insurance agencies.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MONITORING ACCOUNTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The activity of regularly reviewing and checking financial account activity for unusual or suspicious patterns, recommended by the FTC for individuals and performed by financial institutions.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CLOSING ACCOUNTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action taken by financial institutions to deactivate or terminate a customer's account, often as a security measure following unauthorized activity or theft.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REOPENING ACCOUNTS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action taken by financial institutions to reactivate a customer's account, typically after security issues have been addressed and resolved.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="UNUSUAL OR SUSPICIOUS ACTIVITY">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Patterns or occurrences in financial account activity that are not typical for the account holder and may indicate fraud, theft, or other security breaches.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOCAL EMERGENCY MANAGER">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">An official or individual responsible for coordinating and managing preparedness, response, and recovery efforts for emergencies within a specific geographic area or community.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PROTECT AND RECOVER FROM EMERGENCY OR DISASTER">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The dual actions of safeguarding oneself and assets from potential harm during an emergency or disaster, and subsequently taking steps to restore conditions to normalcy or an improved state.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FAMILY EMERGENCY PLAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A structured document or set of guidelines developed by a household to ensure safety and coordinated action before, during, and after an emergency.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EMERGENCY SUPPLY KIT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A pre-assembled collection of essential items, such as food, water, and medical supplies, recommended to be sufficient for at least 72 hours of self-sufficiency during an emergency.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GET INVOLVED IN COMMUNITY'S PREPAREDNESS ACTIVITIES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of participating in local initiatives, exercises, and drills designed to enhance the collective readiness and resilience of a community against emergencies.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TRAINED VOLUNTEERS">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals who have received specific training to assist in emergency response, relief efforts, and community rebuilding following a disaster.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EMERGENCY PLANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">General term for structured documents or strategies developed by organizations like schools or workplaces to guide actions and ensure safety during an emergency.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SCHOOLS">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Educational institutions that need to establish and implement emergency plans to protect students and staff during various incidents.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WORKPLACE">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">A location where individuals are employed, which should have established emergency plans to ensure the safety and continuity of operations for its employees.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NEIGHBORHOOD">
  <data key="d0">GEO</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific geographical area within a larger community, which should be considered when assessing disaster risks and developing local emergency plans.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COMMUNITY PREPAREDNESS EXERCISES AND DRILLS">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">Organized simulation activities conducted within a community to practice emergency response procedures and test the effectiveness of preparedness plans.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BUSINESS OWNERS">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals who own and operate commercial enterprises, for whom the U.S. Small Business Administration provides resources on emergency preparedness and disaster recovery.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FINANCIALLY PREPARE FOR EMERGENCY OR DISASTER">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The proactive step taken by individuals or businesses to secure financial stability and resources to mitigate the impact of, and facilitate recovery from, emergencies and disasters.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PLANNING FOR EMERGENCIES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The comprehensive process of strategizing and developing structured approaches to anticipate, respond to, and recover from various types of emergencies and disasters.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BUSINESS LEADERS">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals in positions of authority within businesses who are responsible for implementing preparedness strategies and guiding their organizations through emergency planning.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TAKE ACTION (PREPAREDNESS)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A general step in emergency preparedness that refers to implementing the strategies and measures outlined in a developed plan.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BE RECOGNIZED AND INSPIRE OTHERS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A step in the Ready Business program encouraging businesses to serve as exemplary models of preparedness and motivate other organizations to adopt similar practices.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONTINUITY OF OPERATIONS (COOP)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A strategic framework or plan designed to ensure that essential business functions can continue to operate with minimal interruption during and after a significant disruption or disaster.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CLEANUP (AFTER DISASTER)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The immediate and ongoing process of removing debris, clearing affected areas, and initiating restoration efforts following a disaster event.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RECOVERY (AFTER DISASTER)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The long-term process following a disaster that involves restoring physical, social, economic, and environmental aspects of a community or business to an acceptable or improved condition.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="STATEMENTS AND ACCOUNT ACTIVITY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The records of financial transactions, balances, and other movements within an account, which should be regularly reviewed for unusual or suspicious patterns to ensure security.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ATM ACCESS LIMITS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Restrictions imposed by certain cards on the number of times an ATM can be accessed within a 24-hour period.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEDERAL CONSUMER PROTECTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Safeguards provided by the federal government to protect consumers from financial risks like unauthorized transfers or errors.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAPER-BASED BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Traditional forms of government assistance, such as paper coupons or vouchers, replaced by EBT cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CASH BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A form of financial assistance provided as cash, which can be sent to a bank account or prepaid card.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OWN PREPAID CARD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A personal prepaid card owned by an individual, which can be used to receive cash benefits to prevent them from expiring.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ONE-TIME ACTIVITY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">An activity performed once, such as selling items, to generate income.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INCREASE YOUR REFUND">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial goal or outcome achieved by claiming additional tax credits.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="USE YOUR SKILLS AND RESOURCES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A strategy for increasing income by leveraging personal abilities and available assets.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EARN EXTRA MONEY WITH SKILLS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The strategy of using personal abilities like providing childcare or doing yard work to generate additional income.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="START A PART-TIME SMALL BUSINESS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The strategy of using talents or hobbies to create and sell items online or establish a small business for additional income.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FRIENDS OR RELATIVES">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals with whom one can exchange services or rent out a room.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="POTENTIAL SERVICE OR INACTIVITY FEES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Charges that might be applied for accessing wages or benefits through certain methods or due to a lack of activity on a card.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="ERRORS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Mistakes or inaccuracies in financial transactions or account management that may lead to financial loss, with varying levels of protection depending on the card type.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="ELECTRONIC BENEFITS TRANSFER (EBT) CARDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific type of government benefits card replacing paper-based benefits, used for needs-based programs like TANF and SNAP, with varying terms by state and program.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="LIMITS ON CARD USAGE">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Restrictions on where EBT cards can be used or what types of purchases can be made with them.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="NO PROTECTIONS FOR UNAUTHORIZED TRANSACTIONS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The absence of safeguards for returning funds taken through unauthorized transactions or errors, a potential vulnerability for some EBT cards.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="BENEFITS EXPIRING">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The possibility that certain benefits will be lost if they are not used within a specified amount of time.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="LOSING BENEFITS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The outcome of benefits expiring or being taken through unauthorized means, resulting in the forfeiture of financial assistance.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="TAX CREDITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Amounts that can be directly subtracted from taxes owed, potentially leading to an increased tax refund.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="REFUND">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Money returned to the consumer by a remittance transfer provider, especially in cases where errors occurred and money never arrived.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="SELLING ITEMS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">A one-time activity to generate income, such as through a garage sale or online sales.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PROVIDING CHILDCARE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Earning income by offering services to look after children.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="DOING YARD WORK">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Earning income by performing outdoor maintenance tasks like gardening or mowing.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="TRADE THINGS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Exchanging goods or services with others, often without direct monetary payment (bartering).</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="RUN ERRANDS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Performing various tasks or deliveries for others, often in exchange for a fee.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="BECOME A DRIVER FOR A RIDE-SHARING SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Earning income by transporting passengers using an online platform that connects drivers with riders.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="RENT A ROOM">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The strategy of generating income by leasing a room in one's home to a friend or relative, if permitted by the housing agreement.</data>
  <data key="d2">3</data>
</node>
<node id="BILL PAY SERVICE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">An online facility that enables users to pay bills electronically using funds from their card or bank account.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="STANDARD REPAYMENT PLAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A loan repayment plan for federal student loans where payments are fixed at a minimum of $50 per month and remain constant each year. The loan period is up to 10 years, or up to 30 years for consolidated loans, leading to less overall payment than other plans.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="GRADUATED PAYMENT PLAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A loan repayment plan for federal student loans where payments start low and gradually increase every two years based on the remaining loan balance. The loan period is up to 10 years, or up to 30 years for consolidated loans, resulting in higher total payments over time than the Standard 10-year plan.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="EXTENDED REPAYMENT PLAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A loan repayment plan with a longer loan period of up to 25 years and smaller monthly payments, which can be fixed or graduated. Borrowers must have more than $30,000 in outstanding federal loans to qualify.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSOLIDATED LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Student loans that have been combined into a single new loan, which may allow for longer repayment periods (up to 30 years) under certain repayment plans.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="BORROWERS">
  <data key="d0">PERSON</data>
  <data key="d1">Individuals who have taken out federal student loans and are responsible for their repayment, potentially qualifying for various repayment plans and temporary options.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REVISED PAY AS YOU EARN (REPAYE)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An income-driven repayment plan for federal Direct Loans where payments are set at 10 percent of discretionary income, recalculated annually. Payments can be as low as $0. The loan period is up to 20 or 25 years, after which any remaining amount is forgiven, though it may be subject to income tax.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PAY AS YOU EARN (PAYE)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An income-driven repayment plan for federal Direct Loans where payments are set at up to 10 percent of discretionary income, recalculated annually. Payments can be as low as $0 and will never be higher than the Standard repayment plan. The loan period is up to 20 years, after which any remaining amount is forgiven, though it may be subject to income tax. Requires partial financial hardship and specific borrower dates.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INCOME-BASED REPAYMENT (IBR)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An income-driven repayment plan for federal student loans (excluding Parent Plus loans) where payments are based on up to 10% or 15% of discretionary income, recalculated annually. Loan periods are 20 or 25 years, after which remaining amounts are forgiven (potentially taxable). Requires partial financial hardship.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PARENT PLUS LOANS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of federal student loan that is explicitly not eligible for the Income-Based Repayment (IBR) plan.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DISCRETIONARY INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial metric used in income-driven repayment plans, typically defined as the difference between adjusted gross income and 150 percent of the Federal Poverty Guidelines.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="FORGIVENESS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The cancellation of the remaining balance of a student loan after a specified period of repayment under certain plans, though the forgiven amount may be subject to income tax.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INCOME TAX LIABILITY">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The obligation to pay taxes, specifically noted for potentially applying to amounts of student loans that are forgiven under income-driven repayment plans.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PARTIAL FINANCIAL HARDSHIP">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">A condition a borrower must demonstrate to qualify for specific income-driven repayment plans, indicating that their income is insufficient to make payments under other standard plans.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ACCRUING INTEREST">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Interest that accumulates on a loan balance, particularly during periods when payments are temporarily stopped or reduced, such as deferment for unsubsidized loans or forbearance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OCTOBER 1, 2007">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific date that serves as an eligibility cutoff for borrowers seeking to qualify as a "new borrower" for the Pay As You Earn (PAYE) repayment plan.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OCTOBER 1, 2011">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific date that serves as an eligibility cutoff for borrowers seeking to qualify for the Pay As You Earn (PAYE) repayment plan, requiring a Direct Loan payout on or after this date.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="JULY 1, 2014">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific date that differentiates the payment percentage and loan period terms for the Income-Based Repayment (IBR) plan, depending on when a borrower's Direct Loan was issued.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RISK OF HIGHER TOTAL PAYMENTS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The potential outcome in some repayment plans (e.g., Graduated, PAYE, IBR) where the total amount paid over the life of the loan exceeds that of the Standard 10-year repayment plan due to longer repayment periods or different payment structures.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RISK OF INCOME TAX ON FORGIVEN AMOUNT">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The financial risk that borrowers may incur income tax on the amount of their student loan that is forgiven under specific repayment plans.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INTEREST ACCUMULATION RISK">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">The risk that interest will build up on a loan, particularly on unsubsidized loans during deferment or on any loan during forbearance, increasing the total amount owed.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LOAN PERIOD">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The total duration over which a loan is scheduled to be repaid, varying across different repayment plans.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SHORT-TERM STRATEGIES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">Approaches and methods for finding additional money or managing immediate financial needs in a tight situation, as suggested by the CFPB's guide.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="PARKING TICKETS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Fines issued for violating parking regulations, which should be paid on time to avoid additional charges.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OTHER FINES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Penalties for breaking rules or laws, similar to parking tickets, that incur additional charges if not paid promptly.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ADDITIONAL CHARGES">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Extra costs or penalties that may be incurred if initial fees or fines are not paid on time.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COST PER SERVING">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A metric used when buying groceries to compare the price of an item relative to its portion size, helping to identify true savings.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SALES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Promotional events where goods or services are offered at reduced prices, presenting an opportunity to save money on needed items.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WEATHERIZATION INCENTIVES OR PROGRAMS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial benefits or government-supported initiatives aimed at encouraging energy efficiency improvements in homes, which can help cut utility costs.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CHECK-CASHING SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Businesses that provide the service of cashing checks for a fee, identified as a source of avoidable fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NO-FEE BANK ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A type of bank account that does not charge regular service fees, offering a way to avoid banking costs.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MAGAZINE SUBSCRIPTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Recurring payments for regular delivery of magazines, identified as a potential cost to cut if not actively used.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MOVIE-STREAMING SERVICES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Subscription-based services providing access to a library of movies and TV shows, identified as a potential cost to cut if not actively used.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HABITS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Established patterns of behavior, especially those related to spending (e.g., cooking at home vs. eating out), that can be changed to save money.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SKILLS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Abilities or proficiencies, such as cooking, crafts, or language, that individuals possess and can leverage to earn extra money.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TRADEOFFS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Situations in financial decision-making where choosing one option necessitates giving up another, requiring careful assessment.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ADD-ON PRODUCTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A general category of unnecessary items, such as additional insurance, unneeded warranties, and monitoring services, that lenders may insist on or imply borrowers must buy, which get incorporated into the loan amount and accrue interest.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LIFE OF THE LOAN">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The full duration or period over which a loan is scheduled to be repaid by the borrower.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPLAINTS (FINANCIAL)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Formal expressions of dissatisfaction or grievance submitted by consumers regarding issues with financial products or services.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MARKETPLACE (FINANCIAL)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The economic environment or system where financial products and services are offered, exchanged, and consumed, and where problems experienced by people are identified.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CFPB COMPLAINT PORTAL">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">The online platform provided by the CFPB at consumerfinance.gov/complaint, where consumers can submit and track the status of their complaints.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPANY RESPONSE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The formal communication from a financial company detailing the steps taken or that will be taken to address an issue identified in a consumer's complaint.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="COMPLAINT PUBLICATION">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act by the CFPB of making anonymized information about consumer complaints, such as the subject and date, publicly available on its Consumer Complaint Database.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CONSUMER REVIEW (OF RESPONSE)">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process where a consumer evaluates a financial company's response to their complaint and provides feedback to the CFPB within 60 days.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="FEEDBACK (CONSUMER)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Input provided by consumers to the CFPB regarding the complaint process or the company's response to their issue.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HOW TO SUBMIT A COMPLAINT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The outlined instructions and available methods (online, phone, mail) for consumers to initiate and file a complaint with the CFPB.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TOOLS (CFPB TOOLKIT)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">Specific components, resources, or instruments included within the "Your Money, Your Goals: A financial empowerment toolkit" prepared by the CFPB.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EDUCATIONAL MATERIALS (CFPB)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">The various resources, content, and materials prepared by the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau for educational and informational purposes for the public.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="THIRD-PARTY SITES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">Websites operated by entities other than the CFPB, which may be linked or referenced in CFPB materials but are not controlled or guaranteed for accuracy by the CFPB.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="THIRD-PARTY ENTITIES">
  <data key="d0">ORGANIZATION</data>
  <data key="d1">General term for external individuals or organizations whose resources or content may be linked or referenced by the CFPB, but are not endorsed or vetted by the CFPB.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="GUIDANCE OR ADVICE (FINANCIAL)">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Professional recommendations or counsel related to financial matters, typically provided by qualified professionals such as accountants or certified financial advisors.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ORGANIZATION'S POLICIES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Rules or guidelines that govern how an organization operates, specifically mentioned in the context of handling personal information.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CIRCUMSTANCES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The current state of an individual's financial and personal situation that can impact their ability to achieve financial goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LUMP SUM">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A single, large payment of money, often from sources like a tax refund or inheritance, which can be strategically applied to financial goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SAVINGS GOALS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Specific financial objectives focused on accumulating money over time, such as saving for a car or a TV.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WEEKLY SAVINGS GOAL">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific amount of money an individual aims to save each week towards a larger financial objective.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="NEW $600 TV">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A specific consumer good, in this context, representing a tangible item an individual is saving money to purchase.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MEDICAL BILLS">
  <data key="d0">RISK</data>
  <data key="d1">Statements of charges for medical services received, which, if unpaid, contribute to medical debt and can be subject to disputes with insurance providers.</data>
  <data key="d2">4</data>
</node>
<node id="MODULE 2: SAVING">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">The second module of the Your Money, Your Goals Toolkit, which provides information and guidance on how to save money effectively to achieve financial goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">5</data>
</node>
<node id="FEES/CHARGES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Additional costs or amounts added to a debt, which may include administrative fees or late payment charges.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DEBT COLLECTION LICENSE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">An official authorization issued by a state agency, required for a firm to legally engage in debt collection activities within that state.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RESOLVE ACCOUNT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of settling a debt account, potentially by paying a negotiated amount to fully satisfy the outstanding balance.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WRITTEN AGREEMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A formal document outlining the terms and conditions that created the original obligation to pay a debt.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TOTAL UP INCOME">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of summing all income received over a specific period.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PREDICTABLE PAYMENT">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A payment that arrives at a consistent time and in a consistent amount, making it reliable for financial planning.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="RELIABLE INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Income that can be consistently counted on each month due to its predictable nature.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ONLINE SPENDING RECORDS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Digital documentation of past expenditures, accessible through online platforms, used for tracking finances.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SPENDING TRACKING APP">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A software application designed to help users record, categorize, and monitor their financial outgoings.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SHELTER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An essential need representing housing or living accommodations as an expense category.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SORT SPENDING BY CATEGORY">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The activity of organizing expenditures into predefined groups for analysis.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SHARED BILLS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial obligations that are split or divided among multiple individuals.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TOTAL UP CATEGORIES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of summing the expenditures within each spending category.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MONTHLY BILLS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial obligations that are due and paid on a recurring monthly basis.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WEEKS WITH MOST MONEY DUE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Periods within a month when the cumulative total of financial obligations is highest, requiring careful cash flow management.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PLAN TO PAY BILLS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The strategic process of organizing finances to ensure timely payment of all outstanding bills.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BILL REMINDER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A feature or system that prompts an individual about upcoming bill due dates, often part of a bill calendar.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ONLINE BILL STATEMENTS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Digital versions of financial statements for bills, accessible through online accounts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CABLE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A financial concept representing expenses for cable television or internet services, listed as an example of a bill.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WEEKLY INCOME">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The amount of income earned by an individual on a weekly basis, used in calculations for wage garnishment limits.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="WEEKLY BILL TOTALS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">The sum of all financial obligations due within a specific week.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="BIRTHDAY EXPENSES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Costs associated with celebrating birthdays, such as gifts or parties.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="HOLIDAY EXPENSES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Costs associated with seasonal holidays, such as decorations, travel, or gifts.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SCHOOL EXPENSES">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Costs associated with education, such as tuition, books, or supplies for school.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="INFREQUENT BILLS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Financial obligations that are due less often than monthly, such as quarterly or annually.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="DAILY REMINDER">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_PRODUCT</data>
  <data key="d1">A feature or system that provides daily prompts or notifications, often for bill payments or tasks.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LABEL CALENDAR WITH DATES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of marking or writing specific dates onto a calendar for organizational purposes.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="LIST BILLS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of compiling a comprehensive record of all financial obligations.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MARK PAYMENT DATE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of noting or highlighting the intended payment date for a bill on a calendar or schedule.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="ENTER INCOME INTO CALENDAR">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of recording income receipt dates onto a calendar to facilitate financial planning.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="IDENTIFY VALUES">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of recognizing and defining personal priorities and what truly matters, guiding goal setting.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WORK TOWARDS FUTURE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of making efforts and progress towards desired long-term outcomes or goals.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="TRACK PROGRESS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of monitoring and evaluating advancement towards a goal over time.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="PICK STATEMENT">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of selecting a specific written declaration or option as a starting point for goal setting.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WRITE DOWN GOAL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The action of articulating and recording a personal objective in written form.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="SHARE GOAL">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of communicating a personal objective to another person for support or accountability.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REALISTIC TIMELINE">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">A practical and achievable schedule for reaching a goal, considering all necessary steps and resources.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="STICK TO ACTION PLAN">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The commitment to diligently follow a predefined strategy to achieve a goal.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="EVALUATING CARDS">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of assessing the fees and protections of a prepaid or payroll card.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="CARD PROTECTIONS">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">Measures and policies designed to safeguard cardholders from fraud, loss, theft, and errors, often detailed in the cardholder agreement.</data>
  <data key="d2">2</data>
</node>
<node id="WRITING RESPONSE">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of recording answers to questions about card fees and protections.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="MANAGING CARD COST">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of controlling or reducing the expenses associated with having and using a card.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="REGISTERING CARD">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The process of officially associating a card with the cardholder's identity to gain full protections.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="WITHDRAWING MONEY FROM ATM">
  <data key="d0">ACTION</data>
  <data key="d1">The act of taking cash out of an account using an Automated Teller Machine.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="IN-NETWORK ATM">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
  <data key="d1">An Automated Teller Machine that belongs to a card's designated network, typically offering lower or no withdrawal fees.</data>
  <data key="d2">1</data>
</node>
<node id="OUT-OF-NETWORK ATM">
  <data key="d0">FINANCIAL_CONCEPT</data>
